<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     05-10 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Hearing Into Highway Killings Postponed Because of Funding
Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special grand jury hearings on the
slayings of nine women whose bodies were found by highways have
been postponed indefinitely because of state funding cuts,
officials said Wednesday.
   The Bristol County grand jury, which has been meeting off and on
for at least two months, will not reconvene until investigators get
enough evidence and serve subpoenas, said Jim Martin, a spokesman
for District Attorney Ronald Pina.
   That could take a long time because state troopers are no longer
authorized to work overtime, Martin said. Most subpoenas have been
served at night and on weekends because witnesses, primarily street
people, are hard to find, he said.
   The female victims were found along or near three highways near
this city close to Rhode Island since July.
   Troopers have run up thousands of overtime hours trying to track
leads, and investigators have gotten some of their best clues at
night, Martin said.
   The end of overtime puts the investigation ``further and further
behind,'' he said. ``Every day that we lose, we can't get back.''
   Another Bristol County Superior Court Grand Jury on Wednesday
indicted Anthony R. DeGrazia on 13 rape and assault charges.
   DeGrazia was arraigned in district court last week after a
witness who appeared before the special grand jury said she had
identified his photo.
   Martin said the indictment had nothing to do with the killings,
and refused to comment on whether DeGrazia had been linked to the
investigation.
   The state Senate has enacted a $17.4 million deficiency budget,
but the Legislature did not approve $2.1 million in emergency
overtime pay for troopers through the end of the fiscal year June
30.
</TEXT>
