<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cannes     05-10 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannes,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entertainment Featured at 42nd Cannes Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 42nd Cannes Film Festival, which opens
Thursday, will bow to mainstream entertainment and glamour with a
selection of films by established directors and more international
stars than last year.
   The often long, austere films competing for last year's Golden
Palm, the festival's coveted award for best film, have been
replaced by what some might see as surer box-office draws.
   West German director Wim Wenders will preside over this year's
jury as it chooses among the 22 films from 14 countries in the
official competition.
   Setting the tone are two American movies opening and closing the
two-week festival: ``New York Stories,'' a trilogy by Francis Ford
Coppola, Martin Scorsese and Woody Allen, and ``Old Gringo,''
starring Jane Fonda and Gregory Peck.
   The rehabilitated version of David Lean's desert saga,
``Lawrence of Arabia,'' which includes segments left out of the
movie first seen 27 years ago, provides a special ``pre-opening''
to the festival Wednesday night.
   Festival Director Gilles Jacob said this year's selection is
``more a diversion than last year's'' and ``laughter is not
forbidden.''
   Indeed, the festival will open with a special hommage to Charlie
Chaplin, who would have been 100 years old this year.
   The United States is making a strong showing at this year's
festival. Two of its other films in the competition are ``Mystery
Train'' by Jim Jarmusch and Hugh Hundson's ``Lost Angels'' about
gangs of teenagers in Los Angeles.
   Italy, absent last year, has four movies competing, including
Ettore Scola's ``Splendor'' with Marcelo Mastroianni.
   Among the most discussed movies is Australian director Fred
Schepisi's ``A Cry in the Dark,'' the true story of a woman, played
by Meryl Streep, falsely accused of murdering her infant who was
snatched away by a wild dingo.
   Ms. Streep is among the stars scheduled to appear in Cannes,
along with Fonda, Peck, Mastroianni, Gerard Depardieu and Omar
Sharif.
   Depardieu stars in Bertrand Blier's ``Trop Belle Pour Toi'' (Too
Beautiful for You), one of three French entries, a story of a
garage mechanic, played by Depardieu, who finds his wife too
beautiful and falls in love with another woman.
   Also in the competition are several directors showing their
first films, including the American Steven Soderbergh with ``Sex,
Lies and Videotapes,'' Swede Carl Gustav Nykvist's ``Kvinnorna Pa
Taket'' (Women on the Roof) and Australian Jane Campion's
``Sweetie.''
   East bloc countries are notably absent from this year's
competition with the exception of Yugoslavia, represented by Emir
Kusturica's ``Domza Vesanje'' (The Time of the Gypsies).
   Japan is present with ``Kuroi Ame'' (Black Rain), directed by
Shohei Imamura, a one-time winner of the Golden Palm for his
``Ballad of Narayama.''
   While just 22 movies are competing for the Golden Palm, more
than 1,500 will be shown before the festival closes on May 23.
   Last year's festival gave the Golden Palm to ``Pelle the
Conqueror,'' a film by Danish director Bille August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
