<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SematechStudy     05-10 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sematech Study,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Consortium Not Sole Key To US Semiconductor Competitiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government study suggests a host of tax,
trade and antitrust issues will dictate the global competitiveness
of the U.S. semiconductor industry regardless of a Texas research
consortium's success in chip manufacturing research.
   The Commerce Department study said Sematech's performance is no
guarantee the United States will capture the competitive edge in
the semiconductor industry.
   Sematech, a jointly funded partnership between the Pentagon and
14 semiconductor manufacturers, was created last year in an effort
to help the U.S. achieve global leadership in such technology by
1993.
   The Austin, Texas, consortium was launched because of fears a
decline in the U.S. semiconductor industry may undermine the
competitive and technological leadership of U.S. computer and
communications equipment makers. A growing U.S. dependence on
foreign sources for state-of-the-art weapons components also is a
concern, the report said.
   The study, a report by the Advisory Council on Federal
Participation in Sematech, recommends the Pentagon spend $100
million on Sematech in fiscal 1990, to be matched by the member
corporations. Withdrawal of federal support now ``would seriously
limit Sematech's operations and prospects for success,'' it said.
   But the recently released study cautioned that even if Sematech
``were a complete success in its own terms, major issues now
affecting the competitiveness of U.S. chipmakers would remain _
limited marketing opportunities and a range of tax, antitrust and
trade policy issues.''
   The U.S. would still trail the Japanese and Europeans in
developing technology needed for competitive leadership in
semiconductors in the late 1990s, particularly in the area of X-ray
lithography, the report said.
   ``If the public investment in Sematech is not followed by an
increase in the competitive strength of U.S. chipmakers and their
suppliers, Sematech as a public policy will not have been
successful,'' the study said.
   Even as Sematech was gaining momentum in 1988, U.S.
semiconducter manufacturers continued to lose ground commercially
as their share of world market sales fell to 37 percent, three
percentage points below the 1987 level, the study said.
   Efforts by other countries to create alliances of business,
government and academia ``have the potential to weaken the United
States economically and militarily. ... Observers have suggested
that the Sematech model _ federally sponsored pre-competitive
industry cooperation _ may be one answer to this problem,'' the
report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
