<FIRST>r a PM-NiemanFellows     05-10 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nieman Fellows,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nieman Fellows For 1989-90 Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nieman Foundation has announced the
U.S. winners of next year's Nieman fellows at Harvard University.
   The program was founded in 1938 to improve the standards of
journalism.
   These journalists were selected Tuesday for Harvard's 1989-90
school year:
   J. Brett Alexander, 40, producer for CBS News-48 Hours, New
York; Daniel Biddle, 35, reporter, The Philadelphia Inquirer; Dave
Denison, 30, editor, The Texas Observer; John Harwood, 32,
political editor based in Washington, D.C., the St. Petersburg
Times; Mary Jordan, 28, staff writer, The Washington Post; Ann
Marie Lipinski, 33, reporter, Chicago Tribune.
   Thomas Morgan III, 37, reporter, The New York Times; Dick
Reavis, 43, senior editor, Texas Monthly; Carla Robbins, 35, Latin
America bureau chief, U.S. News &amp; World Report; George Rodrigue,
33, day city editor, The Dallas Morning News; Dianna Solis, 32,
Houston-based reporter, The Wall Street Journal; Juan Tamayo, 40,
Jerusalem-based Middle East correspondent, The Miami Herald.
   The Nieman fellowships were established from a bequest to
Harvard from Agnes Wahl Nieman to honor the memory of her husband,
Lucius Nieman, founder of The Milwaukee Journal.
   Foreign journalists who have won Nieman fellowships for 1989-90
will be announced later this month.
</TEXT>
