<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-ShamirPlan Bjt   05-10 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shamir Plan, Bjt,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Election Plan Seems Headed For Dustbin</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's proposal for
elections in the occupied lands is edging toward the dustbin of
Middle East peace plans, opposed both by members of his
conservative Likud bloc and by the Palestinians.
   Ariel Sharon, who heads Likud's far-right faction, was reported
Tuesday to be planning a challenge within the party in hopes of
sinking the plan. He called it Israel's ``biggest ever national
blunder.''
   Shamir, in an interview Tuesday, appeared to dash any hopes held
by moderate Palestinians that elections might be a first step to
their dream of an independent state.
   He told The Jerusalem Post he wanted those moderates to reject
the idea of an independent nation even before the election.
   He said his proposal for limited autonomy, with Palestinians
running their own affairs while Israel maintains control of
security, was the best he could offer.
   His plan calls for elected Palestinians from the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip to negotiate an interim peace with Israel to be
followed by talks on the final status of the territories.
   The approach has been rejected by the Palestine Liberation
Organization and a group of influential leaders in the occupied
lands but Shamir has said he does not see the rejection as final.
   In Tuesday's interview, Shamir said he believed elections could
still go forward. One government official said Israel hopes
Secretary of State James A. Baker III can convince the Soviet Union
during his visit to Moscow this week to join Washington in trying
to persuade the PLO to accept the plan.
   Shamir's statement on prior rejection by Palestinians of an
independent state may have been aimed at deflecting right-wing
criticism. But Palestinian leaders said they knew of no politician
in the occupied lands willing to run with that condition.
   ``I can't imagine any Palestinian who would take part in any
political activity in which he has to veto a Palestinian state,''
said Daoud Kuttab, a prominent Palestinian journalist.
   Even Mayor Elias Freij of Bethlehem, who in the past favored
elections and was threatened by the PLO for his stand, criticized
Shamir's latest suggestion.
   ``Shamir's statement that Palestinians must turn down a state
makes the elections meaningless, void of any content,'' Freij told
The Associated Press.
   Shamir, in the interview, said elections could come about if
Israel could convince Palestinians that hopes for a state were
``illusions,'' and their 17-month uprising in the occupied
territories can be broken by Israel.
   Kuttab, however, said the Palestinians would not end the
uprising _ in which 466 Palestinians and 21 Israelis have been
killed _ without some gains for their losses.
   ``Palestinians are willing to stop the intefadeh,'' he said,
using the Arabic word for uprising, ``but for what? Stop the
intefadeh and go back to where we were in December 1987, no way.''
   Kuttab told the AP that Palestinians want a signal from Shamir
that Israel is ready to compromise and give up at least part of the
West Bank and Gaza in exchange for peace _ the formula favored by
the United States.
   ``We want him (Shamir) to recognize that we are occupied, that
this land is not forever Israel, that it's up for negotiations,''
he said.
   A government official, who briefed reporters on the election
plan, said Israel's coalition government was too divided to make
any formal declaration on the final status of the territories,
which Israel seized in 1967.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, leaders of the center-left Labor Party that shares power
with Shamir's Likud, favor trading territory for peace, though not
the creation of a Palestinian state.
   Shamir and his Likud protege, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens,
oppose giving up any land.
   But Shamir's biggest problem may be with his own colleagues and
not with the Labor Party.
   Industry Minister Sharon, who has failed in past challenges for
Likud's leadership, has repeatedly denounced Shamir's plan.
   In an interview on army radio Tuesday, Sharon called the
elections proposal ``a calamity for Israel, representing the
biggest ever national blunder that will lead to the creation of a
Palestinian state.''
   Israel radio reported that Sharon planned to try to kill the
plan by taking it before Likud's Central Committee, which he heads.
   The Jerusalem Post quoted a leading Likud member, Planning
Minister Yitzhak Modai, as saying the plan as it now stands ``will
be rejected out of hand'' by the committee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   G. G. LaBelle is AP news editor in Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Noriega Bjt   05-10 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Noriega, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Welcomes Evidence that Panamanians Finally Rebuffing Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After long periods in which the only
significant opposition to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega seemed to
come from the U.S. government, American officials are encouraged by
the throngs of anti-Noriega demonstrators in Panama the past few
days.
   When Noriega dumped independent-minded Panamanian presidents in
1985 and 1988, the streets of Panama City were quiet. Nary a voice
was raised in protest even though both presidents could claim at
least a modicum of democratic legitimacy.
   There was concern here that an attempt by Noriega to steal last
Sunday's election would be greeted with apathy once again by a
people who often do not expect much from their political leaders.
   But the streets of Panama City have been alive with protest over
the past few days, suggesting that Noriega could be weaker now than
he has been at any time since becoming Defense Forces commander
almost six years ago.
   The Bush administration strategy has been clear. Early on,
officials saw the election as a major opportunity for political
change even though there was little reason to believe that Noriega
would tolerate an honest process.
   The administration reasoned that the Panamanian opposition
needed a catalyst around which it could rally, and the election
provided it. U.S. officials had predicted that Noriega would
respond in one of two ways to evidence of broad-based opposition:
He would either cancel the elections or try to rig the outcome.
   Either way he would be weakened politically, a high-priority
U.S. objective. Noriega decided to go ahead with the election,
thinking all along he would be able to manipulate the results, a
time-honored practice in Panama, according to many who claim to
have seen it firsthand.
   If there were protests, Noriega believed he could ride them out.
After all, he may have felt, with some reason, invulnerable to
pressure. He was able to survive street protests two years ago
after a one-time ally turned against him. He was also emboldened by
his ability to withstand U.S. economic and political pressures. In
addition, Noriega was able to reduce to irrelevance Panamanian
leaders who dared challenge his authority.
   In 1985, President Nicolas Ardito Barletta was ousted with
lightning swiftness after calling for an investigation into the
death of a Noriega critic who witnesses said was killed by
Noriega's agents.
   Fourteen months ago, after President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried
to fire Noriega, it took Noriega's allies in the National Assembly
precisely 10 minutes to remove Delvalle from office.
   Noriega also was able to shrug off U.S. criminal indictments
stemming from his alleged involvement in drug smuggling. An attempt
by dissident officers to oust Noriega a year ago was put down
within hours.
   But now Noriega appears on the defensive, the election seeming
to demonstrate that his base of support is perilously thin. The
Bush administration is now attempting to devise a strategy that
will push him over the edge and thus restore a degree of normality
to the U.S.-Panamanian relationship for the first time in years.
   When the election campaign began several months ago, prospects
for Noreiga's opponents seemed dim but not hopeless. They felt
reassured by the expressions of support and encouragement from
delegations of human rights activists from the United States and
elsewhere interested in a democratic outcome in Panama.
   The opposition also may have been given a shot in the arm from
the $10 million it received, according to reports, in clandestine
aid from the U.S. government. It also has been galvanized by the
steep economic decline Panama has suffered under Noriega's rule.
   Now the administration is groping for new ways to make Noriega
wonder whether he would be better off elsewhere. The Reagan
administration thought for sure Noriega was on his way out well
over a year ago and it miscalculated badly. The Bush administration
is hoping that it is Noriega who has miscalculated this time.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
