<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Austria-Neo-Nazis     05-10 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Austria-Neo-Nazis,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Jailed for Destroying Anti-Nazi Monument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men were sentenced to prison terms
of up to three years for firebombing an anti-Fascist memorial in
the southern city of Graz.
   The memorial, by German-American sculptor Hans Haacke, was part
of an exhibit and arts festival devoted to the country's past
half-century.
   Austria had been incorporated into Adolf Hitler's Third Reich
and Graz was a Nazi stronghold in 1938.
   The monument, a wooden obelisk commemorating Jews, gypsies and
others killed by the Nazis, was firebombed on Nov. 2 and severely
damaged.
   On Tuesday, a Graz court sentenced Peter Lukas, 37, to three
years in jail for carrying out the attack. Hubert Steinbrugger, 68,
was sentenced to 18 months and Arne Mayer, 24, to one year, both as
accomplices.
   The men also were found guilty of Nazi-like activity and fined
$77,000, the cost of the damage to the monument.
   Steinbrugger was sentenced in 1954 to a 15-month jail term for
neo-Nazi activity, according to the Austria Press Agency.
</TEXT>
