<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Panama-Democracy     05-10 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Democracy,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Through 85 Years Of Independence, Democracy Has Had a Rough Ride
in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt ^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The electoral fraud that shocked
former President Jimmy Carter was hardly a surprise in a nation
where voting has seldom determined who holds power.
   Panama was a province of Colombia in 1903, when the United
States helped Gen. Esteban Huertas mount a successful revolt
because President Theodore Roosevelt wanted to build a canal.
   Panama declared its independence on Nov. 3 that year.
   ``I took the Isthmus,'' crowed Roosevelt as the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers went to work to cut a path through the narrow waist
between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
   Democracy has had a rough ride ever since.
   By 1940, the country had had 21 leaders in 37 years, including
four in 1918. And in the last 21 years, Panamanians have rarely
been able to vote for a president.
   In 1940, voters elected Arnulfo Arias Madrid, one of Panama's
most influential politicians to the day he died in 1988.
   Arias Madrid was elected to the presidency three times. He is
thought to have been cheated of victory by fraud in 1984, one year
after Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega took control of the nation.
   Despite his success, Arias Madrid only managed to govern the
country for 2{ years in all; he was toppled by coups three times.
In 1968, he served just 11 days before he was overthrown.
   Even Arias Madrid was not a model democrat. He was an admirer of
European fascism, and some admirers still refer to him as
``caudillo,'' the title taken by dictator Francisco Franco of Spain.
   In 1972, after four years of junta rule, a president was
elected, but the new constitution gave complete control to Gen.
Omar Torrijos, a charismatic populist who made no bones about his
dominance.
   He, not the president, signed the treaties by which the United
States turns over the Panama Canal at the end of the century.
   Torrijos died in a plane crash in 1981. In 1983, Noriega, his
intelligence chief, came to power.
   When another election was permitted in 1984, Arias Madrid looked
like a winner until the count was halted. After 10 days, Nicolas
Ardito Barletta was proclaimed victor.
   Noriega has since imposed and deposed presidents at will.
   Last year, President Eric Delvalle tried to fire Noriega after
the general was indicted on drug-trafficking and money-laundering
charges in Florida. Noriega, who has denied the charges, forced out
Delvalle.
   Manuel Solis Palma was named ``Minister in Charge of the
Presidency.'' He is scheduled to turn power over to the new
president on Sept. 1.
   The U.S. government imposed economic sanctions against Panama in
an attempt to oust Noriega but Noriega has toughed it out.
   Sunday's vote provided little solace for democracy-minded
Panamanians.
   Witnesses said Noriega's troops moved in to seize vote-tally
sheets when it looked like his candidate, Carlos Duque, was losing
to Arias Madrid follower Guillermo Endara.
   According to Carter, who acted as an international election
observer, Noriega had believed that Duque would win fairly but
decided on a steal when things began to look bad.
   The core of Duque's support came from the poor and from
descendants of black Caribbean immigrants, many brought in to work
on the canal.
   The rebellion against Noriega has been led by the middle class.
However, that group has a lot to lose and does not have a
reputation for being willing to fight for democracy.
   ``The people will not go into the streets _ not because we are
cowards but because we are not stupid. Why get shot and killed?''
asked human rights activist Otilia Koster.
   ``It will not be like the Philippines,'' she said, referring to
the military-civlian revolt that brought millions into the streets
to topple Ferdinand Marcos in 1986.
   Retiree Carlos Halphen said he didn't know what the opposition
could do. Like many Panamanians since the days of Roosevelt, he was
looking to the north.
   ``We want the United States to do something. The U.S. got us
into this, it should get us out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-FiresAtSea     05-10 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires At Sea,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Ship Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fire On a Ship _ A Nightmare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire on a ship, an enclosed space made
primarily of heat-conducting metal, can turn into a nightmare for
seamen trying to extinguish the blaze, experts say.
   The latest example came when fire broke out on the USS White
Plains, killing six people and injuring five. The blaze on the Navy
supply ship in the South China Sea was apparently caused by a fuel
leak, officials said Tuesday.
   Guy Colonna, a marine specialist with the National Fire
Protection Association, a Quincy, Mass., organization that works to
develop fire protection standards, said a major problem confronting
firefighters aboard a ship is restrictions on the use of water.
   ``The way to fight fire is with water _ obviously at sea you
can't add too much or you sink the vessel or impair its
stability,'' he said. ``You can't pour water on it the way you
would on land.''
   Maj. Dave Neudorfer, who works in the Navy's safety and
survivability division, said water used to dampen a blaze has to be
pumped off the ship to keep the vessel afloat.
   Another hazard is intense heat that builds up on a ship, with
temperatures often reaching 3,000 degrees Farhenheit. ``Metal
conducts heat rapidly ... and an all-metal facility is not like a
building where you have cement walls,'' Colonna said.
   A Navy source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the heat
on the White Plains was so hot sailors were limited to five-minute
stints in fighting the blaze.
   Additionally, ships are compartmentalized, frequently making it
difficult to move equipment from deck to deck, Colonna said. An
explosion that ripped through the No. 2 gun turret of the USS Iowa
last month was contained to that area. Forty-seven men were killed.
   Colonna, who was formerly in the Coast Guard, said the Navy
trains all sailors in fire-fighting techniques, but special
casualty control teams spring into action when fire breaks out.
   Even so, Neudorfer said on-the-ground training is a
``kindergarten situation'' compared to a ship-board fire, which
often produces billowing smoke and toxic fumes from material used
to coat electrical cables and insulate equipment.
   Repair lockers containing hoses and breathing equipment are
normally kept at each end of the ship, Colonna said. In a large
ship like an aircraft carrier, equipment bins are located at
various places.
   But fire affects everyone one board because it can disable a
ship's navigation and steering equipment and electricity, he said.
``When they have a fire, it's almost like a military operation,''
he said. ``It's a nightmare; things are going on and people have
their jobs to do.''
   The Navy, meantime, is continually trying to upgrade its ability
to cope with fires, particularly using new technologies, Neudorfer
said.
   ``We're challenging the technical world to come up with fire
resistant coating on electrical cables,'' he said.
   Moreover, the Navy is looking at so-called ``sticky water'' that
does not evaporate when it is doused on a fire.
   On a practical level, the Navy recently introduced special
fire-fighting coveralls for sailors, and is looking at
manufacturing taller boots.
   What they found on the USS Stark was that ``water was coming
over the boots and burning their feet,'' Neudorfer said.
   Thirty-seven sailors were killed when the Stark was hit by a
Iraqi missile in the Persian Gulf in May, 1987. Crew members
battled for 24 hours to bring under control the fires set off by
the attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-WhitePlains-History     05-10 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-White Plains-History,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>White Plains is Aging `Floating Grocery Store' for 7th Fleet Ships</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Ship Fire Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS White Plains is an aging but essential
support ship that serves as a floating grocery store for vessels
assigned to the Navy's 7th Fleet.
   The 581-foot food stores ship has been based at the Pacific
island of Guam since 1984 and was returning there Tuesday after a
deployment to the northern Arabian Sea in support of Persian Gulf
operations. It was attached to the aircraft carrier Constellation
and its battle group during the deployment.
   According to Navy records, the White Plains is more than 20
years old but there is no history of any past serious problems
aboard the vessel involving accidents or its machinery.
   The vessel, the fourth in the so-called Mars class of food
supply ships, carries the Navy designation AFS-4 and was
constructed by the National Steel &amp; Shipbuilding Co. of San Diego,
Calif. The ship's keel was laid down on Oct. 2, 1965; it was
launched on July 26, 1966, and then commissioned into active
service on Nov. 23, 1968.
   It has since undergone several major overhauls.
   The ship has spent its entire life plying the waters of the
Pacific and Indian Oceans, at various points calling San Francisco
and the Japanese ports of Sasebo and Yokosuka home in addition to
Guam.
   The White Plains joined the fleet in time for numerous and
lengthy deployments during the Vietnam War and earned seven battle
stars for its performance. Even after American troops were
withdrawn from Vietnam, the White Plains drew additional duty in
the South China Sea supporting warships that had been ordered to
retrieve underwater mines sown in North Vietnamese waters.
   The ship has participated in training exercises with a number of
foreign navies, includes those of South Korea and Australia, and
also served as a ``mercy ship'' following natural catastrophes.
   For example, it carried relief supplies to Guam and other
islands in the Mariana chain in 1976 after Typhoon Pamela. Later
that same year the ship drew another special mission, ordered
without notice to the Indian Ocean to support a carrier task force
monitoring a flare-up in hostilities between Kenya and Uganda.
</TEXT>
