<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Pardon     05-10 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Pardon,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: North Pardon is Touchy Issue for Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush White House is treading carefully
over the issue of a pardon for Oliver North, whom the president has
several times called a hero. It's clearly a touchy subject.
   On Tuesday, Bush declared he had ``wanted all along to see him
exonerated,'' but declined to comment further on last week's guilty
verdicts. He brushed aside a question on whether he was considering
a pardon for North.
   At the White House, officials apparently don't like the word
``consider'' when it comes to talking about a pardon for the
retired Marine lieutenant colonel.
   ``We don't have any comment on the North trial or the
conclusion,'' presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater told
reporters after the former White House aide was convicted of three
felony counts in the Iran-Contra affair. ``And we haven't discussed
a pardon.''
   Asked what that meant, Fitzwater said: ``There has been no
discussion of a pardon whatsoever.''
   A reporter then asked Fitzwater point blank: ``Could you put it
direct and just say the president's not considering a pardon for
Mr. North?''
   ``The president has not discussed a pardon,'' he said.
   ``Well, what does that mean?''
   Fitzwater: ``It means he hasn't discussed it.''
   ``Is he considering it or will he consider it?''
   Fitzwater: ``He hasn't discussed it.''
   ``Who is he supposed to discuss it with?''
   Fitzwater: ``Anybody.''
   A day later, Fitzwater was again asked, ``Any change about the
consideration or lack of consideration of a pardon for Ollie
North?''
   ``Not discussing it,'' Fitzwater said.
   The president wasn't much in the mood for discussing it, either,
on Tuesday when he was asked by a reporter whether he believed
North to be innocent.
   ``I'm not going to argue with the courts,'' Bush said. ``The
process is being appealed. He's entitled to the right of appeal
without a lot of editorial comment from me, although I've already
given you some.''
   When he was asked if he believed in shredding documents _ one of
the counts on which North was convicted _ Bush joked, ``I believe
in taking them with me.''
   Late last month, the president told reporters aboard Air Force
One that he wouldn't even think about a pardon until the legal
proceedings were over _ and that he hadn't discussed it with
anyone, even his wife.
   The issue of a pardon for North is a stick of political dynamite
for the president, who over the past several years repeatedly has
had to deny his own role in the covert dealings that were at the
heart of the case against North.
   Bush has denied any advance knowledge of the Reagan
administration's efforts to sell arms to Iran and to divert the
profits to the Nicaraguan contra rebels.
   And just last week he insisted that a trip he made to Honduras
in 1985 _ a trip disclosed by a document released in the North
trial _ was not part of a scheme to exchange increased aid to
Honduras for help with the Contras.
   Still, despite these denials, the subject of Bush's involvement
or lack of involvement continues to linger.
   Some Democratic critics have said they find it difficult to
believe that Bush, a former CIA chief who claimed he was in on most
major Reagan administration decisions as vice president, could have
been as in the dark as he claims.
   Bush is no doubt mindful of the political backlash that
developed when then President Ford pardoned former President Nixon
in 1974. That action proved extremely unpopular among Americans.
   But at the same time, North is highly regarded among
conservatives, many of whom view him as a patriot _ one who was
just following orders.
   Bush probably isn't discussing the decision with others at the
White House, says Stephen Hess, a scholar who specializes in the
presidency at the Brookings Institution.
   ``George Bush seems to have a habit of making these big ones all
by himself, and they sometimes turn out to be surprises _ like his
choice of (Dan) Quayle (as his running mate).''
   ``I'm not sure what he'll do, but I'm sure that whatever it is,
it will come from his gut,'' said Hess. And, the analyst added,
Bush's decision on North will likely be based on inside information.
   ``He knows something that the rest of us don't know: to what
degree Oliver North was an unguided missile,'' Hess said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
