<DOCNO> AP890510-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Soviet-Trade     05-10 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Soviet-Trade,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Eye Soviet Far East, Siberia</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Chinese economists is backing a
radical proposal to use Chinese labor and Japanese capital to
develop the Soviet Far East, the world's largest untapped
depository of natural resources.
   The Ministry of Agriculture, meanwhile, is considering a
``massive cooperation program'' with the Soviet Union to grow crops
and process food in China's northeast.
   The proposals represent a new vision of Soviet-Chinese economic
relations, which now consist mainly of exchanging low-quality
Russian wood and iron ore for Chinese thermoses and canned foods.
   Both plans were formulated earlier this year as China and Soviet
officials haggled over the countries' first summit in 30 years.
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will come to China on May 15,
accompanied by trade representatives ready to discuss economic
relations.
   The proposals stem from a realization that the current barter
and border trade has its limits.
   Ten years ago there was little trade between the countries. Last
year, they signed contracts for about $3.25 billion in goods, but
because of transportation bottlenecks 25 percent of the Soviet
goods and 40 percent of the Chinese products were not delivered.
   Thousands of tons of goods also were returned because they were
shoddy.
   ``There's lots of hoopla about record-setting trade figures and
contracts but there's little future in that,'' said Fan Yueqiang,
head of the Institute of Development Studies, a think tank in
Beijing.
   ``We only sell each other things we can't sell for foreign
exchange,'' he said. ``They send us low-quality wood and we send
them second-class canned food.''
   Fan and his deputy, Han Xiaofeng, believe the future of
Chinese-Soviet trade is in combining Soviet technical skill and
natural resources with Chinese labor and capital from third
countries, such as Japan and South Korea.
   Labor export began last year when more than 100 Chinese
construction workers went to Zabaikalsk, a Soviet town that borders
China's Inner Mongolia. There they built a gymnasium, dormitories
and a dining hall. Earlier in the year, 77 peasants were given
1,000 acres to grow cucumbers and watermelons in the Soviet Union
north of Vladivostok on the coast of the Sea of Japan.
   ``We've found that if you put a tie around the neck of a Chinese
peasant and send him over the border, he turns into an agricultural
expert,'' Han said.
   Both projects were successful. This year, the official Xinhua
News Agency reported, more than 10,000 Chinese laborers will work
in the Soviet Union on a variety of projects involving agriculture,
forestry, fisheries and mining.
   The proposal for the Soviet Far East has its roots in a series
of plans stretching back decades to tap East Asia's vast economic
wealth.
   Senior Chinese government officials have quietly expressed
backing for the plan, and the Soviet Embassy in Beijing has met
with its proponents. Japan would provide the capital, and
newspapers in that nation have been abuzz with reports.
   Fan and Han have a personal interest in the project.
   During the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution, they spent about
eight years planting rice in the mosquito-infested fields of
Longwangmiao, in a far-eastern corner of Heilongjiang Province
along the Soviet border.
   Like many Chinese from the cities, they were sent to the
countryside to farm and cleanse their minds of urban ways.
   ``I lost my youth in that province,'' said Fan, now in his
mid-40s. ``But I also got to know it. I understand clearly the
possibilities for economic ties with the Soviets.''
   The first step, Fan said, is for China and the Soviet Union to
carry out joint ventures.
   In the 1950s, when relations between the countries were close,
Soviet advisers worked on hundreds of projects around China as part
of Moscow's support for the Communist bloc.
   ``We don't want to see a return to those days of big brother's
help,'' Fan said. ``What we want now is business partners.''
   The countries are already discussing the possible sale of a
nuclear power plant to China. And officials in China's remote
Xinjiang province want Soviet help in mining, and drilling for oil
and gas.
   Next, the investment power of Japan and South Korea must be
brought into play.
   ``For years Japanese businessmen have been wanting to get a
piece of Siberia,'' Fan said. ``But one of the main problems was
labor. Chinese labor is cheap and our workers are hardy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
