<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Jackson     05-10 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Jackson,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Jackson Would Defeat Barry if DC Mayor's Race Held Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson could easily defeat District of
Columbia Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr. if an election were held today
between the mayor and the civil rights leader, a new poll says.
   According to the poll in today's Washington Post, Jackson would
win 68 percent of the vote to 17 percent for Barry. The poll also
found that Barry would lose to Police Chief Maurice A. Turner Jr.,
60 percent to 24 percent, and to three other possible challengers.
   Barry has been facing declining support because of questionable
behavior and mounting city problems.
   Despite Jackson's strong support, nearly half of those polled
said the former presidential candidate should stay out of the
mayoral race, while 40 percent approved of his running. Jackson
recently said he would consider moving from Chicago to Washington,
where he owns a house, and making a bid for mayor if Barry decided
not to run.
   Jackson would be required to establish residence in the district
for one year before the November 1990 election to be allowed to run.
   Barry for years was considered politically untouchable despite a
series of political missteps and the legal woes of many close
friends and associates.
   However, his popularity has been slipping since his visit to the
hotel room of a suspected drug dealer, Charles Lewis, in December,
which sparked an investigation into the city's controversial
involvement in a personnel project involving the Virgin Islands
government.
   Lewis was convicted of cocaine trafficking charges in the Virgin
Islands last month and has been indicted in Washington on 16 counts
of conspiracy, drug trafficking and perjury.
   If Barry chooses to run again, he would enter the race less
popular than any of his potential rivals, according to a Post
telephone survey of 1,021 registered voters conducted between April
28 and May 7. Six out of 10 disapprove of Barry's performance as
mayor.
   Barry dismissed the poll results, saying, ``It's clear to me
that the Washington Post wants me out of office and this poll fits
its plan.''
   Barry and all of his potential rivals are Democrats, although
Turner has indicated that if he chooses to run, he may run as an
independent or Republican.
   The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus three percentage
points.
</TEXT>
