<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-10 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Fall in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange erased
their morning gains and closed lower Wednesday, while the U.S.
dollar also fell back against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 103.37-point loser
Tuesday, dropped 38.54 more points, or 0.11 percent, to finish
trading at 33,993.33, despite a 75.12-point gain in the morning
session.
   The dollar ended at 134.44 yen, down 0.56 yen from Tuesday's
135.00 yen finish. The currency started trading at 134.42 yen and
ranged between 134.15-134.53 yen.
   ``After opening lower, the dollar-yen rate was hardly moving in
Tokyo,'' said an analyst with a commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Uncertainties over a possible interest rate hike by the Bank of
Japan have also made market players reluctant to make major moves
recently, he added.
   Media reports have mentioned the possibility of a hike in the
central bank's official interest rate from 2.5 percent to 3.0
percent, but the Bank of Japan has made no official announcements
so far.
   The analyst said the market was also waiting to see the U.S.
producer price index figure, scheduled to come out later this week.
   A Bank of Tokyo trader said the market started with ``a
dollar-selling mood'' in Tokyo, following a similar downtrend in
New York overnight, finishing at 134.53 yen.
   The dollar's slip followed a remark by a U.S. government
official expressing concern over the currency's further rise, said
the trader who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Charles Dallara, the U.S. Treasury's assistant
secretary-designate for international affairs, told a Senate panel
Tuesday the U.S. government continues to stand by an accord on the
dollar reached by the seven major industrialized countries known as
the Group of Seven.
   That accord, reached in Washington in April, called further
rises in the dollar ``counterproductive.''
   On the stock market, a Nomura Securities' analyst said trading
was directionless, while participants were still concerned with the
yen's performance against the dollar.
   ``Investors didn't have a specific incentive to purchase, so
they just made adjustments by buying issues when prices fell and
selling as they rose,'' he said.
</TEXT>
