<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LadleDeaths     05-10 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ladle Deaths,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dad Charged With Killing Sons in Foundry Believed End of World Was
Near, Psychiatrist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with killing his two sons
in a 1,300-degree foundry ladle believed he was ``doing his
children a favor'' because the end of the world was near, a
psychologist testified.
   Dr. Harley Stock, deputy director of the state's Center for
Forensic Psychiatry, testified Tuesday that Bartley Dobben was
insane when he killed his children on Thanksgiving Day 1987.
   ``In terms of society's rules, he knew it was wrong,'' Stock
said. ``But he was operating under the rules of God ... God had
dictated through the Bible'' that he kill the children.
   About a week and a half before the slayings at the
Cannon-Muskegon Corp. foundry where Dobben worked, one of the
children told his mother that Dobben tried to drown him and his
brother in their bathtub, Stock said in an interview Tuesday.
   However, Dobben told Stock he was baptizing his sons, aged 2
years and 15 months, because he believed the end of the world was
near, Stock said.
   ``Religion was on his mind all the time,'' Stock said, adding
that he agreed with a 1985 diagnosis that found Dobben to be
suffering from paranoid schizophrenia. ``The flames of his mental
illness were fanned by his religion.
   ``He believed he was doing his children a favor by killing
them,'' Stock testified. ``He told us he decided the children had
to die by his hands because they were going to die anyway.''
   Dobben believed his children would come back to life because
they were pure, Stock testified.
   After putting the children in the ladle used to hold molten
metal, Dobben ``played with them, made them comfortable, put the
lid on, lit it and felt all right about it,'' Stock said. The boys
quickly perished in the furnace.
   Dobben took what he read in the Bible literally and when he read
about the end of the world, he believed ``it was going to happen
now and he was going to take action,'' Stock said.
   Dobben's family testified his mental illness seemed to worsen
after Dobben met Rood Vaughan, a self-ordained fundamentalist
minister.
   The prosecution was to call a witness Thursday to show Dobben
was sane at the time of the slayings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
