<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-10 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index declined
today, and the dollar fell from an eight-month high against the yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 39.52
points, or 0.12 percent, following a 103.37-point decline on
Tuesday, and closed at 33,992.35.
   Dealers said the index declined as foreign investors sold
shares. Also, they said, others held back from buying after remarks
by Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita seen as indicating possible
interest rate increases, which usually discourage stock buying.
   Sumita told an upper house Budget Committee session today that
the central bank will ``take necessary measures whenever
necessary'' on interest rates to deter inflationary pressure.
   Market participants believe the Bank of Japan is likely to raise
its key rate by at least 0.5 percentage points in late May to ease
upward pressure on prices.
   Kazuhiro Nomura of New Japan Securities Co. said the stock
market showed little positive reaction to the yen's recovery
against the dollar today.
   The dollar closed at 134.44 yen, down 0.56 yen from Tuesday's
close. It opened at 134.42 yen and ranged between 134.15 yen and
134.53 yen.
   The dollar's 135.00 yen closing Tuesday was its highest since
135.60 yen last Sept. 6.
   ``Although the yen recovered from yesterday's 135-yen level,
stock players took it as rather neutral, and it didn't encourage
them much,'' Nomura said.
   He said foreign investors selling spot issues to buy cheaper
futures issues also contributed to the Nikkei's fall.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 900
million shares, down from Tuesday's 1 billion.
   Masafumi Koyama of the Bank of Tokyo said today's currency
trading was mixed, with traders buying and selling dollars.
   ``But that doesn't mean the dollar's recent uptrend was totally
reversed,'' he said.
   He said a large demand for the dollar remains, ``considering
that Japanese investors have been buying the dollar without
specific economic reasons.''
</TEXT>
