<FIRST>r i PM-SolidarityTV     05-10 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solidarity TV,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Airs Its First Television Broadcast</HEAD>
<UNK>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With potent symbols, familiar faces and
even a lesson on how to vote, Solidarity's first 45-minute show was
broadcast on government television under an accord giving it
limited access to the mass media.
   At 10:45 p.m. Tuesday, the words ``Studio Solidarnosc'' popped
up on the screen followed by the red-and-white national flag and
then another Solidarity sign with the well-known union logo.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa joked, ``I don't know what I came
here for,'' as he walked into the studio filled with union banners.
   ``Because this is the first historic entrance of Solidarity.
It's not that they (the state-run TV) only speak about Solidarity,
it's simply for the first time that we are given a chance to
speak,'' answered the host.
   Walesa immediately launched into an appeal for support of
partially free elections June 4 to the Sejm, or lower house, and
the Senate.
   ``We have been waiting for very long for the moment when Poles _
in a limited way _ will be able to speak about the country's
problems, to take part in deciding about the fate of this
country,'' he said.
   Round-table agreements reached April 5 reinstated Solidarity
after a seven-year ban and allowed the opposition to run for 161
seats of the 460-member Sejm and for the new 100-member Senate.
   The agreements also guarantee the opposition access to mass
media.
   The Solidarity television program will be broadcast once a week
for 45 minutes on Tuesday nights at either 10 or 10:45 p.m.
   Also, as of today, Solidarity will have a portion of half-hour
official ``election studio'' broadcasts every evening until the
vote. Regional nightly news programs will also have short section
of Solidarity information.
   A half-hour weekly show on government-controlled radio had its
first broadcast on April 28, and the opposition published the first
issue of a mass-circulation daily newspaper on Monday.
   All the opposition broadcasts and publications are subject to
the same censorship as government media.
   Walesa dominated the first half of the broadcast.
   He was shown laying flowers at a monument in Gdansk to workers
killed in price riots on the Baltic coast in 1970, then greeting
Solidarity's candidates to the Sejm and Senate at a meeting April
29 at the Gdansk shipyard where the independent union was born in
1980.
   The program showed interviews with pro-Solidarity students,
campaign workers collecting signatures needed to put candidates on
the ballot for the June vote, and then a series of people saying
why they would vote.
   Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz urged voters
to make sure they learn and remember the names of the candidates
backed by Solidarity, since the ballots will list only their names
and not affiliations.
   He told people not to worry about the authorities' list of
candidates since in that part, the elections are not free.
   Once the round-table talks began in February, government
television began showing short bits of his news conferences,
meetings and rallies with extensive coverage of Walesa's trip to
Rome in April to meet with Pope John Paul II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
