<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Politics     05-10 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Politics,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Party Abandons Unilateral Nuclear Disarmament Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition Labor Party's leadership, in a move
to broaden public support after a decade out of power, has
abandoned the party's unpopular policy of unilateral nuclear
disarmament.
   At the urging of party leader Neil Kinnock, Labor's National
Executive committee voted 17-8 on Tuesday for a policy under which
a Labor-led government would only scrap Britain's independent
nuclear arsenal as part of a negotiated arms control deal.
   Hard-line leftists accused Labor of betraying its principles.
   But Kinnock, once an ardent unilateralist, said the doctrine had
not won the support of like-minded politicians in other countries,
including the United States, France and the Soviet Union.
   ``Unilateralism is not even comprehended by those who share our
objectives in other countries,'' he said.
   ``They were totally uncomprehending that we should want to get
rid of a nuclear system without getting elimination of nuclear
weapons on other sides too _ without getting anything for it in
return,'' he said.
   The executive committee also voted 16-9 to defeat a motion by
hard-line leftists to set a deadline for unilaterally scrapping
Britain's submarine-borne nuclear missiles.
   The committee adopted an unopposed amendment that says a Labor
government would negotiate nuclear disarmament with the Soviet
Union if U.S.-Soviet negotiations stalled.
   Labor embraced unilateralism in 1981 and the policy has been
cited as a key reason for its two subsequent defeats by the
Conservatives under Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who believes
nuclear deterrence alone can maintain world peace.
   Kinnock and other party chiefs are trying to kill a widespread
perception that Labor is dominated by doctrinaire left-wingers, and
draw the party back to the political center.
   Labor currently holds 226 of the 650 seats in the
Conservative-dominated House of Commons.
   ``Out of power, we do not have the opportunities of unilateral
or any other sort of disarmament,'' Kinnock said. ``We only have
the chance to talk about it. In power we can act and make dramatic
progress.''
   Leftist hard-liners said they would fight to restore the
unilateralism doctrine at Labor's annual convention in October. The
convention must approve all policy changes.
   The executive committee also adopted unopposed a resolution
saying nuclear weapons are ``not a deterrent and of no practical
use.''
   Answering questions in Parliament Tuesday, Mrs. Thatcher said
she expected the outcome within Labor to be ``unilateralism in a
different wrapping.''
   Defense Secretary George Younger said: ``To arm yourself with a
deterrent, which you then say you will not use, would be about as
effective as a feather duster.''
   Labor's foreign affairs chief, Gerald Kaufman, said the new
policy is in line with most of Britain's NATO partners.
   Thatcher became prime minister in May 1979 after a victory in
parliamentary elections that forced out Labor's James Callaghan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
