<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     05-10 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Storm Jail, Free 189 Prisoners; Fighting Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen stormed Beirut's central jail
early today and freed 189 convicts as Christians and Syrians
battled with tanks across the city's dividing Green Line.
   Police said a special squad of officers armed with M-16 assault
rifles recaptured 90 convicts in a sweep of Moslem west Beirut.
   Seven people were killed and 47 wounded during the night, mostly
by tank fire, said a police spokesman, who cannot be named under
standing rules.
   That raised the overall casualty toll to 334 people killed and
1,281 wounded since fighting broke out on March 8 between Gen.
Michel Aoun's Christian army units and an alliance of Syrian and
Druse forces.
   An Arab League envoy held talks today in Damascus, the Syrian
capital, in an effort to revive a cease-fire called by the
organization on April 28.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, keeps 40,000 troops
across 70 percent of the country under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   The police spokesman said about 30 unidentified gunmen, armed
with Soviet-designed grenade launchers and AK-47 automatic rifles,
broke into the jail in a Moslem district at 2:20 a.m.
   He said a Moslem police sergeant was killed in a shootout with
the gunmen, who ``entered the prison warden's office, took the
keys, opened the cells and turned loose all 189 prisoners.''
   The tank clashes near the Green Line escalated into shelling of
Christian and Moslem residential districts at about midnight
Tuesday, the police spokesman said.
   Tanks deployed between apartment buildings drew howitzer and
anti-armor fire, but most shells missed them and blasted the
buildings.
   ``Both sides were using the population as their shield,'' the
spokesman said.
   Ambulance sirens and thuds from exploding shells echoed across
the city until the fighting slackened into occasional exchanges of
howitzer shells about 3:15 a.m., he said.
   The Arab League envoy, Lakhdar Ibrahimi of Algeria, was
accompanied by Gen. Ali Al-Momen, a Kuwaiti officer chosen to head
a 321-man observer force drawn from six Arab nations to help
implement a lasting cease-fire.
   Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, said
Tuesday that the Arab military observers would not arrive until a
cease-fire takes hold.
   ``It has become difficult in light of the recent developments to
send the observer force to Lebanon to expose their lives to danger
either by assassination or killing as a result of the
indiscriminate shelling,'' Al-Sabah told reporters in Kuwait.
   Aoun, who also heads a Christian military cabinet, and acting
Prime Minister Salim Hoss, his Sunni Moslem rival, both said they
accepted the truce.
   But Syrian forces and their allies from Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party militia continued to shell
the Christian enclave north of Beirut. They said they were trying
to prevent three ships loaded with Iraqi weapons and ammunition
from re-supplying Aoun's forces.
   Iraq, which has a long-running feud with Syria, backs Aoun's
pledge to fight until Syrian troops are withdrawn from Lebanon.
   The current round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war
began two days after Aoun's navy blockaded three ports controlled
by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut in a bid to recoup lost
tax revenues estimated at $100 million annually.
   Jumblatt's militia retaliated by shelling the 310-square mile
Christian heartland, the Syrians joined in later.
</TEXT>
