<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-10 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today
and gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was waiting for signs
of central bank intervention or statements by senior officials that
could shed light on the currency's near-term course.
   ``The general trend remains bullish (for the dollar),'' said one
trader in Rome. ``This is just a moment of reflection.''
   Traders said the dollar remains supported by relatively high
U.S. interest rates, the perception the rates may continue to rise
and by political problems in West Germany and Japan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.56 yen to a closing 134.44. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _ 1.9072 West German marks, down from 1.9158
   _ 1.6895 Swiss francs, down from 1.7035
   _ 6.4435 French francs, down from 6.4645
   _ 2.1535 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1610
   _ 1,390.80 Italian lire, down from 1,397.125
   _ 1.1845 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1869
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6690, more expensive for
buyers than $1.6605 Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $378.00 a troy ounce, up
from $376.50 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $378.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $378.25, up from $376.40 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.87 to close at a bid $378.94.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.67 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.63.
</TEXT>
