<DOCNO> AP890510-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Media     05-10 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Media,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Papers Give Prominent Coverage to Reporter Demands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major state newspapers today gave prominent
coverage of an appeal made by journalists for press freedom, and a
few offered unusually full accounts of reporters' complaints of
censorship.
   ``This action is unprecedented in the history of ... China's
media,'' Science and Technology Daily said of the anti-censorship
petition signed by more than 1,000 reporters and delivered to the
government Tuesday.
   Press freedom has been one of the main demands of the recent
student demonstrations, along with calls for greater democracy and
clean government.
   ``Generally speaking, I believe that today's reports (on the
journalists' appeal) weren't bad,'' said Li Datong, an editor at
the China Youth News who delivered the petition.
   Despite the coverage, the censor's work still was apparent. Some
articles noted the reporters' call for talks with Communist
officials but did not explain the grievances; other reports toned
down the petition's harshest wording.
   For example, the petition said that ``restrictions of every kind
have prevented full, objective and fair reporting'' on the student
protests. The official Xinhua News Agency and some newspapers
changed ``restrictions'' to ``reasons.''
   Science and Technology Daily, which gave a lengthy and
relatively objective account of the reporters' protest, noted the
petitioners complained that ``the press in the capital was tied up
in every manner in their reports on this major event.''
   The newspaper, in explaining the reporters' grievances, said:
``In fact, severe abuses exist in the current system of reporting
news in China.''
   At least two newspapers, the Economic Daily and the Legal Daily,
mentioned the petitioners' request to hold talks with party
propaganda officials on the firing of the editor of China's most
liberal paper after he rejected censor's demands.
   The Science and Technology Daily listed the names of 32 media
organizations, including itself, whose journalists were among those
who signed the petition.
   The official media initially maintained silence on the student
protests, which began on April 15 and brought tens of thousands of
people into the streets of the capital.
   Xinhua later issued brief, understated reports on the
demonstrations, while a few newspapers carried reports that made
the scope of the marches clear. Many reporters attended the marches
and handed in reports and photographs, but said their editors
decided not to use most of the material for fear it would fuel the
protests.
   Li said that while Beijing's newspapers have shown some openness
and flexibility in reporting the past few days, there are no
guarantees such trends will continue.
   ``China's press still lacks a feeling of safety,'' Li said in a
telephone interview, adding that a set of laws and regulations to
protect press freedom still was needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
