<FIRST>r p PM-ElectionsRdp     05-10 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elections Rdp,0451</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Mayoral Elections in Nebraska and New Jersey; Referendum in S.C.
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in Omaha, Neb., rejected a former mayor's bid to regain
the seat he lost in a recall election two years ago, while another
former mayor in Jersey City, N.J., advanced to a runoff in his bid
to win back the post.
   Also Tuesday, residents of Hilton Head Island, S.C., turned down
a measure that would have restricted growth at the golf-and-tennis
resort.
   In Nebraska, Omaha businessman P.J. Morgan ended former Mayor
Mike Boyle's comeback hopes. Boyle lost a recall election two years
ago amid allegations that he abused his executive power.
   With only absentee ballots remaining to be counted, Morgan had
56,774 votes or 53 percent, to Boyle's 48,115 votes, or 45 percent.
   Boyle, 45, said during the campaign that he was a recovering
alcoholic who had changed his controversial management style.
   ``I wouldn't have wanted to put my life on hold for another four
years,'' Boyle said.
   Morgan, 49, a millionaire real estate manager, outspent Boyle by
a margin of nearly 2-to-1, but Morgan said he didn't believe that
had been a factor.
   Election officials said voter turnout was about 50 percent.
   In Jersey City, former Mayor Gerald McCann and City Council
President Glenn Cunningham will face each other in a June 13 runoff
after besting eight other contenders.
   With all votes counted, unofficial returns showed McCann with
13,196 votes and Cunningham with 9,292 votes.
   McCann is hoping to recapture the job he lost in 1985 to
incumbent Anthony Cucci, who placed fourth in the balloting.
   Cunningham would become the city's first black mayor.
   ``The race that I see is the race for the mayor of Jersey
City,'' Cunningham said. ``That's the only race I'm concerned
with.''
   Voter turnout was 52 percent, compared to 67 percent in 1985.
   The mayor of Hilton Head Island said officials were relieved
that residents turned down a measure that would have restricted
growth by tying construction to how long motorists have to wait at
traffic lights.
   ``I think we can take a deep breath now that this is settled and
continue what we've been doing all along _ managing growth,'' Mayor
Marth Baumberger said after Tuesday's referendum.
   Town Clerk Tammy Malone said there were 6,369 votes, or 68
percent, against the measure and 2,995, or 32 percent, in favor.
   The measure would have frozen building permits if traffic, as
measured at any of several specified locations, slowed such that
drivers must wait more than two turns of a traffic light during the
peak of the tourist season in June.
</TEXT>
