<FIRST>r a PM-NarcoticsInspection     05-10 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Narcotics Inspection,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff To Snare Drug Drivers With Bogus Highway Signs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff has deployed a new weapon in his
drug-fighting arsenal: yellow diamond-shaped signs on Interstate 95
warning travelers of a ``Narcotics Inspection Ahead.''
   There is no inspection, but drivers who panic and illegally turn
around in the median will be stopped.
   Volusia County Sheriff Bob Vogel, whose unorthodox anti-drug
methods have caught national attention, says the public supports
his work.
   ``They applaud the efforts that law enforcement is making to
curtail this epidemic,'' he said Tuesday as he unveiled the signs.
   Defense attorneys and civil libertarians cried foul.
   ``You have to admit they're clever. But they're tricking people
into committing a crime,'' said Ron Ross, chairman of the Orlando
branch of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   Controversy isn't new to Vogel.
   He developed a drug suspect profile that produced an 80 percent
arrest rate on drug cases and was featured in a 1987 episode of
CBS' ``60 Minutes.'' Defense attorneys said he really was
arbitrarily stopping blacks wearing gold chains and driving large,
rented cars. Vogel denied any racial factor.
   State and federal appellate courts have ruled that officers can
use a profile to make an arrest only after stopping someone for a
traffic violation. The Florida Supreme Court is considering the
matter.
   Vogel has ordered deputies to continue stopping
suspicious-looking motorists since becoming sheriff of the North
Florida county in January. Since then, deputies have seized nearly
$300,000 in cash when there has not been enough evidence to make an
arrest.
   To defense attorneys and lawyers for the ACLU, the new highway
signs are just another high-handed, questionable tactic.
   ``It is a very drastic step toward a totalitarian form of
government,'' said Daytona Beach lawyer Dan Warren.
   ``To put up a sign that is meaningless is not a legitimate use
of police power,'' said Robyn Blumner, president of Florida's ACLU.
Checkpoints would be illegal anyway because cars are protected from
searches just like homes, she said.
   Vogel said 90 percent of the motorists stopped for traffic
violations and suspected of transporting drugs or having cash
tainted with drugs consent to having their cars searched.
   When a search turns up a large sum of cash but no drugs, a dog
is brought in to sniff the money. The cash is confiscated if traces
of narcotics are found. Motorists are entitled to a receipt for the
money, but often they just drive away, Vogel said.
   Warren said the use of dogs is questionable and cited a Miami
study that found traces of drugs on 20 percent of money tested in
bank vaults.
   But Vogel is undeterred.
   ``It's very uncommon for the average American I know of to be
transporting large sums of cash on the highways,'' he said. Vogel
is asking the courts to award money seized to the sheriff's
department to help finance his war on drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
