<SECOND>PM-Dorothy Bush,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>President's Mother in Fair Condition At Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Walker Bush, President Bush's
87-year-old mother, was listed in fair condition at Greenwich
Hospital after being admitted with a possible blood clot in her
right leg, a spokeswoman said.
   ``Her status is improving, she's alert, oriented and is
eating,'' hospital spokeswoman Vicki Pitluk said Tuesday night.
   Mrs. Bush was brought to the hospital by ambulance Monday night
with ``evidence of a slight thrombotic stroke involving her right
leg, complicated by a 102-degree temperature,'' Pitluk said.
   Mrs. Bush remained on an intravenous infusion and antibiotics
Tuesday, but her temperature dropped to about 99 degrees, Pitluk
said.
   Mrs. Bush underwent a series of diagnostic exams and laboratory
tests Tuesday.
   ``Her neurological status is improved and she is moving all her
extremities, although she is experiencing weakness in her right
leg,'' Pitluk said.
   Mrs. Bush will be released from the hospital when her condition
is stable, Pitluk said.
   Her daughter-in-law, Elizabeth Bush, said she was doing well.
   Elizabeth Bush, of Greenwich, said her brother-in-law, President
Bush, has been in constant contact with his mother's physicians.
   ``He keeps checking all the time,'' she said.
