<HEAD>Heavy Rains Fall on East, South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain soaked much of the East early today while thunderstorms
rocked several Western states with damaging winds and hail.
   Moist, unstable air over the northern Rockies triggered strong
thunderstorms Tuesday evening.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted up to 69 mph in Idaho, damaging
buildings and downing trees and power lines in the state's
southeast corner. Winds also gusted up to 62 mph at Grand Junction,
Colo., and up to 51 mph at Big Piney, Wyo.
   A thunderstorm at White Rock, N.M., dumped 1\ inches of rain and
three-quarter inch hail that covered the ground and dented
automobiles.
   Strong thunderstorms rumbled over southern Texas, with golf
ball-size hail falling on Edwards County.
   Locally heavy rains also occurred across central and northern
California.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms extended along a cold front
from southern Mississippi across central Georgia to the southern
Atlantic Coast. Heavy rains caused water to rise over roads and
bridges in northwest Union County, N.C.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included more than 1\ inches in Atlanta and more than
three-quarters of an inch at Fayetteville, Charlotte and Goldsboro
in North Carolina.
   Rain also was falling this morning from the middle Atlantic
Coast to the lower Great Lakes.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Gulf Goast and northern Florida across the southern and middle
Atlantic Coast, and over much of the Pacific Coast and the northern
and central Rockies; showers from the upper Ohio Valley and central
Appalachians to New England; and cloudy skies over western Texas
and southeast New Mexico.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s along the northern Pacific
Coast and from the northern and middle Atlantic Coast across the
northern and central Appalachians to much of the Great Lakes; in
the 80s over Montana, North Dakota, the Gulf Coast, the central and
southern Rockies and parts of Southern California; and in the 60s
and 70s elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 28 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 81 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 64 foggy; Boston 49 cloudy; Buffalo 46 rain;
Charleston, S.C. 68 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 49 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 48 foggy; Detroit 45 fair; Miami 71 fair; New York 53
rain; Philadelphia 53 rain; Pittsburgh 48 rain; Portland, Maine 42
foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 49 fair; Chicago 47 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
61 partly cloudy; Denver 46 foggy; Des Moines 42 fair; Indianapolis
42 fair; Kansas City 45 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 50 fair;
Nashville 54 cloudy; New Orleans 73 partly cloudy; St. Louis 47
foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 59 windy; Anchorage 41 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 66 windy; Los Angeles 59 partly cloudy; Phoenix 79 fair; Salt
Lake City 58 fair; San Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 53 windy;
Seattle 48 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 43 fair; Toronto 43 cloudy.
