<DOCNO> AP890510-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-ChineseRemains     05-10 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Chinese Remains,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Command to Return Korean War Remains to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of 19 Chinese soldiers
killed during the 1950-53 Korean War will be returned to their
homeland, military authorities said today.
   The U.S.-led U.N. command said the remains would be turned over
to China on Friday at the truce village of Panmunjom in the
demilitarized zone that separates North Korea and South Korea.
   The last attempt to return remains of soldiers to North Korea
was in June 1987, but the north refused to accept them and the
bodies were buried in the south. The U.N. command has asked for the
return of bodies of U.S. soldiers still believed to be in the north.
   Korea was divided into the communist north and the capitalist
south at the end of World War II. In 1950, the north invaded the
south to begin the Korean War. China sided with the north and U.S.
troops fought with the south.
   The Chinese remains were recovered near Chipyong-ni, about 30
miles east of Seoul and the site of a major battle in 1951.
Officials were not immediately available for comment on when the
remains were found or under what circumstances.
</TEXT>
