<FIRST>r i PM-PENConference     05-10 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PEN Conference,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Poet Elected President Of PEN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAASTRICHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French poet Rene Tavernier was
elected president of PEN today, succeeding British novelist Francis
King, who headed the international writers' association for three
years.
   Tavernier, 74, was elected by 35 votes to 30, defeating Nigerian
poet, novelist and short story writer Chinua Achebe, according to
PEN spokeswoman Margot Dijkgraaf. There were two abstentions, she
said.
   PEN _ or Poets, Playwrights, Editors, Essayists and Novelists _
was founded in 1921 and has about 60 local chapters and 10,000
members worldwide.
   Tavernier's candidacy was sponsored mainly by the group's
French-speaking chapters, with Achebe being backed by the
English-speaking groups.
   Tavernier thinks his most important role is to counteract the
meaninglessness of the language used by the electronic mass media,
according to a biography of the poet, made available to reporters
attending PEN's 53rd annual conference in this southern city. In
Tavernier's view, ``The poet is in some way the lifeline of a world
in which language is being permitted to dwindle to
insignificance,'' the biography said.
   From 1941-50, Tavernier edited ``Confluences,'' the most
important literary magazine of the French resistance. His recent
works include two poetry collections, ``34 Poems'' and ``Questions
To The Rising Sun.''
   Later today, the conference was expected to admit a new Soviet
chapter in a move that would open PEN to the Soviet Union for the
first time in 65 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
