<HEAD>Hi-Tech Camera Destine For Soviets Seized By Customs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd pvs, ``The officers...'' to ADD that
camera is British made. Pickup 4th pvs, ``Because the...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs officers say they seized one
of the world's most sophisticated cameras, used in missile
technology, before it could be flown to the Soviet Union.
   The camera was confiscated at Birmingham's airport on Monday,
and the officers said they were questioning two businessmen who had
been arrested early Tuesday in nearby Rugby and in London.
   The officers, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
camera is capable of photographing 2,500 frames a second and costs
about $417,500.
   A customs spokesman said the camera was made in Britain, but he
would not identify it further.
   Because the camera is used in nuclear missile technology,
British regulations restricted its export to the 16-nation NATO
alliance and Japan.
   Customs officers said they suspected that similar
high-technology cameras and laser equipment, shipped through
intermediate countries, had been smuggled to East European
communist countries.
