<FIRST>r i PM-BomberLanding     05-10 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bomber Landing,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Bomber Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPPER HEYFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. F1-11E bomber made an
emergency landing shortly after takeoff when it developed engine
trouble, an Air Force spokesman said today.
   Local residents near the Upper Heyford air base called police
when the plane jettisoned high-octane fuel to reduce the risk of an
explosion on landing and the jet's exhaust plume ignited the fuel
in a ball of flame.
   The supersonic bomber is capable of carrying nuclear weapons but
had no such weapons aboard during the Tuesday night training
flight, said the spokesman. The jet returned to the base 60 miles
northwest of London two minutes after taking off, he said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The jet was not damaged and the two crewmen were not injured, he
said. ``At no time were British residents in the area in danger,''
the spokesman said.
   An investigation will be carried out into the cause of an
``engine problem,'' he said, but he refused to say what had gone
wrong.
   The U.S. Air Force keeps about 150 F1-11s at Upper Heyford and
Lakenheath bases in England. Each aircraft is capable of carrying
three nuclear free-fall bombs over a range of 1,500 miles without
refueling.
   Bruce Kent, chairman of the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament,
said some F1-11s are on constant alert armed with nuclear weapons,
raising concerns about a catastrophic crash.
</TEXT>
