<FIRST>r i PM-Italy     05-10 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millions Of Italians Strike Over Increased Health Fees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Italian workers stayed off the job today
in a general strike called by Italy's three main labor unions to
protest a change in the government's health plan requiring payment
of nominal fees.
   Schools shut for the day, banks and public offices closed in the
morning and newspapers didn't publish. City bus drivers struck for
two hours.
   Union rallies were held in major cities.
   The unions urged 16 million workers to strike for up to four
hours to protest what they say is an unfair burden on workers and
the elderly.
   The so-called ``ticket system'' went into effect April 1 and
requires the payment of small fees for hospitalization and medical
tests in state hospitals.
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita denounced the strike, saying people are
prepared to spend large amounts of money to attend soccer games or
take weekend vacations but not to pay the $7 daily fee required for
hospitalization.
   ``Whoever thinks that this strike is disproportionate in respect
to the (fees) is making a mistake,'' social activist Giovanni Moro
told a rally in Florence, where unions said 150,000 people turned
out. ``Above all, they don't understand that citizens of the
world's fifth industrial power don't want a Third World health
system.''
   The strike was called by the communist-dominated General
Federation of Italian Labor, the mostly Christian Democratic
Italian Federation of Union Workers and the Socialist-led Italian
Union of Workers.
</TEXT>
