<DOCNO> AP890510-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     05-10 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reopens Most Sri Lankan Universities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six of Sri Lanka's eight universities
reopened today, two years after the government shut them to stem
student unrest and violent anti-government demonstrations.
   There were no violent incidents today. But a third of the
students boycotted classes, and at least 850 university janitors
and clerks went on strike to demand higher wages, the Higher
Education Ministry.
   Ministry officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the closures have caused an acute shortage of professionals in the
country.
   Military and government officials said the six colleges were
power bases for the extremist People's Liberation Front, a radical
group of the majority Sinhalese people who are waging a terror
campaign against the government.
   Higher Education Minister Shahul Hameed last month decided to
reopen the colleges after he met representatives of the
Inter-Universities Students Federation, an umbrella body of
scholars from the six universities.
   He said student grievances had been resolved, but the federation
said they were not and called for class boycotts.
   The federation says soldiers have killed at least 26 students
among dozens arrested, and it wants an accounting.
   About 60 percent of the country's 24,000 undergraduates ignored
the boycott and showed up a school, the minisry said.
   Elsehwere in Sri Lanka today, military officials reported
militants from the front killed at least 10 Sinhalese in separate
incidents since Tuesday.
   Four people, including two school principals, were killed and
their bodies dumped in a cemetery at Polgahawela village, 85 miles
northeast of Colombo.
   Six activists in the governing United National Party were killed
in southern villages, the military officials said on condition of
anonymity.
   The ultra-left front is blamed for the killings of more than
3,500 people since it launched its anti-government campaign in July
1987 to protest peace overtures made to Tamil rebels fighting since
1983 for an independent nation.
   Tamils, who form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's population, say the
dominant Sinhalese discriminate against them in jobs and education
and have tried to supplant their Tamil language with Sinhalese.
More than 9,000 people have died in the Tamil insurrection, mostly
Sinhalese civilians.
</TEXT>
