<HEAD>Sympathetic Judge Says `Miss America' Bandit Influenced by Bum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Mast, 24 ...' to RESTORE first reference.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank robber dubbed the ``Miss America''
bandit because of her glamorous disguises received a light two
years in prison from a judge who said she had come under the
influence of a Svengali-like boyfriend.
   ``The history of it is that men have exercised traditional
control over the activities of women, and I'm not going to ignore
that, no matter how much flak I get from women's lib,'' U.S.
District Judge A. Andrew Hauk said Tuesday.
   Danielle Tyece Mast, 24, of Reedsport, Ore., a former
cheerleader and bank teller who favored fashionable wigs and
sunglasses as disguises, was convicted of taking $13,000 in five
holdups last summer. She could have received up to five years in
prison.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Gregory W. Alarcon asked for a stiff
sentence, but Hauk, one of the most experienced judges on the
federal bench, agreed with Miss Mast's lawyer that she acted under
the spell of her live-in boyfriend.
   ``I think it's a fact of life that men can exercise a Svengali
influence over women,'' Hauk declared. He added, ``Women are a soft
touch, particularly if sex is involved.''
   The prosecutor complained that Miss Mast had shown no remorse,
and he argued that the boyfriend wasn't present during any of the
robberies and hasn't been charged.
   Feminist attorney Gloria Allred said Hauk's remarks were
unfortunate.
   ``That is an untrue stereotype, that men are able to control
women,'' she said. ``Unscientific generalizations such as this one
have no place in the courtroom or in the decision-making process.''
