<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Libya 1stLd-Writethru   05-10 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0544,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Company Head Arrested Over Alleged Chemical Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT spelling of name and ADDS 1 graf at
end with comment from judicial officials.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today arrested the
former head of a West Germany company at the center of a scandal
involving a suspected chemical weapons plant in Libya, a prosecutor
said.
   West German and U.S. authorities alleged that the company,
Imhausen-Chemie, was the key supplier of material for the plant in
the Libyan city of Rabta. Libya claimed the plant was for making
pharmaceuticals, but U.S. and West German officials claim it was
intended to manufacture chemical weapons.
   Juergen Hippenstiel-Imhausen, who was chief of Imhausen-Chemie
until March, was arrested in the city of Bochum, said prosecutor
Holger Preisendanz, who is leading the probe into the case.
   Hippenstiel-Imhausen is ``strongly suspected'' of violating West
German export laws, Preisendanz told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview.
   Preisendanz said he had received evidence of such violations
since he began investigating the case in February, but he refused
to release details.
   ``The arrest is in connection with the probe into the Libyan
plant,'' the prosecutor said, adding that Hippenstiel-Imhausen had
not been indicted.
   The prosecutor said authorities were concerned that
Hippenstiel-Imhausen may have been preparing to flee West Germany.
Hippenstiel-Imhausen resigned in March as head of the family-owned
company in the Black Forest city of Lahr.
   In Bochum, judicial authorities released a statement saying they
were concerned that Hippenstiel-Imhausen might have been trying to
hide evidence needed for the investigation.
