<DOCNO> AP890510-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Soviet-Arms 1stLd-Writethru a0445 05-10 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Arms, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Arms Control Experts Say Soviet Arms Concessions Are Real</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Subs pvs grafs 3-5, The remarks ... Andrei,'' with 3 grafs to
correct day of Baker-Shevardnadze meeting, include Kokoshin's title and
include reference to honorifics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet arms control experts, in an unusual
appearance on Capitol Hill, said hard-liners are growing impatient
with Kremlin concessions and denied U.S. intelligence reports that
Soviet military production continues at previous levels.
   ``There are many people in the Soviet Union, and their voices
are heard, who raise the question, `To what extent can we do these
unilateral steps without a response from the other side?''' said
Andrei Kokoshin, one of the leading proponents of the Soviet ``new
thinking'' on national security issues.
   The remarks by Kokoshin, deputy director of Moscow's USA-Canada
Institute, and three other prominent Soviet civilian experts on
military affairs clearly were aimed at spurring the Bush
administration in arms talks with the Kremlin.
   Those talks were expected to regain momentum after Secretary of
State James A. Baker III met in Moscow today with his Soviet
counterpart, Eduard A. Shevardnadze. Baker was to meet Thursday
with Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Capitol Hill session generally was friendly, as House Armed
Services Committee chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., and Kokoshin
addressed each other as ``Les'' and ``Andrei.'' By contrast, when
Cabinet members testify, they usually call Aspin ``Mr. Chairman,''
and are addressed as ``Mr. or Mrs. Secretary.''
   Despite the informal atmosphere, three panel members expressed
concern about the testimony and several all but accused the Soviets
of lying.
   Rep. Richard Ray, D-Ga., asked the Soviets to discuss warnings
by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and other Americans that ``the
goals of the Soviet Union have really not changed'' despite the
reforms.
   ``They point to the fact that weapons manufacturing continues,
tank production at 278 a month continues with no letup, submarine
building, ship building, airplane building, and so forth, continues
to be modernized,'' said Ray.
   Kokoshin said weapons production was down. New Soviet policy
``includes not only unilateral cuts in the Armed Forces and arms
which we possess now, but also the decrease of the production of
military hardware,'' Kokoshin said.
   ``I know that we are cutting the production,'' he said.
   Roald Sagdeyev, a prominent reformer elected to the newly
created Congress of Peoples' Deputies, told the House panel that
Soviet military spending had been cut by 1.5 percent this year, and
would be cut by 7 percent next year and 14.2 percent in 1991.
   The actual Soviet military budget has not been published,
Kokoshin and Sagdeyev acknowledged, but they said the figure would
be revealed in June.
   Intelligence sources said preliminary data indicated that during
the first four months of 1989, Soviet tank production had risen
from the previous level of 3,200 to 3,400 a year, in the same range
as Ray's figure.
   But the statistics were under review, and the surge was believed
to be temporary and related to plans to close down production lines
rather than to reflect Soviet intentions to boost annual output,
according to intelligence sources who asked not to be further
identified.
   A report by Central Intelligence Agency and Pentagon analysts
released last month estimated that Soviet defense spending
increased by 3 percent last year, but cited evidence that Gorbachev
planned to make good on his pledge to cut that level by 14.2
percent.
   The ranking Republican in the panel, Rep. William Dickinson of
Alabama, complained that the Soviets had deployed anti-satellite
weapons.
   Sagdeyev, who formerly headed the Soviet Institute for Space
Exploration, replied that ``I have serious doubts if Russians, my
Russian military space counterparts, have anything like an
operational (ASAT) system.''
   ``Our intelligence apparatus tells us that you do have in fact
more than one (ASAT) operational capability,'' Dickinson responded.
   Dickinson expressed reservations about the presence of the
Soviet delegation and the reluctance of the Soviet government to
grant visas to members of the Armed Services Committee to travel to
Moscow later this month.
   ``I have mixed feelings about foreign witnesses testifying
before the committee in open session on diplomatically sensitive
foreign national issues. We are prohibited by law from
negotiating,'' Dickinson said.
   Rep. Beverly Byron, D-Md., also complained about the visa issue.
   Soviet officials and scholars have testified before Congress at
least twice previously. In April 1986, Vitaly Churkin, then a third
secretary at the Soviet Embassy in Washington, appeared before a
House panel to answer questions about the Chernobyl nuclear reactor
accident, and Kokoshin appeared before the House Armed Services
Committee earlier this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BakerSaysTalksOfftoaGoodStart     05-10 0909</FIRST>
<SECOND>Baker Says Talks Off to a Good Start</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Baker and foreign ministry comments, edits throughout
to tighten, no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III held
his first round of talks today with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze and they jointly pledged to produce ``good
results'' for superpower relations.
   The two-hour, 45-minute session at a Foreign Ministry mansion
established goals and ground rules for four working groups that
opened discussions on arms control, human rights, regional problems
and direct U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``We are very pleased with the way things started,'' Baker said.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, a foreign ministry spokesman, said Baker
and Shevardnadze, at the request of the American side, concentrated
on regional conflicts, including the Middle East, Central America
and Afghanistan.
   ``Dealing with regional problems will enable us to get the last
of the Cold War behind us and move into a new stage of our
relationship,'' Gerasimov said.
   He said the subject of short-range missiles in Europe did not
come up.
   The two sides found common ground on Central America, Gerasimov
said. ``Both sides stated there was good potential for a furthering
of dialogue on a Central American settlement,'' he said.
   Baker wants the Soviets to curb their aid to the Sandinistas in
Nicaragua, which amounted to $500 million last year. The Soviets
also raised Afghanistan, a topic Baker had no intention of bringing
up because the Kremlin is demanding the United States halt its
military aid to Afghan rebels.
   In both countries, Marxist governments have Soviet support,
while the United States is backing the insurgents _ with weapons
through Pakistan for the Mujahadeen and with non-lethal aid to the
Contras in Nicaragua.
   According to Gerasimov, Baker and Shevardnadze also discussed
U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's prediction that perestroika,
the restructuring program of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, would
fail.
   Baker explained that Cheney's remarks did not reflect
Washington's official position, and Shevardnadze did not take
offense, Gerasimov said.
   ``We understand that the secretary of defense needs more money
for military programs and how can he possibly obtain that if the
Soviet threat is going away?'' Gerasimov said. ``We were not
offended.''
   Baker, in the Soviet Union for the first time, later met with
three members of the Congress of People's Deputies, a new
parliament elected as Gorbachev gives greater powers to the
legislative arm of government.
   ``We think there are real changes taking place in the Soviet
Union, and we think those changes are more than cosmetic, as
demonstrated by the fact that we now see competitive elections,
looking towards a sitting legislature,'' Baker said at the meeting
at Spaso House, the U.S. ambassador's residence.
   The congress is to meet May 25 to choose a smaller, full-time
legislature, as well as a president. Asked if more than one
candidate should run for president, Baker said, ``One step at a
time.''
   In two days of talks, Baker is expected to turn to Gorbachev for
help in accelerating the fledling U.S. drive for Arab-Israeli
negotiations.
   The U.S. approach to the Middle East represents a shift in
diplomatic gears from two decades of trying to fence out both the
Soviet Union and the Palestine Liberation Organization as apt to
undermine American peace-making.
   Once before, in 1977, the United States made a concerted effort
to engage the Soviet Union in Middle East peace-making. The Carter
administration at that point was at a dead-end in its Mideast
diplomacy.
   But Egypt and Israel quickly decided to launch negotiations, and
the Soviets were shut out again.
   Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979 and since then
have been the largest recipients of U.S. aid and solidly on the
American side of the superpower divide.
   But Baker is faced with a different situation. He is trying to
prod Israel into negotiations with the Palestinians and has
concluded he needs the support of both Moscow and the PLO.
   He is hoping the Soviets under Gorbachev would bring pressure on
Syria to support peace talks that do not hold out the promise of a
Palestinian state. The Soviet Union has refused to exert such power
in the past.
   The PLO, meanwhile, quietly has been assured that if Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's plan for Palestinian elections does
not break the diplomatic stalemate in the Middle East the Bush
administration will look for alternatives.
   At the same time, Baker and his senior advisers are convinced
PLO chairman Yasser Arafat is sincere about his public acceptance
of Israel.
   If the Soviets push the missile issue they could widen the
fissures between the United States and West Germany over NATO's
nuclear arsenal.
   The Bush administration, supported mostly by Britain, wants to
enhance the range of the 88 Lance launchers and their 700 or so
missiles, most of which are in West Germany, while Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, backed by a majority of the alliance, is resisting and
calling for U.S.-Soviet negotiations on such weapons in Europe.
   By contrast, Baker is playing down arms control.
   He headed to Moscow with a proposed date _ the third week in
June _ for the reopening of U.S.-Soviet negotiations to reduce the
superpowers' long-range bombers, nuclear submarines and
globe-girdling missiles.
   But he was not planning to outline the position the United
States would take at the table. Nor was he assuring the Soviets
that there would be no changes since the talks were recessed in
November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
