<FIRST>r a PM-RacketeeringSentences     05-10 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racketeering Sentences,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Mobster Connected to Mob Boss Scarfo Defects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mobster's decision to turn informant may
finally enable prosecutors to link Mafia boss Nicodemo ``Little
Nicky'' Scarfo to the Atlantic City casinos, law enforcement
sources say.
   Lawrence ``Yogi'' Merlino, facing up to a 40-year prison term in
a federal racketeering conspiracy, agreed to cooperate in an
attempt to shorten his possible jail time, a source said Tuesday.
   Merlino already is serving a life term for murder in a 1985 mob
hit and cannot be paroled unless the governor commutes the sentence.
   ``We think he's got a lot to say,'' an investigator said about
Merlino, the fourth member of Scarfo's mob to break the code of
silence and become an informant.
   The 42-year-old Merlino has been associated with two companies
that reportedly did millions of dollars in Atlantic City
construction, some with the casinos.
   For years FBI agents and New Jersey State Police, despite their
suspicions, have been unable to get sufficient evidence to charge
the mob with infiltrating the construction industry and casino
unions.
   Merlino's lawyer, Nino Tinari, declined to comment on the
reported defection.
   Scarfo's lawyer, Robert Simone, said, ``Nothing surprises me
anymore, but I will be surprised if a new informant comes out of
the woodwork.''
   Merlino was convicted with Scarfo and six others last month in
the murder of gangster Frank ``Frankie Flowers'' D'Alfonso. All got
life terms.
   Seventeen men were convicted in November in the racketeering
case, which involved nine murders, four attempted murders,
extortions, drug dealing, loan sharking and gambling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
