<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief 1stLd-Writethru a0477 05-10 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new penultimate graf of 1st item to include People for
the American Way opposing nomination.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Groups Oppose Lucas in Justice Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of civil rights organizations is
voicing its opposition to the appointment of William Lucas to head
the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   The Leadership Conference on Civil Rights said Tuesday that
Lucas doesn't have the experience or litigation skills needed in
the position, which is the federal government's top civil rights
job.
   The conference is an umbrella group of 180 organizations and the
opposition was adopted ``by consensus'' at a meeting of the
conference, according to Ralph Neas, executive director of the
organization.
   Neas and Benjamin Hooks, chairman of the conference, said Lucas
``may well be qualified for other important positions in the
federal government, but he does not have the experience, the
substantive knowledge of the increasingly technical field of civil
rights, or the litigation skills to carry out the duties
effectively.''
   The NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund, a New York-based
civil rights organization, said in a separate announcement that it
would oppose the nomination because Lucas lacked the ``knowledge
and experience'' for the position.
   People for the American Way, a 275,000-member ``constitutional
liberties organization,'' also announced its opposition to Lucas.
Group President Arthur J. Kropp said in a statement that Lucas
``has demonstrated none of the civil rights experience so necessary
for this position, has no litigation experience whatsoever and has
barely a few months of legal experience.''
   The opposition was the latest round in the controversy swirling
around Lucas, a black Detroit lawyer. Lucas, 61, also has been an
FBI agent, sheriff of Wayne County, Mich., and the chief executive
of that county.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Agency Tightens Workers' Safeguards</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Direct exposure to the pesticide bromoxynil
could cause birth defects, the Environmental Protection Agency has
said in ordering tighter safeguards to protect workers handling the
pesticide.
   The EPA said Tuesday there are only ``negligible'' health risks
to consumers of food products on which the pesticide is used, but
that the risks are substantially greater to workers who come into
direct contact with the chemical.
   Bromoxynil, sold under the trade name Buctril, is used to
control broadleaf weeds in the growing of field corn, wheat,
onions, garlic, mint and flax.
   Under the EPA directive, mixers and other handlers of the
chemical must wear protective clothing, including
chemical-resistant shoes or boots. The manufacturer also must
provide protective labels warning that exposure to a worker during
pregnancy could cause birth defects.
   ``EPA believes that compliance with the new label directions and
restrictions will provide adequate protection from the risk of
birth defects,'' the agency said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Bush To Propose Turning Family Planning Over To States</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official says the Bush administration will
soon propose legislation to provide state control over current
federal family planning programs, which generate continual
controversy over abortion.
   ``Making the states the sole family planning grantees will
enable them to exercise maximum flexibility in tailoring services
to best meet their citizens' needs,'' said Nabers Chambers, deputy
assistant secretary for population affairs at the Department of
Health and Human Services.
   In advocating the transfer Tuesday, she did not specifically
mention differences over how far federally funded family planning
clinics can go in telling pregnant women about the availablity of
abortion, a matter now being fought in three separate federal court
suits.
   But Ms. Chambers said giving states authority over how to parcel
out the federal money allocated to them for family planning would
allow them ``flexibility to operate clinics through county
agencies, private agencies, or hospitals as is most appropriate for
each particular state.''
   Congress consistently rejected similar efforts by former
President Reagan to transfer the program to state control.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Air Force To Continue Hurricane Hunters For Two Years</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has agreed to keep its fleet of
``hurricane hunters'' for two years, reversing Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney's plan to scrap weather reconnaissance flights in the
midst of the hurricane season.
   ``It's a good resolution of the problem,'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, said late Tuesday after a group of coastal states
lawmakers met with acting Air Force Secretary Jack Welch and other
officials of the Pentagon and National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   NOAA and the Air Force will attempt to work out an agreement
over the next two years on which agency would eventually man the
planes that fly into the eye of a hurricane, lawmakers said.
   It has been suggested the hurricane hunters become the
responsibility of NOAA, but Bentsen and others contend the agency
would be unable to take over the program on such quick notice.
   Cheney said the flights, used to predict the intensity and
position of an approaching hurricane, were not a defense mission
and sought to save at least $14 million annually by slashing the
program.
   But lawmakers complained that phasing it out this summer would
leave hurricane-prone regions dangerously exposed.
</TEXT>
