<DOCNO> AP890510-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru   05-10 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0541,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Finds Listening Devices Hidden in Election Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th, `Most leading...' to ADD details
on location of wire. Pickup 6th pvs, `Moskwa said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity workers found electronic
eavesdropping devices in campaign offices in a northern provincial
capital and demanded that the Interior Ministry investigate, a
union spokesman said today.
   The devices were found in the Solidarity Citizens Committee
office in Slupsk, a city near the Baltic coast 270 miles northeast
of Warsaw.
   Jacek Moskwa, spokesman for the Solidarity committee
coordinating election activities, told reporters in Warsaw the
electronic devices were spotted by campaign workers and reported to
the national campaign headquarters on Tuesday.
   A government spokesman in Warsaw, Pawel Byra, said he knew
nothing about the matter.
   Most leading opposition activists in Poland presume that their
homes and telephones are bugged as a matter of routine, although
the government has said its use of eavesdropping devices is limited
and requires a court order.
   The Slupsk campaign offices were provided by provincial
authorities and are in the building of the Provincial Social and
Recreation Club. Wires from one listening device led to the club
director's office, said a Slupsk Citizens Commission spokeswoman,
Maria Skrowonska.
   The wire disappeared behind some paneling in the office, and
efforts were being made to remove the paneling and follow the wire,
said Mrs. Skrowonska.
   Moskwa said that the Slupsk committee asked the local
prosecutor's office to investigate, but it was turned down. The
national committee then complained Tuesday night at the Interior
Ministry in Warsaw. The ministry oversees the country's police
forces.
   ``We are going to protest officially, and we are also going to
lodge a complaint about being refused an official investigation,''
Moskwa said.
   The committee offices are directing local campaigns for the
Sejm, the existing unicameral parliament chamber, and the Senate,
which is to be the East bloc's first totally freely elected
legislative chamber.
   Under an agreement reached last month, the opposition is
competing for 35 percent, or 161 seats, in the 460-member Sejm, and
for all 100 of the Senate seats. Voting will be held in two stages
June 4 and June 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
