<DOCNO> AP890510-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     05-10 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leadership Offers Talks with Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party, faced with an
economic crisis and increasing pressure for more democracy, has
offered to hold talks with opposition groups to work out details of
next year's elections.
   The offer from the party's policy-making Central Committee came
Tuesday night after it stripped former leader Janos Kadar of his
last official posts and said he made mistakes that slowed
democratic and economic progress.
   Similar broad-based talks In Poland earlier this year resulted
in the legalization of Solidarity and a more democratic electoral
system.
   The state news agency MTI said in a statement outlining the
offer of negotiations that they would fix an exact date for the
first multiparty elections in Hungary since the communist takeover
in 1948. The talks would also determine rules and procedures for
the elections, expected in June 1990.
   MTI said the leadership would also negotiate over the exact role
of a new constitutional court and revised powers for the state
president.
   It is not the first time the communists have offered talks, but
the latest offer detailed a broader agenda of issues. The numerous
opposition groups have refused earlier offers for talks because the
agenda appeared to be limited and entirely controlled by the
dominant communists.
   The offer came before a parliamentary session opened today.
About 75 percent of the parliament deputies belong to the Communist
Party.
   The Central Committee offer followed its removal of Kadar from
the committee and the honorary post of party president. Kadar, 76,
rose to power behind the Soviet-led invasion of 1956 that crushed a
popular uprising for democracy.
   By stripping Kadar of the posts, the Central Committee appeared
to be trying to appease a public increasingly suspicious of the
role Kadar played in post-invasion repressions, including the
interrogation and execution of former premier and revolutionary
leader Imre Nagy.
   Kadar is rumored to be suffering from cancer. But Central
Committee secretary Gyoergy Fejti declined Tuesday at a news
conference to specify the nature of Kadar's illness.
   At the parliamentary session that opened today, lawmakers
considered a Cabinet shuffle proposed by Premier Miklos Nemeth.
According to Nemeth's plan, Gyula Horn is to take over foreign
affairs from Peter Varkonyi, who has been named ambassador to
Washington; Csaba Hutter, head of a farming cooperative, takes over
agriculture; and financial expert Laszlo Bekesi moves to finance.
   The new ministers, whose names were published two weeks ago, are
expected to strengthen recent reforms and assist Nemeth in an
economic overhaul he said he will present later this month.
   The foreign debt of $17 billion remains the largest per capita
in the East bloc. With inflation expected to top 20 percent this
year, workers who have shown little interest in political reform
are unhappy and even official trade unions are demanding the
government ease its austerity drive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Pollard 1stLd-Writethru a0543 05-10 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Pollard, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0543,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Hold Talks In Israel On Pollard Affair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to show team headed by assistant attorney general</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials traveled to Israel last week
for talks on several unresolved matters concerning the case of
convicted spy Jonathan J. Pollard, Israeli and American sources
said.
   The team was led by Assistant Attorney General Edward Dennis,
who heads the Justice Department's criminal division, and included
State Department representatives. It was accompanied by the No. 2
diplomat at the Israeli Embassy here, Oded Eran, said the sources,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The officials are trying to tie up loose ends remaining from the
affair, in which Pollard, an intelligence analyst for the U.S.
Navy, was convicted of selling thousands of secrets to Israel and
was sentenced in 1987 to life imprisonment. His wife, Anne
Henderson-Pollard, was sentenced to five years in prison as an
accessory after the fact.
   The officials are trying to tie up loose ends remaining from the
affair, in which Pollard, an intelligence analyst for the U.S.
Navy, was convicted of selling thousands of secrets to Israel and
was sentenced in 1987 to life imprisonment. His wife, Anne
Henderson-Pollard, was sentenced to five years in prison as an
accessory after the fact.
   It could not be learned whether the U.S. team managed to resolve
the outstanding problems, although one official said he doubted the
case was now closed. ``It's been going on for so long and so
slowly, I doubt this trip is the end of the matter,'' this source
said Tuesday.
   A top aide to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, Elyakim
Rubinstein, has held periodic talks in Washington in an effort to
close the case, which has been an embarrassment and strain for the
close ties between Israel and the United States.
   Last week's mission appears to be only the second time a U.S.
team has traveled to Israel to discuss the Pollard affair. The
first team went there in 1986 and was allowed to interview three of
Pollard's contacts who had worked at the Israeli Embassy and
consulate in Washington and New York.
   But the team, headed by former Justice Department prosecutor
Joseph DiGenova, claimed later the Israelis had not told them the
whole truth and had withheld information about the man who first
recruited Pollard in Washington, Aviem Sella.
   Sella was indicted here in 1987 and was forced to retire from
the Israeli air force because of U.S. pressure. The Justice
Department also threatened to revoke the immunity granted at the
time to the other three Israelis.
   U.S. officials also want Israel to return some of the documents
that Pollard supplied and which were not given back during the
initial phase of the investigation.
   Israel has contended the Pollard espionage operation was run by
Rafi Eitan, who headed an obscure Israeli defense bureau, without
authority from the government. It has apologized to the United
States but the affair continues to affect Israel's close
intelligence ties with the United States.
</TEXT>
