<FIRST>r w PM-McGillis-Shakespeare 1stLd-Writethru a0439 05-10 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McGillis-Shakespeare, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kelly McGillis Taking Holiday From Films to Play Shakespeare</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to read comedian instead comedienne to conform
with style; SUBS pvs 5th graf, She will, to correct to Friedrich sted Friedlich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frustrated by her Hollywood bosses, actress
Kelly McGillis is taking a holiday from her lucrative film career
and happily returning to the Shakespearean stage, where she'll play
some long-sought comedy roles.
   A comedian? Kelly McGillis? The gentle young Amish beauty whose
demure sensuality tempted Harrison Ford in ``Witness;'' the tough
district attorney in ``The Accused;'' the woman who had Tom Cruise
flying emotional barrel rolls in ``Top Gun?''
   ``I have good instincts and a good sense of timing,'' she says
quietly. ``I have a good sense of humor.''
   Miss McGillis will get her chance to display her comic talents
when she joins the acting company of the Shakespeare Theater at the
Folger for its four productions next season, which begins in
September.
   She will appear in two Shakespeare comedies, ``Twelfth Night''
and ``Merry Wives of Windsor,'' as well as ``The Tempest.'' She
also will play the title role in Friedrich von Schiller's tragic
drama, ``Mary Stuart.''
   She was interviewed over a late-morning breakfast at her hotel _
two poached eggs, whole wheat toast and cappuccino _ a few hours
before she attended the annual Helen Hayes Awards show Monday night
at the National Theater.
   She was nominated for _ but did not receive _ a best-actress
``Helen'' for her Portia in the Folger's production of ``Merchant
of Venice'' last year. The awards recognize outstanding
achievements in Washington's professional theater community.
   Miss McGillis is eagerly looking forward to her nine-month
sabbatical from the movie grind, partly because she'll be working
again with Michael Kahn, the Folger's artistic director. They first
met in 1979 when she was a drama student and he was a teacher at
the Juilliard School in New York.
   ``Michael knows my weaknesses and my strengths, and I think he
will push me to get better,'' she said.
   ``That's very difficult to find when you work in film, where you
only come together with a group of people for two or three months
and then you leave. With Michael there's a sense of continuity.
He's seen me and my work over the years.''
   She says she'll also enjoy staying close to her new husband,
California yacht broker Fred Tillman, whom she married last New
Year's Eve. They plan to live in a small rooming house near the
Folger with the nine other members of the theater's acting company.
   What are her strengths?
   ``Probably commitment, thoroughness and, I think, the ability to
work with other people. ... I really am an artist who truly
believes that what I do cannot be done without other people.
Theater is a communal art. We all need one another on that stage or
in that film.''
   Her biggest weakness? ``Confidence,'' she replies with a low
chuckle. She doesn't look insecure, she's told. ``Ah, but you don't
know me,'' she replies. ``I may be 5 foot 10 but inside I'm only 5
foot 1.''
   Miss McGillis says she is drawn to ``the poetry, the beauty of
language, the sense of period and style'' in Shakespeare's plays,
for which she was trained at Juilliard. She readily acknowledges
that her string of screen hits has made her wealthy enough to
afford the luxury of a low-paid season on the Folger stage.
   At 31, she can boast nearly a dozen movies plus an occasional
stage appearance. She refuses to be type-cast as the new Grace
Kelly, and says she plays ``a very unwholesome type of woman'' in
her latest film, ``Cat Chaser.''
   She complains, though, that Hollywood's play-it-safe producers
aren't willing to take a multimillion-dollar gamble and cast her in
comedies or classical drama. So her stint at the Folger, she says,
will ``really be a challenge and push me forward in a way that I
haven't allowed to do in films.''
   In her days as a single actress, Miss McGillis seduced Harrison
Ford in ``Witness'' with a convincing display of sexual fireworks.
Did she feel the same way when the cameras weren't rolling? she was
asked.
   ``He's not my type,'' she replied. ``Harrison's a nice man. I
don't look at him as a sex symbol. I look at him as an actor. He's
very charming, and he's very delightful to work with.''
   Did she ever have a crush on any leading man?
   ``Yes, I have, but I won't tell you which ones,'' she said,
laughing. ``It's none of your business.''
</TEXT>
