</TEXT>
<NOTE>PM-Radar Blocked,0366</NOTE>
<NOTE>Hotel Interferes with Airport Radar in Maine</NOTE>
<NOTE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-story hotel going up closer to the
airport than expected because of a typographical error is
interfering with traffic controllers' radar, but a federal official
says flights are in no danger.
   The Federal Aviation Administration today sent a jet full of
computer equipment to fly around the Portland International JetPort
to find the gaps in coverage caused by the Quality Suites.
   ``We considered it urgent,'' FAA spokesman Michael Ciccarelli
said this morning, a day after 16 controllers brought the gaps to
the FAA's attention.
   The FAA blamed the problem on an error in plans submitted by the
hotel developers to the FAA for approval.
   ``They showed it 12,000 feet from the runway. It was actually
1,170 feet,'' said Jim Lucas, manager of the FAA's New England air
traffic division.
   However, Lucas said the airport is safe and that air traffic
routes could be changed if a serious enough problem is detected.
``I think any time we lose radar coverage, it's a problem, but we
have the ability to procedurally work around it,'' he said.
   The situation might be corrected by moving the radar, said
Cheryl Readio, local president of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association.
   ``I don't think they'll knock down the hotel,'' she said.
``Somebody already goofed and allowed the hotel to be built.''
   She said local flights could fall out of the radar's sight, as
could planes coming in from Boston if they are flying under 6,000
feet.
   A spokesman for the air traffic controllers' union in Washington
characterized the gaps as serious.
   ``If you can imagine the radar, all of a sudden a big slice of
pie becomes dead,'' Tony Dresden said. ``They're starting to lose
things. It's about eight miles, which is a big chunk of space.''
   Dunfey Properties Inc. President Bob Dunfey Jr. said Tuesday the
hotel is being built according to plans signed by the FAA, and
Ciccarelli said the error was an ``innocent mistake.''
   ``We're not pointing the finger at anyone,'' he said.
</TEXT>
