<FIRST>r i PM-China-Vietnam 1stLd-Writethru a0528 05-10 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>China, Vietnam End Talks on Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Xinhua reporting no progress.
Pickup 6th pvs, ``The sources ...'' DELETES grafs 14 and 15 to conform.
Pickup 16th, ``Vietnam's invasion ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China and Vietnam, backers of rival forces in the
Cambodian war, failed to make progress at talks to end the
10-year-old war, the official Xinhua News Agency reported today.
   Three days of talks between Vietnam's Deputy Foreign Minister
Dinh Nho Liem and his Chinese counterpart, Liu Shuqing, ended today.
   ``We had hoped for some progress toward a fair and reasonable
settlement of the Cambodian issue and it's a pity that the
consultations have made no progress and achieved no
understanding,'' the agency quoted Chinese Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen as saying.
   Qian, who also met Dinh, said China's relations with Vietnam
will improve only after the Cambodian conflict is resolved.
   Vietnamese sources said the talks ``contributed to mutual
understanding.''
   Relations have been strained since China launched a 20-day
border war against Vietnam in early 1979 to punish Hanoi for its
invasion of Cambodia.
   China is the main backer of the anti-Vietnamese resistance
battling Vietnamese troops and forces of the Hun Sen government
Hanoi installed in Phnom Penh.
   The sources said the two sides agreed on previous positions that
China will stop aid to the resistance after Vietnam withdraws its
estimated 50,000 to 70,000 troops from Cambodia.
   Hanoi has said it will pull out all troops by the end of
September.
   The sources also reiterated their broad agreement on the need
for international supervision of the withdrawal, that the future
government in Cambodia should be non-aligned and neutral and that
an international conference on Cambodia be convened as soon as
possible.
   The two sides still differed on the composition of a proposed
coalition government to be formed after the Vietnamese depart, the
sources said.
   The resistance, led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, has called for
the Hun Sen government to be dismantled before a coalition is
formed, an idea rejected by Vietnam and Phnom Penh.
   Vietnam also has refused to accept Sihanouk's call for U.N.
supervision of the troop withdrawal.
   The meeting was the second following a secret visit by Dinh to
Beijing in January for the first high-level contacts between the
two countries in more than nine years.
   Both sides agreed today the consultations should continue, but
did not set a date for the next meeting.
   Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia ended the brutal regime of the
Khmer Rouge, which in its campaign to turn the country into an
agrarian commune caused the deaths of hundreds of thousands of
people through execution and starvation.
   The Dinh visit comes just one week before Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev arrives in Beijing for the first Sino-Soviet summit in
30 years. China is critical of the Soviet Union for supporting
Vietnam's military presence in Cambodia, and the Cambodian question
is expected to be discussed in detail during Gorbachev's visit.
</TEXT>
