<HEAD>Palestinian Reported Killed; Army Accused of Harassing Medical Crews</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with spokesman saying Shamir stumbled
at home and hit his head. Pickup 6th pvs, `Earlier, Shamir...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot to death a Palestinian in the
occupied lands today, Arab reports said. U.N. officials accused
troopers of harassing medical crews trying to evacuate wounded
Palestinians during weekend clashes.
   The West Bank and Gaza Strip were sealed for the third day to
prevent violence as Israel celebrated the 41st anniversary of its
founding.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was hospitalized for medical tests
after complaining of weakness, spokesman Yossi Ahimeir said.
Ahimeir said Shamir stumbled and hit his head at his home Tuesday
night.
   ``He felt weakness a little bit, and his doctors decided he
should be hospitalized for checks,'' Ahimeir said. ``There appears
to be nothing serious.''
   Shamir made several public appearances today before he was taken
to a Jerusalem hospital at about noon, Ahimeir said. Shamir, 73,
has attended more than a half-dozen events since Tuesday night to
mark the Israeli holiday.
   Earlier, Shamir said only Palestinians who do not insist on
eventual creation of a Palestinian state will be acceptable
negotiating partners with Israel.
   Shamir has called for elections in the occupied lands to choose
representatives who would negotiate an interim arrangement with
Israel on limited Palestinian self-rule.
   ``We can't talk with the PLO because their minimum demand is a
Palestinian state. We can't agree to this,'' Shamir told Israel
radio. ``Therefore we have to talk to people who are interested in
a solution ... those who don't insist on this minimum demand for a
Palestinian state.''
   The PLO and leading Palestinians have rejected Shamir's plan.
   According to Arab reports, the worst violence today was in the
West Bank town of Ramallah, where troops opened fire to disperse
about 200 Palestinians throwing stones.
   A 17-year-old Palestinian, identified as Mahoud Sami Abdul
Ranni, arrived dead at Ramallah Hospital with a gunshot wound in
the chest, hospital officials said. One youth was wounded in the
clash.
   The death brought to 468 the number of Palestinians killed in
the 17-month-old uprising against Israeli rule of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip. Twenty-one Israelis have died.
   In the Gaza Strip, four Palestinians were wounded by army
gunfire in clashes in Gaza City and the Nuseirat refugee camp,
hospital officials said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   The army maintained a curfew on the Gaza Strip, confining
700,000 Palestinians to their homes. About 200,000 West Bank
residents were also under curfew, and all 1 million West Bank Arabs
were barred from entering Israel for the holiday marking the
anniversary of Israel's establishment on May 14, 1948.
   The U.N. Relief and Works Agency, meanwhile, complained to the
army that soldiers hampered the work of its medical crews Saturday
when troops fatally shot three Palestinians and wounded dozens of
others in the Gaza Strip.
   ``There have been problems with (stopping) ambulances from time
to time, but we have never had so many incidents as on Saturday,''
said a Western U.N. official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In a statement issued in Vienna, the agency said ``ambulances
carrying injured persons were repeatedly stopped and searched by
the Israeli military.''
   Army officials said they could not immediately comment on the
report by the agency. The agency was set up in 1949 to care for
Palestinians made refugees at the founding of Israel.
</TEXT>
