<HEAD>Prime Minister Hospitalized for Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Shamir hit his head after
stumbling in the darkness in his home. Pickup 4th graf, ``Shamir, 73 ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was hospitalized
for medical tests today after he stumbled and hit his head at home
and complained of weakness, his spokesman said.
   Shamir was taken to Hadassah Hospital at about noon, said Shamir
spokesman Yossi Ahimeir.
   Shamir walked into a piece of furniture in his Jerusalem home on
Tuesday night, and ``in the darkness, he hit his head,'' Ahimeir
said.
   Shamir today ``felt weakness a little bit, and his doctors
decided he should be hospitalized for checks,'' Ahimeir said.
``There appears to be nothing serious.''
   Ahimeir said he expected Shamir to be released later today or
Thursday.
   A hospital security guard barred an Associated Press reporter
from entering the hospital, saying the hospital spokeswoman was not
in her office. The spokeswoman's home telephone went unanswered.
   Shamir, 73, has been at more than a half dozen events since
Tuesday night to mark two successive Israeli holidays, Memorial Day
and Independence Day.
   Earlier today, he visited an immigrant center at Mevasseret Zion
on the outskirts of Jerusalem and attended the annual Bible Quiz in
Jerusalem.
   He has been at the center of political debates for several
months as the government works out a peace proposal that it hopes
will quiet the 17-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Ahimeir said Shamir has no past history of major medical
problems. ``He is absolutely healthy,'' he said.
   The Polish-born Shamir, who is head of the right-wing Likud
bloc, first became prime minister in 1983 after Prime Minister
Menachem Begin resigned.
   Shamir was succeeded in 1984 by his political rival, Labor Party
leader Shimon Peres, but in a rotation agreement between the two
parties resumed power in 1986. He was re-elected to head the
coalition government in November.
