<TEXT>
   May 9
   The Union Leader, Manchester, N.H., on Bush's first 100 days:
   We are still waiting to discover his basic agenda and the path
on which (President Bush) plans to lead the country.
   In the meanwhile in Washington, committees and departments sit
and twiddle their thumbs awaiting direction because the president
has not yet provided the map.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 8
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer on flight attendants' work periods:
   This week a House subcommittee will hold hearings on a topic
that ought to interest every airline passenger: the length of work
periods required of airline flight attendants.
   A bill sponsored by Rep. Norman Y. Mineta, D-Calif., would set
limits on the number of consecutive hours flight attendants must
work.
   As it now stands, flight attendants are the only crew members
not covered by Federal Aviation Administration regulations to limit
work hours, and they have been known to be required to work 24-hour
shifts. Since the FAA requires the flight attendants to be aboard
for safety reasons, the rationale for this oversight is hard to
figure.
   In an emergency, passengers depend for their safety on the
alertness and quick response of cabin attendants. A cabin attendant
who is exhausted from long flights and quick turnarounds with no
rest break is a potential safety hazard to passengers. ...
   Protecting flight attendants from exploitation that hampers
their performance is public interest legislation that deserves
speedy enactment.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 8
   Sun-Sentinel, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on discrimination at work:
   All too often, laws that are supposed to protect persons from
sex, race or age bias in employment fail to do so in all but the
most blatant and outrageous circumstances.
   On Monday (May 1), the U.S. Supreme Court made it easier for
persons to pursue and prove charges of discrimination.
   The court's decision is an excellent refinement of job
discrimination laws and reflects the original intent of Congress
that all workers be treated and judged according to the same
standards.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 9
   The Wichita (Kan.) Eagle-Beacon on crack's impact on children:
   When children's advocate David Liederman addressed members of
the Kansas Children's Service League last week, he emphasized the
dire consequences to children and families that result from drug
abuse, particularly crack cocaine.
   The strong correlation between substance abuse _ especially
crack _ and escalating rates of child abuse and neglect is
convincing and deeply troubling.
   Current federal priorities, sadly, help assure that children who
don't even smoke crack will remain its front-line victims. ...
   The federal government, if it is truly serious about the war on
drugs, must devote more spending on programs that help
drug-afflicted children and families. Without assistance from a
benevolent government, children of crack addicts may well consider
themselves America's unloved and unwanted.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 4
   The Daily Astorian, Astoria, Ore., on the spotted owl
controversy:
   For anyone who has followed Northwest timber politics for more
than a few years the current hullabaloo over the northern spotted
owl has a familiar ring. ... We have heard these kinds of
prophecies of doom before.
   The likelihood that the Fish and Wildlife Service will list the
owl as a threatened species has given license to industry's hit
men. ...
   The aspect of the timber industry's grumbling that gets a little
tiresome is the implicit attitude that everyone else must give way
in favor of its economic demands. That attitude becomes especially
galling when you review the industry's historically favored
position in the federal tax code or its subsidies. ...
   It is no secret that a number of companies have overcut their
Northwest lands. ...
   The industry has already sent more than 60 times as many raw
logs overseas to be cut by Japanese and other foreign sawmills as
are in jeopardy because of the spotted owl.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 4
   North Jersey Herald and News, Passaic, N.J., on Pete Rose:
   At first, the charges seem pretty serious.
   Baseball's Pete Rose, manager of the Cincinnati Reds and future
Hall of Famer, gambled on baseball, maybe even his own team. He
cheated the Internal Revenue Service of earnings from gambling.
He's broke from gambling debts.
   Or so they said.
   New speculation sprouts daily. Many want Rose to quit his job
and leave baseball.
   But after 10 weeks or more of investigation by the IRS and
baseball Commissioner A. Bartlett Giamatti, the goods to nail Pete
Rose are still missing. Nothing's happened, except for a very
public trial by innuendo.
   If there's evidence linking Rose to illegal gambling, it should
be disclosed, pronto. If there's no case against the man, he
deserves public vindication _ and apologies _ from his accusers.
</TEXT>
