<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Boatner     05-10 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Boatner,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Member of the Ink Spots Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELMONT, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Boatner, a later member of the
singing quartet the Ink Spots, has died at the age of 70.
   Boatner died Monday in Lakes Region General Hospital in Laconia
after a brief illness.
   Boatner joined the soft rhythm 'n' blues quartet in 1952, after
the group reached its heyday in the 1930s and '40s. All four of its
original members are dead, but Boatner once said, ``I'm the closest
you get to an original.''
   The original group, considered one of the early influences on
rock 'n' roll, was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in
January. They made their fame with songs like ``Java Jive'' and
``If I Didn't Care.''
   Born in Lovejoy, Ill., Boatner graduated from the Conservatory
of Music in Cleveland.
   He once said his ambition had been to be a doctor. ``I sought
admission to two black medical schools, but both were filled. Due
to segregated practices back then, I couldn't get into the white
schools,'' he said.
   Survivors include his wife, a daughter, a stepson and
stepdaughter, and five grandchildren.
</TEXT>
