<FIRST>u i PM-WHO-PLO     05-10 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WHO-PLO,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>WHO Postpones Vote on PLO Membership Until Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual assembly of the World Health
Organization today put off for 48 hours a decision on the PLO's
controversial bid to be admitted as a state member of the
166-nation U.N. body.
   Failure by the Arab countries to obtain an immediate vote
boosted hopes of those favoring a compromise to head off a showdown
with the United States.
   Washington has threatened to stop all financial support to any
U.N. agency that grants full membership to the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which now is a non-voting observer in the United
Nations.
   The United States made that threat even though it reveresed a
longstanding policy earlier this year and opened talks with the PLO
after it's chairman, Yasser Arafat, recognized Israel's right to
exist.
   On Friday, the WHO annual assembly will vote on two rival draft
resolutions:
   One, co-sponsored by all 21 Arab countries, would ``admit the
State of Palestine'' as a member of the 166-nation organization.
   The other, backed by nine Western and Third World states, would
combine deferring the issue until the 1990 assembly with calls for
increased assistance to residents of the Israeli-occupied Gaza
Strip and West Bank.
   An Austrian motion to adjourn the debate until Friday, seconded
by Canada, was carried by 56-47 votes with 20 abstentions. Bahrain,
seconded by Libya, opposed adjourning.
   The Western and Third World resolution invites the assembly to
express the hope ``that the Palestinian people will be fully
represented within the WHO by their legitimate representatives.''
   That language apparently is addressed at developing countries
that sympathize with the PLO but are worried by WHO
Director-General Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima's warning that a cutoff of
U.S. funds would ``completely destroy the agency.'' The United
States funds a quarter of the organization's budget and this year
contributed $71 million.
   WHO plays a vital role in assisting governments worldwide to
strengthen their health services and advance work to eradicate
diseases, such as AIDS, and to promote health care and nutrition.
   Washington and its Western allies say the PLO-declared ``State
of Palestine'' does not fulfill internationally accepted criteria
of statehood, including control of a defined territory.
   U.S. Secretary of State James Baker III also has says PLO
admission would harm the Middle East peace process and the entire
U.N. system.
   But the PLO seems determined to push its bid throughout the U.N.
system, with support of nearly 100 of the 159 member states that
have recognized the State of Palestine or acknowledged its
proclamation.
   On Tuesday, the PLO announced in Paris that it will seek
admission to three more U.N. bodies: the Paris-based U.N.
Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization, the Rome-based
Food and Agriculture Organization, and the Geneva-based
International Labor Organization.
   The International Labor Organization probably will be the next
target because its annual conference opens June 7. Admission,
however, would require a two-thirds majority while a simple
majority suffices in the WHO assembly.
   The United States, which withdrew from the International Labor
Organization from 1977 to 1980 to protest what it charged was
growing politicization, pays one-fourth of its budget of $357
million for fiscal 1988-89.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
