<DOCNO> AP890510-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Refuseniks     05-10 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group of Soviet Jews Calls for Preserving Jackson-Vanik Amendment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baker, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police broke up a demonstration today by about 40
Soviet Jews calling on the United States to keep denying
most-favored-nation trading status to the Soviet Union as long as
limits on emigration remain.
   The half-hour protest outside Moscow's International Trade
Center came on the first day of Secretary of State James Baker's
visit to Moscow, and at least four of the demonstrators were to
meet later in the evening with Baker at the U.S. Embassy, protest
organizer Yuri Semenovsky said.
   Many in the group, which stood on the pedestal of a statue of
Mercury, the Roman god of trade, carried banners calling on the
U.S. government to maintain the 1972 Jackson-Vanik amendment. The
measure bars trade concessions to communist states unless the
president can state that he has received assurances that emigration
will be liberalized.
   ``I wait for permission to leave the U.S.S.R. for 10 years,''
another protest sign read. ``Mr. Vanik, we are still here!'' said
another.
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union rose in April to its
highest level since 1979, with 4,129 Soviet Jews allowed to leave,
according to the Geneva-based Intergovernmental Committee for
Migration, which helps emigres resettle.
   Charles Vanik, no longer in Congress, called May 4 for waiving
the restrictions he had co-sponsored for one year, saying such
action would encourage further human rights improvements in the
Soviet Union under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. But Semenovsky
claimed it was misleading to look only at the emigration figures.
   ``The Soviets say only 1 percent to 3 percent of those who want
to leave are refused permission'' he said. ``But that's only the
tip of the iceberg. Many others want to leave but are afraid to
apply, or the government will not accept their applications.''
   Semenovsky, leader of a refusenik group called ``Poor
Relatives,'' said the Jackson-Vanik amendment should not be
repealed until the Soviet Union passes a law allowing anyone who
wants to to emigrate. He claimed that 100,000 people were refused
permission last year.
   Uniformed police and KGB agents in plainclothes surrounded the
protesters and forced them off the statue's pedestal after a local
government official announced through a bullhorn that the
demonstration was illegal.
   Although police placed their hands on some protesters' shoulders
to make them leave, there were no arrests or violence.
</TEXT>
