<FIRST>r w AM-FarmScene     05-10 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Scene,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crops Suffer from Drought in Some Areas, Too Much Rain in Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some farmers are stuck in the mud, others wish
it would rain enough to create some muddy fields.
   Crops continued to suffer in major areas of the Great Plains
while too much rain slowed spring planting in the eastern Corn Belt
and the Southeast, the government's Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility reported Tuesday.
   Nationally, winter wheat was in mostly fair-to-poor condition
during the week of May 1-7, although the Great Plains crop was
rated below that. In the Pacific Northwest, Corn Belt and
Southeast, winter wheat was in ``mostly good to fair'' shape.
   The report said 89 percent of the winter wheat crop in Kansas
was in very poor or poor condition ``and continued to deteriorate
due to lack of moisture'' during the week.
   But ``cool, wet weather reduced crop stress in Oklahoma,'' where
wheat was reported in mostly fair condition. Lack of moisture
continued to hurt the crop in Colorado and Nebraska.
   Harvesting of the 1989 winter wheat crop has begun in southern
Texas and will gradually move north. The Agriculture Department
will issue its first official estimate of this year's production on
Thursday.
   Meanwhile, the facility, which is operated jointly by USDA and
the Commerce Department, said corn planting nationally was about 43
percent completed, eight percentage points behind normal for this
time of year.
   ``Lack of moisture has slowed germination and emergency (of
corn) in Kansas,'' the report said. ``Rain continued to slow
planting in the eastern Corn Belt and the Southeast.''
   Corn planting was 42 percentage points behind in Ohio and 25
points behind in Indiana, the report said, while planting trailed
the usual pace by 34 percentage points in North Carolina.
   Only about 5 percent of the soybean crop had been planted, four
percentage points behind the normal pace, although planting was
under way in all major soybean states except Minnesota and North
Carolina.
   Cotton planting was 42 percent completed, only one percentage
point behind normal.
   Sorghum planting was reported 23 percent completed, one point
ahead of normal. Rice seeding was 71 percent completed, six
percentage points ahead of the normal pace.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has put federally
inspected poultry and hog slaughtering plants in Arkansas under
``intensified surveillance'' for traces of the cancer-causing
pesticide heptachlor.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said Tuesday the agency may ``expand
testing into surrounding states'' over the next few weeks. The
stepped-up program for heptachlor in Arkansas began on Monday, he
said.
   The USDA agency has been monitoring Arkansas slaughter plants
since January for traces of heptachlor after finding contaminated
poultry at Townsends of Arkansas in Batesville, he said.
   ``We also began surveillance testing in other poultry and
red-meat slaughtering plants in Arkansas to determine if the
heptachlor problem extended beyond Townsends,'' Crawford said.
``Regrettably, we found additional problems.''
   One hog tested positive for heptachlor at unacceptable levels,
and two others showed traces of the chemical. Meanwhile, he said,
the Food and Drug Administration reported unacceptable heptachlor
levels in non-commerial egg samples.
   Contaminated feed is the suspected cause, although the FDA has
not been able to determine the specific source. At least four feed
mills have been under investigation.
   Crawford said his agency will inform the FDA ``whenever actual
or potential violations are detected through our testing.''
Meanwhile, the FDA will attempt to determine who bought the
contaminated feed. After that, Crawford said his inspectors will
test animals from those producers.
   ``The problems occurring with heptachlor are disturbing,'' he
said. ``Heptachlor has been shown to induce tumors in mice. In
1978, the Environmental Protection Agency banned heptachlor for all
agricultural uses except as a seed treatment, but it is apparent
from the problems we're finding now that residues from treated seed
persist in food animals.''
   Crawford said the problem will not be resolved until the
practice of using chemically treated seed as animal feed is
stopped. ``We are very encouraged by the EPA announcement that they
will ban the future use of heptachlor on treated seed,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Agriculture Department talks about an
underground spy camera, the camera really is under the ground _ six
feet or so under.
   Dan R. Upchurch of the department's Agricultural Research
Service says he'd ``rather poke a camera in the ground than dig
down six feet or so and pull out a plant, roots and all.''
   Upchurch, a soil scientist at the agency's research facility in
Lubbock, Texas, showed some of underground videos at an annual
symposium this week at Beltsville, Md.
   Another alternative to pulling out plants, roots and all, is to
use a rhizotron, a room-sized cellar with glass observation windows
_ just as zoo and marine aquarium visitors view underwater life.
   Upchurch's version is a minirhizotron, which uses a portable
color video system that lets scientists watch roots develop over an
entire growing season. A clear plastic tube is inserted in the soil
and a pocket-sized video camera is lowered. The researchers watch
roots on a television monitor.
   The roots are seen about 25 times actual size, depending on the
monitor, he said. Through time-lapse photography, drought-stricken
roots are seen to break up as the soil shrinks.
</TEXT>
