<FIRST>r a PM-CubanArtSeizure     05-10 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuban Art Seizure,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Seizes Cuban Art Allegedly Smuggled By USIA Worker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publicity about a Cuban art auction in Miami sent
investigators on a trail that led to the former spokesman for the
U.S. government in Havana, according to court papers accusing him
of smuggling.
   Although no charges have been filed, the Customs Service on
Tuesday said U.S. Information Agency employee Jerry W. Scott
brought the Cuban paintings into the United States in violation of
the Cuban trade embargo.
   Records and the paintings have been seized from a Miami art
dealer, Ramon Cernuda, said Diane Cossin, spokeswoman for U.S.
Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   ``We have a lot of documents, records and other evidence to go
over,'' Ms. Cossin said Tuesday. ``It's not over yet by any means.''
   Customs agent Peter D. Liston said in court papers that Scott
brought 40 paintings into Miami International Airport in February
1988 and failed to declare them. He later acknowledged turning over
the paintings to Cernuda, the agent said.
   Customs began its investigation following publicity about an
April 1988 auction at the Cuban Museum of Art and Culture in Miami.
The auction involved Cernuda-owned Cuban paintings, Liston said.
   U.S. law has prohibited virtually all commerce with Cuba since
1963. Violators can face up to 10 years in prison and $250,000 in
fines.
   Scott worked for USIA as spokesman for the U.S. Interests
Section. The United States has no formal relations with Cuba but
maintains the Interests Section to handle such things as visas and
routine legal transactions.
   USIA spokesman William Reinckens said no disciplinary action was
planned. He would not discuss the case against Scott, who now works
in Washington.
</TEXT>
