<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Avalanches     05-10 0095</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Avalanches,0097</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll Falls in Dry Swiss Alps Winter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVOS, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of avalanche deaths in the
Swiss Alps fell to 13 last winter as a drought helped keep the toll
the lowest in 29 years, an official said Wednesday.
   The deaths were down from 25 the previous winter, said Paul
Foehn, an expert at the Federal Institute for Snow and Avalanche
Research. Most victims were skiers or other winter sports
enthusiasts, he said.
   Last season brought the lowest number of victims since
snowslides killed six people in winter 1959-60.
