<FIRST>r a PM-Avon-Amway     05-10 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Amway,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway Knocking At Avon's Door</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. today said it received a
$39-a-share cash takeover offer from its smaller rival in the
door-to-door sales business, Amway Corp.
   Amway's bid places a value of about $2.1 billion on Avon, based
on nearly 54 million outstanding common shares. The value would be
higher if it included 18 million shares of preferred Avon stock in
investors' hands.
   Avon was up $2.62{ a share to $38.62{ at midday on the New York
Stock Exchange following the announcement.
   Avon, a cosmetics, toiletries and household products company
with sales last year of $3.06 billion, has said it is not for sale
and has taken legal action to discourage takeover interest by Amway
and Amway partner Irwin Jacobs.
   The partnership of Ada, Mich.-based Amway and Jacobs, a
Minneapolis investor, previously disclosed it held 10.3 percent of
Avon's common stock and might attempt to get control of the company.
   In an effort to block a bid, Avon sued in federal court,
accusing the partnership of not complying with securities
disclosure requirements.
   Amway is a privately held consumer and household products
company.
