<FIRST>r w PM-PublicHousing 1stLd-Writethru a0437 05-10 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Public Housing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Presents Plan for Fighting Drugs in Public Housing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 6 grafs to include fresh quotes from Kemp testimony;
pick ups pvs 5th graf, Green said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp said today that
fighting drugs in public housing rank in importance with repair and
modernization of units, as hundreds of residents gathered outside
the White House to protest the lack of federal money for
construction and rehabilitation.
   Kemp also said that if given flexibility in allocating the
Department of Housing and Urban Development's public housing budget
and additional money specifically earmarked for anti-drug efforts
he could make ``a significant attack'' on the problem.
   ``The anti-drug effort in public housing is as important a part
of modernization and rehabilitation in public housing as anything
else,'' he told the Senate's Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigations.
   Housing officials and tenants from Chicago, New York,
Washington, D.C. and Delaware joined Kemp to discuss federal
anti-drug efforts in public housing at the hearing.
   Meanwhile, members of the National Tenants Organization gathered
for a rally in Lafayette Park across from the White House.
   ``We're asking HUD to make emergency money available for an
immediate rehabilitation program for all boarded-up public
housing,'' Maxine Green, NTO's chairwoman, said in advance of the
rally.
   Green said her group is concerned with recent estimates that
70,000 units of public housing lie idle and in disrepair.
   ``We talked about drugs years ago and no one wanted to address
that because they felt it only touched poor people,'' said the Ft.
Pierce, Fla., resident.
   Drug abuse and trafficking in public housing have been key
issues for Kemp since he witnessed drug sales while touring
developments in several major cities in February.
   In March, Kemp waived HUD administrative appeals procedures to
allow public housing officials in Virginia to speed evictions of
suspected drug dealers. The secretary said he would extend the
exemption to other housing authorities that could demonstrate state
and local laws would provide due process to tenants facing eviction.
   Last month the secretary outlined a series of anti-drug actions
_ issuance of photo tenant identification cards, installation of
security fences around projects and increased police patrols _
available to local public housing authorities.
   But Green said, ``Mr. Kemp was not appointed drug czar,'' and
the responsibility of dealing with the nation's housing problems is
too great for Kemp to take on the added duties of fighting drugs.
She also said NTO has requested that Kemp appoint a committee of
representatives from NTO, HUD, Congress and city officials to work
with federal drug czar William Bennett.
   ``It is within the secretary's responsibility to make sure that
public housing is decent, livable and safe,'' said Mary Brunette,
Kemp's special assistant.
   ``I think that although Kemp's drug initiative in public housing
is important, the real issue is in building more housing and
maintaining the housing stock that we have left after the Reagan
years,'' said Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., who was to deliver the
keynote address at the rally marking the tenant group's tenth
annual ``Save Public Housing Day.''
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Select
Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, said he sees no conflict
between the NTO and the secretary because both want to preserve
public housing.
   Rangel, who was also to appear at the rally, said he hadn't seen
Kemp's proposals and while he wants to ensure tenants are afforded
due process in any eviction procedure, he was adamant about
punishment.
   ``When apartments are used for the packaging, processing and
sale of drugs that apartment should not be available to those
people,'' Rangel said. ``They should be in public housing of
another kind, jails.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
