<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Swiss-Tunnels     05-10 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swiss-Tunnels,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Backs $4.5 Billion Rail Link Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Wednesday its
support for a $4.5 billion rail link to handle an anticipated
increase in commercial trans-Alpine traffic in the next 20 years.
   The plans call for a new 31-mile tunnel through the Gotthard
Massif in central Switzerland, which would run below the
107-year-old, 9.3-mile link. The tunnel, estimated to be completed
by the year 2005, would match the length of the channel tunnel
between Britain and France planned for 1993.
   The old Gotthard tunnel handles more than four-fifths of the
rail freight passing through Switzerland but won't be able to cope
with an increase in traffic expected after the unified European
Economic Community market after 1992.
   The project also envisions a new 17.6-mile tunnel through Mount
Loetschberg connecting the Bern region with western Switzerland and
Italy. That link could be finished by 1997.
   Parliament is expected to take up the project next winter. If
100,000 people sign petitions against the plan, it would be put to
a nationwide vote.
   Switzerland has about 680 railway tunnels through its mountains.
It also has about 40 road tunnels, including the world's longest _
10.1 miles _ also piercing the Gotthard Massif.
</TEXT>
