<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     05-10 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says He's Willing to Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon said
Wednesday he is willing to bow to opposition demands to resign if
he is held responsible for mishandling state affairs such as the
wave of political violence.
   But the leader of President Roh Tae-woo's 22-member Cabinet
reiterated his government's determination to crush leftist radical
groups.
   ``The government will not sit idle when campuses are becoming
firebomb-manufacturing factories. Neither will we allow them to
become the bases of violence,'' Kang told the National Assembly.
   ``Also, I am willing to resign if held responsible for any state
affairs that have been mishandled,'' he said.
   Opposition members used the session to launch an offensive
against Roh's government, demanding Kang and all Cabinet ministers
resign for failing to provide effective leadership.
   Dissenting legislators charged the government is blocking
democratic reform and using a crackdown on violent protests to
suppress all its opponents. They accused the government of
provoking unrest.
   The opposition-controlled assembly can pass a resolution calling
on the Cabinet to resign, but the administration is not obliged by
law to honor such a motion. Opposition legislators did not call for
Roh's resignation.
   Answering their charges, Kang said diss and undermine the
Seoul government. The two nations have been bitter rivals since
1945.
   The government stepped up its crackdown after six riot policemen
were killed in a May 3 clash with radical students in southern
Pusan city.
   Roh warned he would invoke emergency powers to end violent
protests.
   Justice Minister Huh Hyung-koo, testifying in parliament
Wednesday, said 234 radical students, workers and dissidents have
been arrested since last month. Police are hunting for 76 more
radicals, he said.
   The ruling Democratic Justice Party is trying to ban firebombs,
a major radical weapon in anti-government protests, and increase
prison sentences for using them from the existing three years to
seven years.
   Opposition leaders have agreed in principle to adopt the
anti-firebomb bill, but they contend the government also must limit
police use of tear gas, which they say is excessive and tends to
aggravate violence.
   Radical students and the anti-government dissident groups have
little support because of their violent tactics and extreme
political views. The radicals want a leftist state ruled by workers
and farmers.
</TEXT>
