<FIRST>r w AM-US-Philippines     05-10 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Philippines,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Expresses U.S. Resolve to Help Philippine Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assassination of Army Col. James N. Rowe
in the Philippines last month will not keep the United States from
helping the Philippine government or from using its military bases
in that country, said a resolution endorsed Wednesday by a House
committee.
   The communist New Peoples Army has declared responsibility for
the April 21 fatal shooting of Rowe, chief U.S. ground forces
military adviser in the Philippines, while he was en route to his
office in suburban Manila.
   ``The Congress categorically rejects any attempts by the New
Peoples Army, whether through assasinations or through other
methods of violence or intimidation, to force the United States to
withdraw from mililtary facilities in the Philippines or to end its
support for the democratically elected government of the
Philippines,'' declared the resolution approved by voice vote of
the subcommittee on Asian and Pacific affairs. It was sent to the
full Foreign Affairs Committee.
   The subcommittee chairman, Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y.,
sponsored the resolution, which also says that ``the United States
should continue to provide economic and military assistance to the
Philippines in order to facilitate efforts by the government of the
Philippines to consolidate democracy, address ... underlying
economic problems and combat the New Peoples Army insurgency.''
   The resolution also contained authority to give the Philippine
government two surplus Navy vessels, a tug and a floating drydock.
</TEXT>
