<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CannibalismDig     05-10 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibalism Dig,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dig They Must to Find Who Cannibalized Whom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of forensic scientists plans to dig
into a Colorado grave and perhaps settle the century-old questions
surrounding Alfred _ or is it Alferd? _ Packer, to wit: Who killed
whom and who ate whom?
   Packer, a gold prospector and Union Army veteran, has stood
accused in history of killing five fellow prospectors and eating
the flesh of some of them.
   He confessed to killing only one, but said he did it in
self-defense and admitted to cannibalism, but only in the interest
of self-preservation.
   Much is not known about him for certain, including his first
name. It is ``Alfred'' in some court documents _ he signed a
confession that way and some letters to the parole board, and his
death certificate reads ``Alfred'' _ but it was ``Alferd'' in a
tattoo he wore and on some other documents he'd signed. At his
trial, he referred to himself pretty consistently as ``Packer.''
   To demonstrate how much can be learned when the sciences of
anthropology team up with pathology and archeology in solving
crimes, James Starrs, professor of law and forensic science at
George Washington University's National Law Center, plans to lead
an expedition in July to the prospectors' joint grave near Lake
City, Colo.
   The experts think they can determine the extent of which
cannibalism was committed by looking for bone scrapes that would
likely occur.
   If they find evidence of gunshot holes in the bones of more than
one victim, they will have disproved the story that Packer told in
court.
   He said that an awesome snowstorm in April 1874 in the Colorado
Rockies stranded the prospectors for a month and threatened them
with starvation. So he was sent out with a rifle to kill an animal.
   Five days later, he subsequently told the authorities, he
returned empty handed to find four of the prospectors dead, killed
by hatchet, and the fifth, Shannon Wilson Bell, about to attack him
with a hatchet. He said he shot Bell, then struck him with the same
instrument.
   Packer also claimed that he found parts of his colleagues
boiling in a stewpot. He confessed to helping himself, but said he
did it to stay alive.
   Packer left and mingled in society for some weeks, but questions
about the case finally led to his arrest.
   He escaped but nine years later was recaptured in Wyoming. He
was tried for murder and sentenced to hang. The sheriff sent out
fancy invitations to the hanging, but the Colorado Supreme Court
set the verdict aside on the grounds that the legislature had
repealed the death penalty during the time Packer was a fugitive.
   Packer was retried for manslaughter, sentenced to 40 years, and
paroled after 17. He died in 1907, still insisting he had killed
only Bell and only in self-defense.
   Packer found a defender in Ervan F. Kushner, 74, a retired judge
and prosecutor from Paterson, N.J., and author of ``Alfred G.
Packer: Criminal! Victim?''
   Kushner accepts Packer's version, says his two trials were
riddled with errors and questions the worth of Starrs' ``macabre''
undertaking.
   ``Mr. Starrs is a well-known forensics expert,'' Kushner said,
``but what possible proof can there be found in the bones as to
motive? If he enjoys digging in that beautiful scenery, that's a
great place to dig, but how will it establish who struck the first
blow?''
   Starrs agreed the bones won't tell much about motive, but can
answer other questions. Packer, he said, ``was a concerted and
deliberate and long-term liar throughout the trial.''
   Starrs said that bullet holes in more than one set of bones will
tend to establish that Packer, not Bell, killed the four other
prospectors.
   Starrs also said there is no truth to the legend that presiding
judge Melville B. Gerry, in sentencing Packer to hang, commented on
the demographic-political consequences of the slayings, saying that
there had been only seven Democrats in all of Hinsdale County ``and
ye ate five of 'em!''
   In 1981, Kushner petitioned Richard D. Lamm, then the governor
of Colorado, to pardon Packer posthumously.
   Lamm, although a Democrat, wouldn't, but said he found himself
agreeing with another Packer defender, poet Olive Nagel Porter:
   ``Let's not condemn poor Packer
   Nor crowd his soul with abuse
   Though he hardly would merit approval,
   `Hunger' is valid excuse.''
</TEXT>
