<FIRST>r i AM-China-Intellectuals     05-10 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Intellectuals,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Join Protest for Press Freedoms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of 50 bicycle-riding writers, poets and
novelists joined Wednesday's demonstration for a free press and
democracy, marking the first time intellectuals have taken part in
China's student protests.
   ``People stand up, don't be slaves,'' read the T-shirt worn by
Xu Gang, a poet and a writer.
   ``We made them ourselves,'' he said, pointing proudly to his
chest. ``Very fine calligraphy, wouldn't you say?''
   Xu and his colleagues said they came out to support students and
journalists in their call for a free press.
   ``They should not be allowed to stand alone,'' said Su Xiaokang,
a leading essayist.
   On Wednesday, thousands of students bicycled to the offices of
major media to press their call for freedom of expression. The
protest came a day after journalists presented the government with
a petition signed by more than 1,000 reporters requesting a
dialogue with the government.
   Reporters said they wanted to discuss the recent firing of the
editor of a liberal Shanghai paper and the issue of censorship.
   The intellectuals joined the protest midway and bicycled with
the students to the gates of the People's Daily, the newspaper of
China's Communist Party.
   Recognized by many in front of the newspaper's office, they were
almost crushed as the crowd pressed in.
   ``I can't breathe,'' said novelist Xu Xin. After sevaral minutes
of pushing and shoving, the band of intellectuals broke through.
   Xu Gang said he felt odd coming back to the People's Daily as a
protester. The poet once worked as a journalist at the paper.
During the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, he was accused of being a
``rightist'' and ousted from his job.
   ``They haven't really changed much,'' he said, as the crowd
around him chanted, ``The People's Daily deceives the people.''
   ``They are just serving different masters,'' he said.
   Xu Xin said he also felt odd, but for a different reason.
   The novelist, well-known among the young for his black humor and
bawdy prose, said he usually doesn't participate in politics.
   ``But this is something special,'' he said. ``This is a real
movement.''
   China's intellectuals for the most part have stayed on the
sidelines during the recent student demonstrations for a freer
China. Protests began following the death April 15 of Hu Yaobang,
the ousted Communist Party chief.
   Many of them support the movement but do so quietly. Some are
fearful that participation could affect their livelihood. Others
say that as adults they feel ``silly'' demonstrating.
   Earlier in the year, intellectuals were at the forefront of a
movement calling for the release of China's political prisoners.
   Essayists, poets, scientists and novelists wrote open letters to
the government, calling for the release of Wei Jingsheng, who was
sentenced in 1979 to 15 years in prison for ``counterrevolutionary
crimes.''
   The government has said no amnesty will be granted and has
denied that China has political prisoners.
   ``Freedom, the voice of a poet,'' read a T-shirt worn by the
young poet, Qu Wei.
   ``Today we are doing what little we can,'' he said as he got on
his bicycle to ride home. ``Perhaps tomorrow we will be able to do
more.''
</TEXT>
