<FIRST>r a AM-OldNewlyweds     05-10 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Old Newlyweds,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wedding Follows Brief Courtship</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her hearing is faulty and his dancing is
wobbly, but that didn't stop them from getting married so they
could grow old together.
   Boris Feldman, 80, and his bride, Jean, 81, were living separate
lives at Victory Village, one of two retirement communities
operated by the Jewish Homes for the Aging of Greater Los Angeles.
   They met in the dining room in March.
   ``We just started talking to each other. I did like her. I
figured she was just about the size I wanted _ not too tall and not
too fat,'' said Feldman.
   ``He was just a nice person to talk to,'' his wife said.
``That's all I was looking for.''
   On their first and second dates, they attended Victory Village
dances, just ``old-fashioned waltzes,'' Feldman explained, because
``my legs are not as fit as they used to be.''
   Their courtship lasted only two weeks and they were married
March 26.
   Mrs. Feldman said she was ``surprised when he proposed and I
accepted. He caught me at the right moment.'' He noted it ``was a
little hard to propose but she made it easy for me.''
   They decided getting married ``was a good idea and did it. I
like him and I'm comfortable with him. What more do you want in a
man?'' Mrs. Feldman said.
   They have yet to have their first argument. ``We don't have any
money to fight for,'' Feldman quipped.
   ``We still hold hands,'' he added.
   Life is not very demanding, Feldman said. ``We have a lot of
respect for each other,'' his wife added.
   Their days are filled with retirement community activities:
Three meals a day, lectures, bingo games where the top prize
sometimes reaches $1, dances and walks around the grounds.
   ``We just make small talk. We can't make any big plans,'' Mrs.
Feldman said. But they do try to keep each other fit and healthy.
   Mrs. Feldman, just 5 feet tall, says she has to watch what she
eats because she doesn't want to get ``too fat'' for her new
husband.
   Feldman likes to garden and proudly points out there will be
fresh radishes and green onions soon. Mrs. Feldman can't knit much
anymore, so she watches her husband tend to his hobby on their
patio.
   Before they were married, he had a single room at the center,
she shared one with another woman. Combining belongings and moving
into their small married quarters caused few problems. They found
room for everything, although ``he's got more clothes than I
have,'' Mrs. Feldman said.
   They have a television set in their room. Feldman's favorite
shows include ``Phil Donohue'' and ``60 Minutes.'' Mrs. Feldman
turns on the set ``only if I'm bored with myself.''
   Feldman was married once before, a relationship that lasted 50
years until his wife died two years ago. About his second marriage,
his son and daughter ``said it was OK and wished me a lot of
luck,'' he said.
   This is Mrs. Feldman's third marriage. After a 12-year marriage
and divorce, she met ``the love of my life'' and spent 36 happy
years with him until he died 5{ years ago.
   Her stepchildren and grandchildren were delighted when she
remarried. ``My 8-year-old granddaughter is wild about him,'' she
said.
   They had a large wedding at the Victory Village synagogue, with
few jitters because ``we are too old to get nervous anymore,''
Feldman said.
   ``I think I love him,'' Mrs. Feldman said. ``He's a kind and
gentle man.''
   Has love changed, they were asked.
   ``No. Love is the same. It's just like in our young days,'' Mrs.
Feldman said.
</TEXT>
