<FIRST>r a AM-BushBugs     05-10 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Bugs,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Test Confirms Bush Planted Tree Infested With Gypsy Moths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests have confirmed that a tree
transplanted from the White House lawn to the North Dakota Capitol
grounds by President Bush carried the destructive, leaf-eating
gypsy moth.
   ``It's the first time we've ever had gypsy moths in North
Dakota,'' said Keith Winks of the federal Animal and Plant Health
Inspection Service.
   The gypsy moth is a troublesome insect in the eastern United
States and some western states. Its larvae defoliate trees, which
will die if infested too many years in a row, Winks said Tuesday.
   Several tiny moth larvae were found on the president's tree when
it was delivered to Bismarck on April 23, the day before Bush
dedicated the American elm in honor of North Dakota's centennial.
   The tree is a descendant of one planted by President John Quincy
Adams.
   City Forester Paul Blumhardt picked the larvae off the tree and
sprayed the tree with an insecticide. The burlap in which the tree
was wrapped was discarded and the truck that hauled the tree was
sprayed.
   Entomologists at the National Museum in Washington confirmed
that the larvae were gypsy moths, Winks said.
   As part of North Dakota's centennial celebration, the state
plans to plant 100 million trees over the next 10 years.
</TEXT>
