<FIRST>r a PM-WallaceSuit     05-10 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wallace Suit,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Suit Filed By Wallace's Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. George Wallace's brother
says two businessmen owe him stock in a dog track for not asking
his brother to veto the venture, but a judge said such a deal would
be illegal and threw out the claim.
   Circuit Judge William Gordon, in dismissing the $1 million
lawsuit, ruled Tuesday that the agreement, if it existed, could not
be enforced because it was against the law.
   In court papers, Gerald Wallace said he promised Milton McGregor
not to tell his brother, who was then governor, to veto a bill
allowing dog racing. In return, Wallace claimed, McGregor agreed to
pay him a 5 percent stake.
   ``Mr. McGregor knew I could tell my brother to kill the bill,
and it would have been killed,'' Wallace said.
   The law allowing dog racing was approved in 1983, and McGregor's
VictoryLand track opened the next year. George Wallace left office
in 1987.
   Gerald Wallace said lawyer Thomas Marr, in whose name the stock
was held, refused to give him the stock.
   Marr and McGregor maintained no deal was made.
   ``Perhaps Mr. Wallace is hallucinating,'' McGregor said after
the case was dismissed.
</TEXT>
