<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO     05-10 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Opposes PLO Application to Join UNESCO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States opposes a Palestine
Liberation Organization application for membership in UNESCO, the
State Department said Wednesday.
   Richard Boucher, a State Department spokesman, said membership
in the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization is limited to states, a requirement the PLO lacks.
   Boucher noted that the United States withdrew from UNESCO in
1984. He said that the admission of the PLO as ``Palestine'' would
seriously damage any prospects for resumed U.S. membership.
   ``We have urged UNESCO to make every effort to prevent actions
that would have adverse consequences for the organization, the U.N.
system and the Middle East process,'' he said.
   The PLO applied for UNESCO membership at the organization's
headquarters in Paris on Tuesday.
   The application was made as U.S. representatives were attempting
to defeat a PLO bid for membership in the World Health
Organization, which is also a U.N. agency. The Bush administration
has threatened to cut off funding of any U.N. body which admits the
PLO as a member state.
   In Geneva, the annual assembly of WHO put off for 48 hours
Wednesday a decision on the PLO's membership application.
   At present, the PLO is a non-voting observer in the United
Nations.
   The United States funds a quarter of the WHO budget, donating
$71 million this year, but has not contributed to UNESCO since
dropping its membership five years ago.
   The United States withdrew from UNESCO, alleging excessive
politicization, long-term lack of budgetary restraint and poor
management. At the end of this year, the Bush administration will
review its decision to withdraw.
</TEXT>
