<FIRST>r p AM-Evers-GOP     05-10 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evers-GOP,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Activist Says He's Becoming A Republican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-time civil rights activist Charles
Evers, the mayor of Fayette, says he plans to abandon his
long-standing Democratic affiliation to join the Republican Party.
   An outspoken political maverick who has supported Republican
candidates in the past, Evers said it's a mistake for blacks to
primarily support the Democratic Party.
   ``If we don't like what the Republicans do, we need to get in
there and change it,'' he said, adding that he was concerned about
a political realignment along racial lines.
   ``If they don't change rapidly, by the turn of the century,
it'll be a 95 percent white Republican Party and a 99 percent black
Democratic Party. That's not what we need,'' he said.
   State Republican Party Chairwoman Evelyn McPhail said the party
welcomes Evers.
   ``I think what he's doing is what so many elected Democrats and
independent officials are doing. They're saying, `I've been
supporting Republican candidates, and now I'm going to call myself
a Republican,''' she said.
   State Democratic Party Chairman Ed Cole said Evers was only
making official what he has practiced for years. Cole said Evers,
who recently lost a bid for re-election as mayor, still has clout
among black voters.
   ``But clout works only when you're trying to take people where
they want to go. There ain't any man alive who can take a
significant number of black voters to the Republican Party,'' Cole
said.
</TEXT>
