<FIRST>r a AM-HailSales     05-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hail Sales,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deals Deals Deals After Hail Battered New Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New cars dented by hail the size of oranges
are going at bargain prices as dealers try to move the dented,
dinged goods off the lot to make way for replacements.
   Dealers participating in ``Hail Sales'' had sold about 600 cars
by Wednesday, estimated Ray Flowers, general manager of Cooper
Buick GMC Inc.
   A brief but brutal hail storm slammed into Monroe on May 4.
Flowers said he had never seen anything like it.
   ``There's some old people around here who don't remember one
like this,'' he said. ``That's a once-in-a-lifetime hail storm I'm
sure.''
   Damage at the Cooper dealership was mostly minor but Dick
Gifford said his nearby Honda dealership took a severe pounding.
   ``Out of 137 cars in stock we had 67 windows out,'' Gifford said.
   Gifford said he's adding $100 to the wholesale cost of his cars,
then discounting the cost of storm damages. He's replacing windows
at his own cost, he said, but otherwise selling the cars as is _
dents, dings and all.
   ``We're just gettin' `em gone,'' he said. ``We got new cars
coming.''
   An estimated 2,000 cars valued at about $24 million were damaged
by the storms in the Monroe-West Monroe area of northeast
Louisiana, said Larry Cooper, owner of Cooper Buick GMC and
president of Monroe-West Monroe Auto Dealers.
   ``Hail Sales'' brought a flood of loan applicants to banks
Monday.
   ``It was one of our busiest days we've had in several months,''
said Stan Hargett, Central Bank's vice president and manager of the
consumer loan department.
   Banks are financing damaged new vehicles at their actual value
after an insurance company has assessed the damage, lenders said.
</TEXT>
