<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     05-10 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer for Nicaragua Says Don't Assume Elections Will Be Unfair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for Nicaragua's government sparred
Wednesday with the co-chairmen of a commission studying plans for
the 1990 Nicaraguan election and charged that some members of the
commission are biased.
   ``Our European and Latin allies are as committed to the spread
of democracy as we are,'' Washington attorney Paul S. Reichler told
the privately financed Commission on Free and Fair Elections in
Nicaragua.
   ``And, as judges, they have two distinct advantages over the
Bush administration, the majority of witnesses before this
commission, and even some of the members: They are unbiased, and
they are unburdened by a need to justify their support for what
even the secretary of state has called `a failed policy.'''
   Reichler told the commission he had represented Nicaragua in
legal cases for nearly 10 years. But he said he was testifying on
his own Wednesday and the Sandinista government ``may or may not
agree with what I have to say.''
   A representative of the Nicaraguan Embassy was invited to
testify, but the embassy declined.
   The commission, established by the conservative World Freedom
Foundation, is made up of three Democrats and three Republicans.
Several witnesses at its opening session Tuesday were skeptical of
the prospects for a fair election in Nicaragua.
   Former Sen. Gaylord Nelson, D-Wis., co-chairman of the
commission, told Reichler the fact that Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega would appoint all five members of the proposed Supreme
Electoral Council for the election ``makes the process suspect from
the word `go.'''
   Two of the members are to be drawn from Sandinista ranks, two
from opposition parties and the fifth is to be neutral.
   ``I think you would be helpful to your client if you told him
that ... if Ortega insists on appointing the fifth member, it will
be rejected by everybody in this country who understands what
democracy is all about,'' Nelson said. ``We wouldn't accept that in
any precinct in this country.''
   Reichler replied that Ortega has asked the opposition parties
for nominations, and said judgment should be suspended until the
members of the council are named. But Nelson said he believed ``the
integrity of the process is at stake.''
   When Reichler said Nicaragua's much-criticized press law is
``less restrictive than the laws of Venezuela or Costa Rica,'' the
other co-chairman, Curtin Winsor, interjected, ``That's rubbish.''
Winsor, who served as ambassador to Costa Rica during the Reagan
administration, said he was familiar with the laws of both
countries.
   Under an agreement made by Ortega with the governments of Costa
Rica, El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala, Nicaragua's election is
to be held next February. Reichler said he believes the Sandinistas
will win, and that they will hand over power to the winner if they
do not.
   The United States government has been supporting the Contra
rebels in their fight to oust the Marxist-led Nicaraguan
government, though military aid was cut off last year.
   ``The upcoming election in Nicaragua will certainly test the
Sandinistas' commitment to democracy,'' said Reichler, a Washington
attorney. ``It will also test our own. ... The Bush administration,
and most longtime Contra supporters, have already begun to
discredit the process.''
   Peter Rodman, counsellor to the National Security Council at the
White House, told the panel that ``the possibility of a pluralist
future'' in Nicaragua ``is not excluded, and the election obviously
is a test of it.''
   Asked by Nelson what U.S. policy would be if a fair election
resulted in an Ortega victory, Rodman replied, ``I think there is a
presumption that if there is a fair election and we accept it as a
fair election, that makes a big difference in our attitude toward
Nicaragua and certainly our policy.''
</TEXT>
