<FIRST>r a AM-GreenTenure     05-10 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green Tenure,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnesotan Didn't Have Time to Reform New York Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Green</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was to be the start of a new day for New York
City's beleaguered schools.
   Fourteen months ago, Richard R. Green strode through the
auditorium of Erasmus Hall High School in Brooklyn. The former
Minneapolis school chief, decked out in academic robes, was
attended by the mayor, the governor and every other top city and
state official.
   He was the hero riding in from the West, taking over as New York
City's first black schools chancellor at a time when many wondered
if the schools were capable of positive change.
   ``Business as usual must come to an end,'' Green told the
gathering at his inaugural, ``and it must do so today.''
   Green died early Wednesday, unexpectedly stricken by
asthma-related respiratory failure. He never got the chance to
duplicate his successes in Minneapolis _ reforms that persuaded
normally clannish New York educators to cast their lot with an
outsider.
   For much of his brief tenure in New York City's 939,000-child
school system, Green had to deal with scandal.
   An elementary school principal was arrested on drug charges.
Investigations into drug use, sexual harassment and job-selling by
members of community school boards led Green to suspend two boards.
   Children brought guns into class. Green installed metal
detectors at some shools and launched an anti-gun campaign.
   Green had little time to turn around the city's dropout problem
or institute concrete reforms. Still, there were successes.
   He trimmed the infamous central School Board bureaucracy by
one-fifth. He scored points with teachers and others with gestures
such as removing time clocks from schools.
   And anyone who saw Green with children and parents saw something
special and inspirational. Green, who could be shy and aloof, lit
up with children.
   ``He was very much a symbol for minority kids and parents,''
said Stanley Litow, who headed the search committee that offered
Green the New York job two winters ago.
   ``He was turning the corner,'' Litow said. ``He was beginning to
be much more on top of things, the who's who and what's what.''
   Asked at the beginning of last school year what his chief
accomplishments were, Green answered without apology: ``None.''
   He explained that he was still sizing up the problems in the
school system, that he was looking at long-term solutions and
wasn't interested in blowing his own horn.
   ``My mission, it may sound altruistic, is to serve children,''
he said. ``My eye is on that prize.''
</TEXT>
