<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1455EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     05-10 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ito Says No to Prime Minister's Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary-general of the governing party met
Wednesday with former Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ito to try to
persuade him to take the post of prime minister, but Ito refused.
   Ito said after the meeting he remains determined not to accept
the offer.
   Shintaro Abe, the Liberal Democratic Party's secretary-general,
told Ito the party unanimously supports him to succeed Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, Kyodo News Service and the Japan
Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   Takeshita announced April 25 that he would step down to assume
responsibility for a scandal involving the Recruit Co., an
information and publishing conglomerate accused of trying to buy
influence in the government by selling bargain-priced unlisted
stock in a subsidiary.
   Ito is one of the few senior Liberal Democratic Party members
not linked to Recruit. Three Cabinet members have resigned over
their links to the scandal.
   The news reports said Takeshita agreed to talk to Ito on
Thursday, and it quoted him as saying, ``Political reform is the
urgent need of the party, and we need to promote that under Mr.
Ito's leadership.''
   They also quoted Takeshita as saying he was willing to take his
time in efforts to persuade Ito.
   Ito, 75 and diabetic, has cited his age and health for not
wanting to replace Takeshita.
   But Japanese news reports have said he is holding out for
promises of major reforms. Party sources said that among other
things, Ito wants abolition of factions within the party and the
resignation of all politicians linked to the scandal.
   The Liberal Democratic Party is a group of about a half dozen
factions whose relative strengths and desires have to be considered
each time a Cabinet is formed. Because fundraising is a key part of
factions' efforts to boost their influence in the party,
factionalism is often said to be one cause of ``money politics.''
   In the absence of any other widely supported candidate, party
officials have said Ito is the ``only solution for the time being''
to a replacement for Takeshita.
   Leaders of four major opposition parties, however, have called
on Abe to have the Liberal Democrats hand over power to the
opposition. Abe refused, citing the Liberal Democrats' majority in
the House of Representatives. It holds 297 of the 512 seats.
</TEXT>
