<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1502EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OverlookedBody     05-10 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Overlooked Body,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Miss Accident Victim Found Dead Later by Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police, ambulance crews and fire rescue
units that responded to a wreck overlooked a passenger thrown from
the car, and her body was found by her husband 18 hours later,
authorities said.
   After the car left the road and overturned near Portland
International Airport, the hospitalized driver did not tell
authorities there was a passenger, said Dave Simpson, a police
spokesman.
   Don Griffin of Gresham went looking for his wife when she failed
to return home. He found the body of Gina Griffin, 19, in tall
grass Tuesday afternoon, said Bob Felton, chief deputy medical
examiner.
   The body was about 150 feet from the accident site, said Tom
Steinman, Portland Fire Bureau emergency services coordinator.
   Griffin suffered serious head injuries, but the time and
official cause of her death remained undetermined.
   Police identified the driver as Teresa Barnes, 20.
   Griffin was not at home Wednesday and could not be reached
anywhere else, his sister, Barbara Griffin, said when she answered
the phone at his home. Asked if Teresa Barnes was living at the
same address, as police reported, she said, ``She was, but she
hasn't been here since (the accident).''
   Barnes, who could not be located for comment, was treated for
head contusions and released Tuesday, said Ken Strobeck, Emanuel
Hospital &amp; Health Center spokesman.
</TEXT>
