<FIRST>u i PM-Baker 9thLd-Writethru a0657 05-10 1071</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker, 9th Ld-Writethru, a0657,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Arms Talks to Resume in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf to CORRECT Atlantic, sted America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union will resume
negotiations on strategic nuclear arms reductions next month, a
Soviet spokesman announced today, the start of talks between
visiting U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, spokesman for the Soviet Foreign Ministry,
said the next round of talks on nuclear and space weapons would
probably resume in Geneva on either June 12 or June 19 and last for
six weeks. He said the Soviets had wanted the negotiations to begin
again in May but that the Americans demurred.
   Baker had planned to propose the third week in June for the
reopening of the U.S.-Soviet negotiations to reduce the
superpowers' long-range bombers, nuclear submarines and
globe-girdling missles. The talks recessed in November.
   Gerasimov said the U.S. side explained that Richard Burt, who
has been nominated by President Bush to head the U.S. bargaining
team, probably would not be confirmed by the U.S. Senate in time to
resume talks this month.
   The two leaders met for almost three hours today after Baker's
arrival from Helsinki for his visit to the Soviet Union.
   The discussions began with regional issues, such as the Middle
East and Afghanistan, and included arms control, human rights,
regional problems and direct U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``We are very pleased with the way things started,'' said Baker,
who is making his first trip to the Soviet Union.
   Gerasimov had told reporters earlier that at the request of the
U.S. side, Baker and Shevardnadze concentrated on regional
conflicts, rather than nuclear weapons.
   ``Dealing with regional problems will enable us to get the last
of the Cold War behind us and move into a new stage of our
relationship,'' Gerasimov said.
   He said the subject of short-range missiles in Europe, which has
caused a rift in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, did not
come up.
   The two sides found common ground on Central America, Gerasimov
said. ``Both sides stated there was good potential for a furthering
of dialogue on a Central American settlement,'' he said.
   Baker wants the Soviets to curb their aid to the Sandinistas in
Nicaragua, which amounted to $500 million last year. The Soviets
also raised Afghanistan, a topic Baker had no intention of bringing
up because the Kremlin is demanding the United States halt its
military aid to Afghan rebels.
   In both countries, Marxist governments have Soviet support,
while the United States is backing the insurgents _ with weapons
through Pakistan for the Mujahadeen and with non-lethal aid to the
Contras in Nicaragua.
   According to Gerasimov, Baker and Shevardnadze also discussed
U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's prediction that perestroika,
the restructuring program of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, would
fail.
   Baker explained that Cheney's remarks did not reflect
Washington's official position, and Shevardnadze did not take
offense, Gerasimov said.
   ``We understand that the secretary of defense needs more money
for military programs and how can he possibly obtain that if the
Soviet threat is going away?'' Gerasimov said. ``We were not
offended.''
   Baker, in the Soviet Union for the first time, later met with
three members of the Congress of People's Deputies, a new
parliament elected as Gorbachev gives greater powers to the
legislative arm of government.
   ``We think there are real changes taking place in the Soviet
Union, and we think those changes are more than cosmetic, as
demonstrated by the fact that we now see competitive elections,
looking towards a sitting legislature,'' Baker said at the meeting
at Spaso House, the U.S. ambassador's residence.
   The congress is to meet May 25 to choose a smaller, full-time
legislature, as well as a president. Asked if more than one
candidate should run for president, Baker said, ``One step at a
time.''
   In two days of talks, Baker is expected to turn to Gorbachev for
help in accelerating the fledling U.S. drive for Arab-Israeli
negotiations.
   The U.S. approach to the Middle East represents a shift in
diplomatic gears from two decades of trying to fence out both the
Soviet Union and the Palestine Liberation Organization as apt to
undermine American peace-making.
   Once before, in 1977, the United States made a concerted effort
to engage the Soviet Union in Middle East peace-making. The Carter
administration at that point was at a dead-end in its Mideast
diplomacy.
   But Egypt and Israel quickly decided to launch negotiations, and
the Soviets were shut out again.
   Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979 and since then
have been the largest recipients of U.S. aid and solidly on the
American side of the superpower divide.
   But Baker is faced with a different situation. He is trying to
prod Israel into negotiations with the Palestinians and has
concluded he needs the support of both Moscow and the PLO.
   He is hoping the Soviets under Gorbachev would bring pressure on
Syria to support peace talks that do nothold out the promise of a
Palestinian state. The Soviet Union has refused to exert such power
in the past.
   The PLO, meanwhile, quietly has been assured that if Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's plan for Palestinian elections does
not break the diplomatic stalemate in the Middle East the Bush
administration will look for alternatives.
   At the same time, Baker and his senior advisers are convinced
PLO chairman Yasser Arafat is sincere about his public acceptance
of Israel.
   If the Soviets push the missile issue they could widen the
fissures between the United States and West Germany over NATO's
nuclear arsenal.
   The Bush administration, supported mostly by Britain, wants to
enhance the range of the 88 Lance launchers and their 700 or so
missiles, most of which are in West Germany, while Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, backed by a majority of the alliance, is resisting and
calling for U.S.-Soviet negotiations on such weapons in Europe.
   By contrast, Baker is playing down arms control.
   He headed to Moscow with a proposed date _ the third week in
June _ for the reopening of U.S.-Soviet negotiations to reduce the
superpowers' long-range bombers, nuclear submarines and
globe-girdling missiles.
   But he was not planning to outline the position the United
States would take at the table. Nor was he assuring the Soviets
that there would be no changes since the talks were recessed in
November.
</TEXT>
