<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     05-10 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be topped.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on House Ways and Means Committee
mounted an assault on President Bush's savings and loan bailout
plan in a move that also could upset a ``no new taxes''
deficit-reducing budget agreement between Congress and the White
House.
   Led by Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., members of the tax-writing
panel moved to include all of the $50 billion government infusion
of cash to cover S&amp;L failures in the fiscal 1989, 1990 and 1990
budgets.
   ``I have great ethical and moral problems with the way this
program is financed'' under Bush's plan, Gibbons said. ``This is a
mess that ought to be cleaned up without ... passing the costs on
to our children and grandchildren.''
   Bush would have included only the anticipated interest costs of
$3.5 billion over the three years in the budget by borrowing the
$50 billion through private maket bond sale instead of directly
through the U.S. Treasury.
   The plan involved closing or merging some 350 insolvent thrift
institutions that because of bad loans and often fraud have lost up
to $100 billion in federally insured deposits. Most of the money
would be used to cover those losses.
   The House and Senate last week approved a budget resolutions for
fiscal 1990 beginning next October that would trim this year's $160
billion deficit to just over $99 billion. Neither plan reflected
most of the bailout's costs, assuming it would be handled ``off
budget'' as Bush proposed.
   ``We've fairly well destroyed the budget agreement between the
administration and Congress,'' Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn.,
complained Tuesday.
   Gibbons' alternative adds $10 billion to this year's deficit and
potentially $25 billion in fiscal 1990, ending any hope of meeting
the Gramm-Rudman deficit target of $100 billion then without
spending cuts elsewhere or an increase in taxes.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady spent more than an hour behind
closed doors with members of the committee, trying to convince them
to go along with Bush's plan and repeating a threat that he would
urge the president to veto it if they didn't.
   He left the meeting smiling. But when asked by reporters if
Bush's plan had sufficient support in the committee, he said only,
``You never know about that. We'll have to wait and see.''
   Gibbons led the attack on the administration's plan after the
panel's chairman, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said Tuesday that
he would not mount an offensive against it.
   Senate Democrats also had pushed for handling the cost of the
bailout _ which, including interest, is expected to exceed more
than $250 billion over the next 30 years _ directly.
   But they stopped short of forcing a showdown after the White
House and Brady threatened a veto and said it would upset then
on-going negotiations on reducing the deficit through spending cuts
in defense and domestic programs in order to fulfill Bush's
campaign pledge of ``No new taxes.''
   A confrontations with Bush over the S&amp;L financing would have
stopped ``dead in its tracks'' the budget accord that had been
negotiated over three months, said Senate Budget Committee Chairman
James Sasser, D-Tenn.
   Frenzel, who led the support for Bush's plan, said changing it
will only force a veto that will ``prolong the crisis and allow
(S&amp;L) institutions to keep on making bad loans.''
   Actually, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has taken control
of more than half of the 350 most troubled thrifts in the past
three months and stopped some of their riskier lending activities.
But losses are still mounting at a rate of $10 million a day
because of past bad loans, according to the administration.
   Frenzel also echoed the administration's arguments in contending
that waiving the Gramm-Rudman deficit target will open the door for
increased government spending and drive all interest rates up.
   ``Once the credit market understand that we are willing to
breach Gramm-Rudman, they will understand that we are willing to
breach it for toxic waste cleanups, homelessness or whatever comes
down the pike,'' he said.
   Democats, however, seemed willing to force a veto showdown.
   ``There's not going to be a delay unless the administration
wants a delay,'' said Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif. ``It will be up
to the president to sign the bill or not sign it.''
   The Democratic alternative retains the same Resolution Financing
Corp. that Bush would establish for raising the $50 billion _ $6
billion of it from the industry and the rest borrowed. The industry
also would have to pay $300 annually for 30 years as its share of
the bailout.
   However, the financing corporation would have to borrow the
balance through the Treasury or the Federal Financing Bank rather
than via the private bond market.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates the savings in lower
interest rates that have to be paid through direct Treasury
borrowing will total $671 million over the first five years, $1.5
billion by the year 2000 and $4.5 billion over 30 years.
   my
</TEXT>
