<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ResortFilming     05-10 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Resort Filming,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resort Town Shuns Film Spotlight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Town Council in this winter resort
is shunning the spotlight, endorsing a move to limit filmmaking to
seven days a month.
   The town already restricts filmmaking to the off-season months
of April to November, when many residents go back north. But the
measure given preliminary approval Tuesday on a 3-2 vote would
further limit filming on grounds of preserving public safety.
   Town Attorney John Randolph warned that the measure might not
stand up to a court challenge, but council members weren't
dissuaded.
   ``This is Palm Beach. This is not a sound stage,'' said council
member Bernard Heeke.
   ``What if they're half through on the seventh day? Will we say
go home?'' asked council member William Weinberg, one of the
opponents.
   ``Yes,'' shot back council President Nancy Douthit. ``Because
they're notorious time wasters.''
   Segments of Burt Reynolds' ``B.L. Stryker'' mystery series have
been filmed in Palm Beach and the island has been used as a setting
in recent movies.
</TEXT>
