<FIRST>r i AM-Swiss-Money     05-10 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swiss-Money,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Legislation Against Money-Laundering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday announced
draft legislation that would make money-laundering a crime.
   The proposal, expected to be presented to Parliament before
mid-June, is aimed at combatting drug-trafficking and organized
crime, said Justice Minister Arnold Koller.
   Switzerland's financial and political communities have been
rocked by the ``Lebanon Connection'' scandal in which investigators
say about $1.2 billion, including alleged drug money, was recycled
through Swiss banks.
   The case led to the resignation of the former justice minister,
Elizabeth Kopp, after it was revealed she tipped off her husband to
sever his links with Shakarchi Trading, a Lebanese-controlled,
Zurich-based company under investigation.
   The legislation would outlaw those acts that obstruct the
investigation of the ``origin, the tracing, or the seizure'' of
assets known to have come from illegal activities.
   Violators would be punished by up to five years in prison and a
fine of up to $600,000.
   A second part of the proposed law would punish bankers, lawyers,
financial advisers and banknote traders for lack of care if they
fail to determine the identity of their customers in transactions.
Offenders face up to a year in prison.
   The draft law was greeted by three of the four parties making up
the government coalition and was cautiously welcomed by the banks.
The Social Democratic Party said it did not go far enough.
</TEXT>
