<FIRST>r w AM-US-Vietnam 1stLd-Writethru a0623 05-10 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Urges Refuge for Vietnamese</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 10 grafs new or recast to include Senate panel action,
picks up pvs graf 3, ``The legislation''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Wednesday approved a resolution urging Southeast Asian nations to
resume providing refuge for asylum-seeking Vietnamese.
   Meantime, a House subcommittee endorsed a resolution urging
Vietnam to speed the emigration to America of thousands of people
sent to ``re-education'' camps because of their ties to the former
pro-U.S. government of South Vietnam.
   The Senate panel's resolution is directed to members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations and seeks to state U.S.
policy before an international conference on Indochinese refugees
is held next month in Geneva under auspices of the United Nations.
   The resolution, sent to the full Senate, states that ASEAN has
announced a policy of screening all asylum-seekers to determine
their refugee status. It says Vietnam has ``demonstrated its
hostility to those leaving Vietnam illegally and, in particular, to
those refusing to return to Vietnam voluntarily.''
   The resolution declares that ASEAN should reinstate the practice
of providing ``adequate refuge'' for all Vietnamese seeking asylum
while carrying out their screening.
   It calls for early access for the United Nation's High
Commissioner for Refugees to provide humane care and protection to
those seeking asylum.
   The resolution states that no Vietnamese seeking asylum should
be sent back to their homeland without guarantees they will not be
persecuted.
   ``Given Vietnamese attitudes toward illegal departure, forced
repatriation of refugees to Vietnam should not be considered a
viable option,'' the resolution declares.
   And it says the United States should ``remain committed to a
generous and humane Southeast Asian refugee resettlement policy.''
   Meantime, a resolution approved by voice vote of the House
subcommittee on Asian and Pacific affairs, and sent to the full
House Foreign Affairs Committee for further action, says that the
willingness of Vietnam's government to ``satisfactorily resolve
this humanitarian issue'' involving emigration will have ``an
important bearing'' on U.S.-Vietnamese relations.
   The legislation noted that the United States ``has made it
clear'' to Hanoi that it is ready to allow those detained because
of loyalty to the Saigon government to enter the United States.
South Vietnam collapsed in 1975.
   The United States and Vietnam agreed in principle last July on
the U.S. resettlement of ``re-education'' detainees and their
families but Hanoi later suspended negotiations, the resolution
said. It asked Hanoi to resume talks and to publish the names of
and to release those still in ``re-education'' camps, as well as
dissidents arrested for non-violent political or religious activity.
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., wrote the resolution, which has been
co-sponsored by 32 other members of both parties.
</TEXT>
