<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     05-10 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Louisiana Priest's Fast Wins Equipment For Health Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast by a Louisiana priest to
protest government delays in finishing a health clinic for peasants
Wednesday prompted officials to begin installing new equipment.
   ``It's a minor miracle. They're bringing in everything from
X-ray machines and hospital beds to fluorescent lights,'' said the
Rev. Donald Bahlinger, who began his fast Friday.
   The 60-year-old Roman Catholic priest from Baton Rouge said he
would continue his meals of bread and water for one more day ``as a
way of thanking God.''
   Bahlinger camped out on the first floor of the empty health
center in San Ignacio, Misiones, 135 miles southeast of Asuncion.
   Although the 35-bed hospital building was finished in 1981, it
remained an empty shell until this week. Critics blamed official
corruption and inefficiency during the regime of Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner, who was ousted Feb. 3.
   His last health minister, Adan Godoy Jimenez, is in jail facing
charges that include overcharging the government for building
health centers, dozens of which never were properly equipped or
staffed.
   San Ignacio residents were cared for in a run-down, six-bed
veterans' hospital where three beds in one room were reserved for
maternity cases and three in another room were for any ill men,
women or children.
   ``We would ask authorities if we could just use some rooms in
the new hospital as dormitories and they would tell us we couldn't
use them until it was inaugurated, and they couldn't inaugurate it
because it wasn't equipped,'' said Bahlinger.
   Hundreds of residents turned out to support Bahlinger with
Masses and a silent march during his fast.
   ``One of the things that really made it click was the support of
the people,'' said Bahlinger, who came to Paraguay eight years ago
to serve as parish priest in San Ignacio.
   Late Tuesday, two loaded flatbed trucks pulled up at the
hospital, and Assistant Health Minister Ruben Mayorquin asked
Bahlinger to bless the new equipment.
   ``It turned into a real fiesta with close to 1,000 people
singing, chanting and applauding,'' said the Rev. Leo Leise, a
fellow Jesuit from New Orleans.
   The first patient to be treated in the new hospital is a
30-year-old mother of five suffering from cancer, who was turned
away from the old veterans clinic.
   ``She regained consciousness and seems to be in good spirits.
They have her in a nice room now,'' said Bahlinger.
</TEXT>
