<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     05-10 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racist Government Abolished; Police Arrested In Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South African-imposed racist system
of government was abolished Wednesday in preparation for November
elections leading to independence for this mineral-rich territory.
   In a separate development, police announced Wednesday they
arrested two white policemen suspected in the shooting of a
van-load of civilian supporters of the black nationalist South-West
Africa People's Organization.
   Louis Pienaar, Namibia's South African-appointed
administrator-general, issued a proclamation Thursday transferring
all executive and legislative powers of government to himself.
   The proclamation leaves in place such institutions as racially
segregated schools. In effect, government activities still will be
conducted on a racial basis because the administrative arms of
racially separated regional and municipal entities will remain in
operation.
   Rehoboth regional government, in the area of the mixed-race
Basters people, is the only one unaffected. Rehoboth has had a
special semiautonomous status since 1870, and is governed by a
South African law which is being repealed.
   The Rehoboth government and whites-only National Party of South
Africa oppose the U.N. independence plan for Namibia and have
refused to vacate their offices.
   South Africa, which has controlled Namibia for 74 years, agreed
to implement the U.N. plan in a three-way regional accord that
includes withdrawing 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, Namibia's
northern neighbor.
   The South African-led territorial police announced Wednesday
they arrrested two policemen in northern Namibia suspected in the
April 2 shooting of SWAPO supporters. Seven people were injured,
and one, 26-year-old David Indongo, died Tuesday from a bullet
wound in the back. The police did not identify the suspects.
   According to reports, two white men in a car opened fire on the
van carrying civilians home from a rally in Windhoek, the capital,
where they had celebrated the beginning of the independence process
April 1.
   South Africa says about 1,600 SWAPO guerrillas crossed into
northern Namibia starting April 1, violating an agreement they
would remain temporarily at bases in Angola. Most of the guerrillas
have withdrawn following clashes that South African officials say
left 27 security force members and 314 SWAPO fighters dead.
   The guerrillas are to return, unarmed, with thousands of other
Namibians who fled the territory during SWAPO's 23-year bush war
against South African occupation. The repatriation will start May
22, a week later than scheduled, and be completed by June 30, the
territory's National Health Secretary Louwrence Erasmus said
Wednesday.
   He said the government, churches and U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees expect nearly 58,000 refugees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
