<FIRST>r w AM-Mail-OrderTax     05-10 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mail-Order Tax,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Asked to Let States Tax Out-of-State Mail Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With their eyes on revenue of at least $1.5
billion a year, representatives of state and local government asked
Congress Wednesday to require that taxes be collected on mail-order
sales to out-of-state residents.
   Under a 22-year-old Supreme Court decision, a state may not
require an out-of-state merchant to collect sales taxes unless the
merchant has a retail outlet in the state. A bill introduced by
Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, would require only that a company regularly solicit
business in a state before the state could require that taxes be
collected.
   Gov. George Sinner of North Dakota, speaking for the National
Governors' Association, said present law is unfair to local
merchants because it allows their competitors to undercut prices by
the value of sales taxes, which range from 5 percent to 8 percent.
That, Sinner said, is greater than most merchants' average profit
margin.
   ``A 5 percent sales advantage is overwhelming the Main Street
retailer,'' he told a news conference. ``That is why the National
Governors' Association and other state government groups are
joining with a new coalition of retail and labor groups to end this
competitive interstate disadvantage.''
   Across Capitol Hill, opponents of Brooks' bill were having their
say.
   ``This will have the maximum irritation effect on tens of
millions of consumers who would have to do the tax calculations
every time they order,'' said Robert Levering, vice president of
the Direct Marketing Association.
   ``If this legislation were to pass, direct marketers would be
saddled with tax collection duties for over 7,000 municipal and
state tax jurisdictions,'' he said. ``That means we can be audited
by every one of those jurisdictions, even where our companies don't
have physical presence (in a state) and don't receive benefits.''
   Sen. Robert W. Kasten Jr., R-Wis., who is leading the fight
against Brooks' bill, said it ``unfairly targets the elderly, the
handicapped, farm families and the millions of consumers who rely
on mail-order purchases for many of their basic needs.''
   Kasten's state is home to Land's End, one of the nation's
largest catalog suppliers of clothing.
   Here is the problem created by present law:
   If a Wisconsin woman buys a $20 blouse from a Land's End catalog
or from a hometown store, she pays the 5 percent Wisconsin sales
tax. If a Tennessee woman buys the same blouse from Land's End, she
pays no sales tax; if she buys it in her hometown, she pays
Tennessee's 5{ percent tax plus any local sales tax.
   Brooks' bill would require that out-of-state mail-order and
telephone-order companies _ including the popular television
shopping shows _ collect sales taxes from out-of-state customers
only if the firms have annual sales above $12.5 million.
   Sinner said that would exempt from collection about 95 percent
of mail-order companies. The remaining 5 percent account for 70
percent of mail-order sales, he said.
   State officials estimate enactment of Brooks' bill would bring
state and local governments more than $1.5 billion a year.
</TEXT>
