<FIRST>r w AM-ChryslerRecall     05-10 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler Recall,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automaker Agrees to Recall Nearly 600,000 Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chrysler Corp., has agreed in two separate
actions to recall nearly 600,000 1984-model through 1987-model
vehicles because they do not meet federal pollution requirements,
the Environmental Protection Agency said Wednesday.
   The EPA said one recall involves 127,000 1984-model cars that
were found to exceed federal carbon monoxide exhaust emission
standards. The action involves the Chrysler E Class, New Yorker,
LeBaron, Laser, Laser XE, Dodge 600 and Daytona.
   At the same time, the EPA said the automaker also has agreed to
issue a recall of 468,000 vans, wagons, pickup trucks and sports
utility vehicles covering the 1984 through 1987 model years to fix
a gasoline vapor control valve.
   The EPA said the vehicles exceed the federal standards for
pollution caused by the escape of gasoline vapors from the fuel
system and engine. Such vapors are a contributor to smog and other
air pollution.
   The agency said the automaker had agreed to make an adjustment
in the carburetor bowl-vent valve, which controls the release of
gasoline vapors.
</TEXT>
