<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DevelopmentBank     05-10 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Development Bank,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Asked for Funds to Enable Bank to Lend $22.5 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration asked Congress on
Wednesday for funds to enable the Inter-American Development Bank
to lend $22.5 billion to Western Hemisphere countries by 1993.
   The U.S. contribution would be $78 million a year. Only 2.5
percent of the proposed increase in the bank's capital is paid in,
with the rest remaining ``on call'' but not expected to be needed.
   David C. Mulford, assistant secretary of the Treasury for
international affairs, said the bank will begin making loans to
help change borrower countries' policies in whole sectors such as
agriculture. Past lending has been for specific projects, such as
dams, roads or schools.
   Sector loans are disbursed quickly so they can also help a
borrowing country meet interest payments on old loans which amount
to more than $400 billion and will not be directly affected by the
new ones.
   Regarding the debt problem, the bank's present role is ``to
encourage the borrowers to adopt policies that improve economic
performance, stimulate new foreign investment, increase domestic
savings and encourage the repatriation of flight capital,'' Mulford
said.
   Mulford's request for funds came after three years of
negotiation to get more power for the United States and other
contributing countries over the bank's lending policies. They can
now delay a loan for as long as a year.
   ``The intent and design of the new loan approval mechanism is to
foster a ... consensus in support of loans and thereby improve loan
quality,'' Mulford said.
   He appeared before the subcommittee on international economic
policy of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</TEXT>
