<DOCNO> AP890510-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     05-10 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Denounces Kadar Leadership; Parliament Approves Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Miklos Nemeth on Wednesday
criticized the 32-year leadership of former party chief Janos Kadar
and denounced the Communist Party's past monopoly on political
affairs.
   Kadar said he may have made mistakes but that he meant well.
   Parliament approved changes recommended by Nemeth that installed
six new Cabinet members expected to speed the pace of reform.
   The move came a day after the policy-making Central Committee
offered to negotiate democratic reforms with opposition groups.
Similar talks have brought about a more democratic electoral system
in Poland and legalized Solidarity there.
   The party said the new talks could include all registered
opposition groups and focus on an exact date for next year's
multiparty elections, a new constitutional court, the powers of a
new state presidency and a new electoral law.
   A leader of one of the new independent political groups, Karoly
Ravasz of the Smallholders Party, said his initial response to the
offer was positive.
   He said the leaders of eight opposition groups planned to meet
to decide on a common strategy for replying to the offer.
   In a speech to Parliament, Nemeth suggested the Budapest
leadership is caught in an impasse.
   ``The conservative forces are unable to turn the clock back, but
the reform forces are still unable to attain a decisive turn,''
Nemeth said. He said the situation is not conducive to a coalition
with non-communist groups, ``although I would liked to see this
come about.''
   Nemeth gave the most critical appraisal yet of the Kadar years,
although he did not mention the longtime leader by name.
   Kadar, 76, rose to power behind the Soviet-led invasion of 1956
that crushed a popular uprising. On Monday, he was removed from the
Central Committee and stripped of the honorary post of party
president.
   In another sign that the party is opening up about the past, the
state news agency MTI on Wednesday published for the first time the
names of all 277 people it said were executed after the 1956 revolt.
   ``Hitherto, government decisions have been almost exclusively
based on party decisions,'' Nemeth said. ``The activities of the
government were accompanied by the least possible openness.''
   ``Not only did the government not accept Parliament as a
supervisory body, but it did not accept Parliament as an equal
partner either,'' he said, referring to the Parliament's longtime
role as a rubber-stamp body.
   Nemeth blamed Kadar's economic policies for the crisis facing
Hungary now. The rise in living standards in the 1970s was based on
massive borrowing, resulting in a $17 billion foreign debt that
requires further loans of up to $3 billion annually to cover the
interest.
   Replying to a letter from the Central Committee that echoed
Nemeth's criticism, Kadar said he was sure he had made mistakes but
added that ``all of my actions were guided by good intentions.''
   The letter, dated Wednesday, was made public by MTI. In it,
Kadar also said his health ``took a turn for the worse'' in April,
but he did not elaborate.
   At a news conference, Nemeth introduced his new Cabinet members
and said all are reform-minded.
   They are Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, 57; Finance Minister
Laszlo Bekesi, 46; Industry Minister Ferenc Horvath, 46;
Agriculture Minister Csaba Huetter, 45; Culture Minister Ferenc
Glatz, 48, and Ernoe Kemenes, 48, head of the planning office.
   Horn replaces Peter Varkonyi at the Foreign Ministry. Varkonyi
has been named to be the next ambassador to the United States. The
others replaced in the 17-member Cabinet will be retired or
transferred to other government jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
