<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0641 05-10 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0641,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Shell Aoun's Headquarters, U.S. Residence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with TV station hit, details of
hits in Jounieh. Pickup 6th graf, ``Only the ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Shelter, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners blasted the presidential
palace, army headquarters and the U.S. ambassador's residence with
mortar fire Wednesday.
   Gunmen stormed the central prison in Moslem west Beirut, freeing
189 convicts. A special squad of police, armed with M-16 assault
rifles, recaptured 95 of them despite shellfire across the divided
city, authorities said.
   Police said 10 people were killed and 89 wounded in Wednesday's
duels between the Christian army units of Gen. Michel Aoun and
their Syrian and Druse militia foes.
   That raised the overall toll to 337 people killed and 1,323
wounded since the latest round of fighting, believed to be the most
destructive of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war, erupted March 8.
   One salvo crashed into the building of the state-run Channel-7
television station in west Beirut during the 8:30 p.m. newscast.
The announcer ducked, then ran, and the station went off the air.
   Witnesses said 80 Syrian rockets struck the bay of the Christian
port city of Jounieh north of Beirut within five minutes, setting
off loud blasts and fires that burned in the night sky.
   Within an hour, 60 rounds, mostly 240mm mortars, struck the
presidential palace in the Christian suburb of Baabda and the
nearby Defense Ministry in Yarze, where Aoun has his headquarters.
   Only the Syrian army possesses such weapons in Lebanon.
   ``They've decided to demolish both facilities,'' a military
spokesman said by telephone from underground shelters at the
Defense Ministry.
   ``Our gunners are responding to silence the source of fire,'' he
said, insisting on anonymity.
   Aides said Aoun, 53, his wife and three daughters have been
living in a shelter at the palace.
   ``Damage was considerable, but we cannot really give a more
precise assessment because we have all been living in the bunker
for four days,'' said an official at the presidential palace.
   The U.S. Embassy said Ambassador John McCarthy's two-story villa
was hit, but there were no casualties. McCarthy and his family are
abroad.
   The one-sentence statement gave no other details.
   Tank clashes escalated into a savage shelling of Christian and
Moslem residential districts at about midnight, the police
spokesman said.
   ``Both sides were using the population as their shield,'' the
spokesman said. He cannot be named under standing police rules.
   Ambulance sirens and thuds from exploding shells echoed across
the city until the fighting slackened three hours later, he said.
   Early Wednesday, about 30 gunmen, armed with grenade launchers
and AK-47 automatic rifles, broke into the jail, the spokesman said.
   He said a Moslem police sergeant was killed in a shootout with
the gunmen, who ``entered the prison warden's office, took the
keys, opened the cells and turned loose all 189 prisoners.''
   The special police squad set up checkpoints at the southern
entrances to Beirut and searched cars for the wanted prisoners.
   In Damascus, Syria, an Arab League mediator met with Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa in an effort to revive an Arab
League-mediated cease-fire declared on April 28.
   Lakhdar Ibrahimi, an Algerian, was accompanied by Gen. Ali
Momen, a Kuwaiti officer chosen to head a 321-man observer force
drawn from six Arab nations to help implement a lasting cease-fire.
   Ibrahimi and Momen later traveled to the Syrian-controlled Bekaa
valley and met with Parliament Speaker Hussein Hussini, a Shiite
Moslem.
   Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah, said the
military observers would not arrive until a cease-fire takes hold.
   Aoun, who also heads a Christian military cabinet, and acting
Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni who heads a rival Moslem
cabinet, both said they accepted the truce.
   But Syrian forces and Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's militia
kept shelling Christian areas, claiming they were trying to prevent
three ships loaded with Iraqi weapons from supplying Aoun's forces.
   Iraq, which has a long-running feud with Syria, backs Aoun's
pledge to fight until the estimated 40,000 Syrian soldiers, in
Lebanon under a 13-year-old Arab League peacekeeping mandate, are
withdrawn.
   The latest fighting began two days after Aoun ordered a blockade
of ports controlled by Syrian-backed militias in a bid to recoup
lost tax revenues estimated at $100 million annually.
   Jumblatt's militia retaliated by shelling the 310-square-mile
Christian-held region, and the Syrians joined in later.
</TEXT>
