<FIRST>r i AM-Shamir     05-10 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shamir,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Hospitalized for Tests, Reported in Good Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has been
hospitalized for tests after complaining of tiredness and weakness,
but hopes to be released by Friday, his spokesman said.
   Shamir, 73, was taken to Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem after he
became faint Wednesday while attending Israel's annual Independence
Day Bible contest, spokesman Avi Pazner said.
   The prime minister had attended more than half a dozen events
since Monday night to mark two successive holidays, Memorial Day
and Independence Day.
   Pazner said Shamir fell against a piece of furniture in his home
Tuesday, bruising his cheek, but the injury was not serious and had
no connection with his hospitalization.
   Hospital spokeswoman Ruth Mekel said he was admitted ``for
general tests'' by Dr. Yehezkiel Stein, the hospital's director of
internal medicine. She said he was ``resting and is feeling fine.''
   His spokesman said Shamir ``hopes that in a day or two he will
be let out.'' Pazner said his boss was ``in an excellent mood ...
working on his schedule from his hospital room'' and had asked that
a radio and telephone be installed.
   Shamir's wife Shulamit visited him and more visitors were
expected, Pazner reported. He said the prime minister's general
health was ``excellent'' and he has no history of major medical
problems.
</TEXT>
