<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru   05-10 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0637,0918</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Opposition Candidate Injured When Police Break Up Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with opposition leader injured.
Pick up 5th pvs, `Guillermo Cochez...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt ^LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition presidential candidate
Guillermo Endara was injured today when police broke up an
opposition demonstration with gunfire and tear gas, an aide said.
   Endara was taken to a hospital, his head bleeding and his shirt
covered with blood, the opposition coalition said in a statement.
   ``The wound apparently is not serious. They're giving him first
aid,'' Maria de Montenegro, a secretary at Endara's office, said in
a telephone interview.
   Endara and his vice presidential candidates were leading a
motorcade when riot police began using tear gas and birdshot to
disperse demonstrators who took to the streets to cheer the
opposition and condemn the election as rigged.
   Earlier today, an opposition leader predicted that violence will
occur if the hand-picked candidate of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
is declared the winner of Sunday's presidential election.
   Supporters of the opposition canceled a plan to present an
official protest claiming fraud, saying they wanted to prepare for
today's march.
   Opposition leaders and the United States, which has long tried
to drive Noriega from power, have condemned the vote as fraudulent.
   Since the election, the presidents of Guatemala, Costa Rica,
Peru and Venezuela have contacted Endara, and he urged them to ask
the Panamanian government not to proclaim Noriega's candidate the
victor, sources in the opposition said today.
   Guillermo Cochez, vice president of the opposition Christian
Democrat Party, told reporters today that a government proclamation
of victory would incite violence ``because the people know who
won.''
   Troops fired into the air to disperse an opposition march
Monday, and at least three people were wounded.
   According to official results from the national tabulation
center, Carlos Duque, Noriega's choice for president, was leading
Endara 2-to-1. With about 15 percent of Sunday's vote counted, the
results showed Duque with 105,522 votes and Endara with 51,844.
   But results supplied by opposition pollwatchers gave Endara the
lead 236,097 to 79,260 with 35.8 percent of the vote counted. That
was close to the 3-to-1 edge indicated by a Roman Catholic Church
exit poll.
   Nevertheless, telephone operators at COLINA, the pro-government
coaltion, answered telephones Tuesday with ``Duque is President, up
with Duque.''
   Panama swept up from the boisterous, acrid but colorful campaign
that saw virtually every tree and wall pasted with posters.
   Police still patrolled the streets, but shopkeepers began to
open boarded up establishments and streetsweepers began hauling
away campaign debris by the truckload.
   President Bush and the presidents of Peru, Costa Rica and
Venezuela condemned election fraud, and the foreign ministers of
the Group of Eight, whic promotes regional stability, were planning
a special meeting to discuss ousting Panama from the organization.
   Panama has been suspended since early last year from the group,
which backs democratic processes and tries to mediate peaceful
solutions to regional disputes.
   Other members are Argentina, Venezuela, Peru, Mexico, Colombia,
Brazil and Uruguay.
   A spokesman for Venezuela's foreign ministry said Panama could
be kicked out of the Group of Eight if election fraud was proved.
   The opposition has said it will continue peaceful efforts to get
rid of Noriega, Panama's de facto leader since 1983 and head of its
15,000-member Defense Forces. Noriega has not made a public
appearance or statement since election day.
   Endara said Tuesday he opposes ousting Noriega through U.S.
military intervention _ an option cited by the White House as under
discussion. Endara said intervention would cause more problems than
it could solve.
   He and other opposition leaders did not specify what action they
wanted from Washington, which has been trying to topple Noriega
since his indictment last year in Miami on drug-trafficking charges.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, who was in Panama as part of an
independent delegation monitoring the elections, returned to
Washington, where he briefed Bush on Tuesday and denounced the
elections as fraudulent.
   He told Bush that military force and any break in the terms of
the 1977 Torrijos-Carter treaties would play into Noriega's hands.
   Noriega has tried to unite Panamanians by contending that the
United States plans to invade Panama and renege on the treaties,
which cede control of the canal to Panama at the end of the century.
   In Washington, Bush called on foreign leaders to urge Noriega to
honor the election results.
   A Bush spokesman said the U.S. president was considering
sanctions ranging from increased economic measures to military
action. American economic sanctions have damaged Panama's economy
but have failed to force Noriega out.
   Most journalists' visas expired today and some, including two
correspondents from the Voice of America, were told they would be
denied extensions, forcing them to leave Panama.
   VOA correspondent Mike Drudge said he was told the government
considers VOA, a U.S. government agency, to be ``an agency of
misinformation.''
   Oswaldo Velasquez, the head of Panama's human rights commission,
said most of the more than 350 foreign observers it invited had
left Tuesday and that others were collecting more reports of troops
confiscating voting tallies.
   Also today, Holland asked the Panamanian government for an
explanation in the death of a Dutch priest who was shot Sunday
while under arrest in the western province of Chiriqui.
</TEXT>
