<FIRST>r a AM-RapeDismissed     05-10 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Dismissed,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Dropped Against Stony Brook Basketball Player</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges were dismissed Wednesday against
a popular university basketball player who last month was accused
of raping a woman on campus.
   The Suffolk County district attorney's office said it had
determined that Quincy Brandon Troupe, 22, who is black, had not
attacked the 20-year-old white woman.
   His arrest had triggered demonstrations on campus at the State
University of New York at Stony Brook in which protesters alleged
the arrest was racially motivated.
   The victim had picked Troupe out of two police line-ups and
identified him from a yearbook picture.
   Troupe, a Harlem resident who had been free in $10,000 bail,
maintained that he was with friends in Manhattan at the time of the
March 24 attack.
   Assistant District Attorney Michael Ahearn told Suffolk County
District Court Judge Edward Green that a ``long and exhaustive
investigation'' showed the evidence against Troupe was weak and
insufficient.
   He said there was no physical evidence against Troupe, his alibi
witnesses were strong and the victim decided not to appear before a
grand jury.
   Troupe smiled broadly and hugged his parents, Margaret and
Quincy Troupe Sr., and his lawyer, C. Vernon Mason, when the judge
dropped the case.
   John Williams, spokesman for the district attorney's office,
said outside the courtroom that the decision to drop charges did
not mean the victim was lying. ``This means that we do not believe
that he (Troupe) did it,'' said Williams.
   ``I knew I wasn't guilty,'' Troupe told reporters. ``I felt it
was just a matter of time.''
   Of the victim, Troupe said, ``I hope in her case that justice
will be done, because if the rape occurred, then there's still a
guy running around out there.''
   Troupe, a popular senior engineering student and starting guard
on the basketball team, was initially suspended by the school after
his arrest April 1. A week later he was granted unrestricted access
to the campus.
</TEXT>
