<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RadarBlocked     05-10 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radar Blocked,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Study Radar Blockage Caused By Hotel At Portland Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government brought in a special plane
Wednesday to determine how much airspace a new six-story hotel is
obscuring from controllers' radar.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials insisted flights in
and out of Portland International Jetport are safe. But they
considered the gaps in the radar coverage serious enough to send in
an airplane full of computer gear, two pilots and a technician less
than 24 hours after air traffic controllers complained about the
problem.
   ``We considered it urgent,'' FAA spokesman Michael Ciccarelli
said.
   He said it would be at least a few days before any information
on the problem could be analyzed, he said.
   Air traffic controllers said a wedge of airspace 6,000 feet high
and perhaps eight miles wide at its broadest point has been blocked
from radar by the construction of a Quality Suites hotel.
   The FAA said that when Portland-based Dunfey Properties Inc.
proposed the hotel, no objections arose because a typographical
error in the developer's documents indicated the building would be
about 12,000 feet from the runway instead of about 1,200 feet away.
   ``But we're not pointing the finger at anyone,'' Ciccarelli
said. ``Why point the finger at an innocent mistake.''
   Dunfey President Bob Dunfey Jr. on Wednesday acknowledged the
typo. But he said the company's documentation included a U.S.
Geological Survey map that showed the correct location. Dunfey
suggested FAA officials should have caught the error.
   ``A quarter of a mile and 2{ miles is a big difference,'' Dunfey
said.
   Dunfey and the local president of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, Cheryl Readio, said moving the radar or
altering its setting might solve the problem.
   Jim Lucas, manager of the FAA's Air Traffic Division for New
England, said that if Wednesday's testing found a serious enough
problem, some flight corridors could be temporarily changed.
   Ms. Readio said no flights had run into trouble, but the air
traffic controllers wanted the situation changed before a problem
did develop.
   Controllers said the gap could cause some planes southwest of
the city to disappear from the radar screen, including flights from
Boston to Portland, flights in and out of smaller airports in
Biddeford and Sanford and some military flights from Pease Air
Force Base in Newington, N.H.
   President Bush flies in that area of southern Maine on the
Marine One helicopter when he travels from Pease to his summer home
in Kennebunkport, but Lucas said the president's flights could not
be affected because they are controlled through Pease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
