<FIRST>r a AM-Quayle     05-10 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Says Senate Should Stay Out Of Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said Wednesday a
Senate committee is considering legislation he called
``unfortunate'' because it would undermine U.S. efforts aimed at a
negotiated political peace in Cambodia.
   ``It surprised me to learn that the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee is considering a measure that would abruptly change U.S.
policy toward Cambodia and essentially eliminate whatever leverage
we may be able to exercise over the situation there,'' Quayle told
the Philadelphia World Affairs Council during a luncheon.
   Quayle returned last week from a tour of Southeast Asia. At a
Cambodian refugee camp near the Thai-Cambodian border, he noted
that the refugees would like to return home but must await the
withdrawal of Vietnamese forces.
   The refugees also must consider the political climate in their
homeland after troop withdrawals before they could go home, he said.
   ``Considerable progress has been (made) in ongoing negotiations
among the Cambodian factions toward agreement on an interim
coalition government under Prince Sihanouk,'' he said. Part of that
agreement is a provision for free elections later.
   With negotiations now in a ``delicate state,'' he said, the Bush
administration is staying away from any binding policy decisions
``with respect to possible additional aid to the non-Communist
resistance'' as well as some form of concession to the Communist
factions who might help in achieving a peaceful settlement.
   The group of prime concern is the Communist Khmer Rouge, once
the most powerful faction and believed responsible for the deaths
of 20 percent of Cambodia's 1975 population during its bloody rule.
   Quayle said the Senate committee is considering legislation that
would ``prevent the U.S. from supporting any Cambodian settlement
in which any elements of the Khmer Rouge would play a role of any
kind,'' even a peace-making or maintaining role.
   Quayle said the effect of the committee proposal would be to
reward the Vietnamese by leaving their puppet regime in place.
   During a question and answer period, the vice president was
asked about U.S. reaction to the recent Panamanian elections in
which Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega declared victory for his
candidate despite claims of election fraud.
   President George Bush ``has all the options,'' Quayle said.
``I'm not going into that.''
   Before his speech, Quayle explored the Mediterranean Sea by
means of a live satellite arrangement set up by Dr. Robert D.
Ballard, who found the Titanic in the north Atlantic using a
remote-controlled robot-camera known as Jason.
   Jason, television and satellites are providing live coverage of
Ballard's work to audiences of children at nine museums around the
country, including Philadelphia's Franklin Institute.
   Quayle also was in Philadelphia to place a wreathe at the Tomb
of the Unknown Revolutionary War Hero near Independence Hall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
