<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Bomb     05-10 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Bomb,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>H-Bomb Controversy Opens Old Wounds Over Military Presence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversy over the loss of a U.S. hydrogen bomb
off Japan 24 years ago has added to the tension surrounding the
U.S. military presence here and created anxiety among Japanese.
   Japan, the only nation ever attacked with nuclear weapons, is
especially sensitive about any kind of danger from nuclear arms.
   The U.S. military said Monday that an A-4 Skyhawk jet carrying
the bomb fell off the U.S. aircraft carrier Ticonderoga in 1965
about 80 miles from a small island in southern Okinawa.
   The statement followed the release of a report by the Greenpeace
environmental group that detailed the loss.
   ``The U.S. government said the bomb does not threaten the
environment,'' Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno said in response to
opposition party questions in Parliament on Wednesday.
   Uno said Tokyo would decide whether to take action on the
matter, which has triggered angry citizen protests, after it hears
from Washington. On Monday, the government asked for a U.S.
explanation of the incident.
   The controversy has added an irritant to U.S. military relations
with Okinawa, site of one of the bloodiest battles in World War II.
The presence of about 35,000 U.S. troops there has led to friction
over a range of issues, from soldiers' behavior to target range
accidents.
   The Japan Congress Against Atomic and Hydrogen Weapons blasted
U.S. secrecy about the bomb loss in a statement Tuesday.
   The governor of Okinawa, Junji Nishime, said he will urge the
government to take steps to calm anxiety among residents of the
island prefecture. The Okinawa assembly is to open an extraordinary
session to look into the bomb loss.
   Another anti-nuclear group in Kagoshima, in southwestern Japan,
sent telegrams to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and President
Bush, asking them to abide by Japan's ban on nuclear weapons or
abolish the Japan-U.S. Security Treaty.
   Under the treaty, about 60,000 U.S. troops are posted in Japan.
   Citizen protests of accidents, aircraft noise and the presumed
presence of nuclear weapons aboard U.S. ships visiting Japan are
common.
   Japan maintains that the security treaty requires prior
consultation by the United States if it wants to introduce nuclear
weapons into Japanese territory. It says there never have been any
such consultations.
   U.S. policy is to neither confirm nor deny the presence of
nuclear weapons in specific locations.
   Japanese citizens and opposition politicians have accused
Washington of covering up the 1965 incident, but the Defense
Department denied the allegations.
   ``It was way out to sea in international waters,'' said Defense
Department spokesman Dan Howard. ``The weapon went down in 16,000
feet of water. There was no danger to anyone. ... There was not
then and there is not now.''
   ``We have faithfully honored our obligations under the
U.S.-Japanese Treaty of Mutual Security and its related
arrangements, and we'll continue to do so,'' he said.
</TEXT>
