<FIRST>u a AM-TreeSpat Bjt   05-10 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tree Spat, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Village, County Locked in Tree Spat: `Pruning' or `Destruction'?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAK PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a few times since young George
Washington took a hatchet to a sapling has cutting into trees
caused such a ruckus.
   After court fights, charges of lying and deception, and a work
stoppage, a judge has told officials of Oak Park and the DuPage
County Water Commission that if they can't agree on how to finish
carving out the path for a new water main, ``I will deal with this
on a tree-by-tree basis.''
   And so Tuesday, as Cook County Judge Kenneth Gillis ordered,
officials from both sides set off on a walking tour in the brisk
spring air. Their mission was to determine exactly how much more
tree trimming is necessary to make room for the pipe-laying crane.
   Long-time residents of the historic west Chicago suburb, which
won national recognition as a ``Tree City'' just last year, say too
much trimming already has been done.
   ``It already looks like a war zone,'' said Tina Birnbaum, an Oak
Park resident for 10 years. ``You can define anything as `pruning,'
I guess, but when you take off everything but the trunk, I'd call
it destruction.''
   At the center of the controversy is DuPage County's attempt to
pump in water from Lake Michigan and replace a system of wells
inadequate to serve a booming housing and business corridor.
   ``I used to live in Elmhurst (a DuPage County community) and I
can appreciate how bad well water is,'' said Mrs. Birnbaum. ``But
one of the reasons I moved here was because I got tired of looking
at tiny trees in all those new subdivisions.
   ``Worse yet, I walk my son to school each day and ... the work
crews don't have the good sense to stop the machinery and the
driving back and forth.
   ``They came to school one day and told the kids to be careful,''
she said. ``But these are little children we're talking about, not
high schoolers.''
   The eastern edge of DuPage County is only about 20 miles west of
Lake Michigan, but about 160 miles of pipe will be laid _ most of
it channeling the water to different communities within county
boundaries.
   In Oak Park, residential streets along a two-mile stretch have
been torn up at an average of one block each week while work crews
dig trenches about 20 feet deep.
   Branches of trees that hang over the street _ most of them elms,
oaks and maples, many 70 years old _ are pruned to make room for
the 90-foot crane that lifts the pipe sections _ 20 feet long and 9
feet wide _ and drop them into the trench.
   Donald Mulack, an attorney for Oak Park, told the court Monday
that 47 of 356 trees designated for ``pruning,'' have been
``amputated'' and nine others were destroyed.
   Clifford Weaver, attorney for the water commission, said only
three trees have been destroyed and plans call for destruction of
just one more to finish the route.
   Gillis sided with the village on the extent of damage to the
trees.
   But rather than granting either side's request for an
injunction, the judge ordered representatives from both sides to
walk the route, negotiating ``by inches and branches'' and agreeing
on ``every cut'' before moving on to the next tree.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
