<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Strike     05-10 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strike,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Leaders Agree to Management Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike leaders at four southwestern copper
mines on Wednesday accepted a management proposal to increase wages
by 30 percent and end a six-day walkout, a spokesman said.
   The workers had been demanding a 50 percent increase in their
pay, which now averages $118 to $176 a month. The strike they began
last week reportedly has cost millions of dollars in lost
production.
   Jan Sugalski of the strike committee said the proposal presented
Wednesday by management also provided for a 30 percent bonus if
production goals are met.
   The strike committee plans to present the proposal to the
workers for approval, Sugalski said. He said he expected crews to
be back on the job by Thursday.
   Solidarity's national spokesman, Janusz Onyszkiewicz, told a
news conference Wednesday the strike had been ``inspired'' by the
official trade union OPZZ but that Solidarity members were
supporting it.
   The strike represented the first significant labor unrest since
a broad-ranging accord between the Solidarity-led opposition and
the communist government was concluded April 5.
   The agreement restored legal status to Solidarity, the
independent trade union that was outlawed in 1982 after the
imposition of martial law in 1981.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, speaking Tuesday at a workers'
rally, stopped short of telling the copper miners to return to
their jobs but said there were more significant problems to solve
first.
   The four affected mines employ about 20,000 miners near the
southwestern city of Lubin and produce most of Poland's copper. The
official PAP news agency said the strike has cut production by
about 100,000 tons daily. The television news said losses amounted
to $2.8 million daily.
   About 15,000 miners have supported the strike, the strike
committee said.
   The committee includes 10 members of the independent Solidarity
trade union, seven from the party-dominated OPZZ union and 13
unaffiliated miners, Solidarity said.
   Poland is the world's eighth-largest copper exporter and ranks
fourth in Europe after the Soviet Union, Belgium, and West Germany.
</TEXT>
