<SECOND>AM-People, SUB, a0671,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of 1st item, dateline LOS ANGELES, with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with Collins comment; picks up 4th graf, `Hackman's 1971 ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar-winning actor Gene Hackman is suing
makers of the film ``Hoosiers'' and a video distributor for $5.5
million he says is owed him.
   In the Superior Court lawsuit filed Tuesday, Hackman claimed he
is owed one-third of a $15 million advance royalty allegedly paid
by video distributor Home Box Office to Hemdale Film Corp. The suit
contends that HBO and Hemdale cheated Hackman by denying there was
such a payment.
   Paul MacKee, director of business affairs at Hemdale, said
Wednesday the film company hadn't seen the suit and there would be
no comment.
   ``We have not received any notice of that lawsuit. We have not
been served,'' said HBO lawyer Horace Collins, refusing to comment
further.
   Hackman's 1971 role as relentless cop Popeye Doyle in ``The
French Connection'' earned him an Academy Award. He was nominated
for the best actor Oscar again this year for his role as a savvy
FBI agent in ``Mississippi Burning.''
   ``Hoosiers'' stars Hackman as a down-on-his-luck basketball
coach who leads a rural Indiana high school team to the state
championship.
</TEXT>
