<FIRST>r w AM-EEC-Austria     05-10 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-Austria,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Congress Urges EEC To Bar Austria Unless Reparations Are Paid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Jewish Congress has received
assurances from several governments that Austria will not be
admitted to the European Economic Community unless it pays
reparations to Jewish victims of the Nazi Holocaust, a spokesman
said Wednesday.
   The assurances were given in response to a letter by the WJC to
the 12 nations of the EEC asking them to link Austria's expected
application with its commitment to compensate fully the Jews who
suffered persecution when the Nazis ruled Austria. Austria intends
to apply for membership in the trading body by the end of the year.
   WJC Executive Director Elan Steinberg declined to say which
European governments had responded to the letter but said he was
encouraged by their reaction.
   In its letter to the 12 EEC ambassadors in Brussels, the WJC
said ``The Jewish communities of Europe are of the firm view ...
that prior to EEC membership, Austria must recognize its moral and
material responsibilities towards Jewish survivors.''
   The WJC, which provided copies of the letter, said a similar one
was sent last November to the chancellor of Austria, Franz
Vranitsky.
   Some 68,000 Austrian Jews died in Nazi concentration camps in
World War II, and another 120,000 were incarcerated or fled the
country.
   Austria's parliament last year voted a one-time compensation of
between $200 and $400 for each victim.
   Jewish groups called the decision a sacrilege, saying it was
motivated by the international condemnation of the election of Kurt
Waldheim as president despite allegations of his involvement in
Nazi atrocities. Waldheim has been banned from entry into the
United States because of his past.
   West Germany agreed in 1952 to pay Holocaust victims lifetime
reparations, but Austria contends it was annexed by Nazi Germany
and is not as culpable even though many of its citizens cooperated
with the Germans.
   ``Austria seeks entry into the European Community based on a
desire for financial benefit,'' Steinberg said. ``It should not
receive such benefits unless it fulfills its financial obligations
arising from its participation in the persecution of Jews.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
