<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearRules     05-10 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Rules,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Leaders Complain of Unfair Regulatory Burden</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear industry leaders accused federal
regulators Wednesday of overloading plant operators with new and
unneeded safety requirements.
   J. Phillip Bayne, president of the New York Power Authority,
told members of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission that despite a
recent trend toward improved safety at nuclear plants, the burden
of NRC safety orders was growing rapidly.
   Bayne also said the commission's staff has gone beyond the
normal bounds of regulation to impose the safety orders.
   ``The perception is that plants are being evaluated on a scale
that is rising, but without the benefit of the formal regulatory
process,'' Bayne said. He and other industry leaders held a
one-hour public session with the commissioners at NRC headquarters
as part of the industry's annual Nuclear Power Assembly.
   Bayne said there had been a fourfold increase between 1987 and
1988 in the number of NRC bulletins to plant operators that require
a specific safety improvement. He said the number of such bulletins
had declined over the previous six years.
   Industry officials think last year's spurt in safety orders may
mean the commission's staff is trying to impose requirements that
go beyond established standards, Bayne said.
   ``This would be a dramatic reversal in NRC policy, and I'd
suggest that there is no evidence of safety concerns that would
justify it,'' he added. ``I acknowledge that this industry has some
poor performers who should and must be called to account, but we,
the industry ... have the means to get their attention.''
   Bayne also complained about what he said was a 50 percent
increase over the past four years in the number of NRC actions that
result in civil penalties against utilities.
   Lando W. Zech Jr., the commission chairman, responded by saying
the technical demands and risks of nuclear power oblige the
industry to try to exceed minimum safety standards.
   ``It bothers me when I hear that we're criticized for
encouraging excellence,'' he said.
   Zech also criticized the industry for giving the NRC
``essentially no cooperation at all'' in attempting to make a new
rule on maintenance standards for nuclear plants.
   Bayne said the industry should be allowed to resolve what he
called isolated problems with maintenance, without the need for new
rules affecting all plants.
</TEXT>
