<FIRST>r w AM-GAO-Defense     05-10 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAO-Defense,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Spending Plan Too High by $150 Billion: GAO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's five-year defense plan is
``fiscally unrealistic'' and would cost about $150 billion more
than what Congress would approve, congressional investigators said
Wednesday.
   Charles Bowsher, head of the General Accounting Office, an
investiagative arm of Congress, told the Senate Armed Services
Committee that his agency had found that the defense spending plan
for fiscal 1990 through 1994 exceeds President Bush's own budget
plan by $45 billion.
   He also said that the Pentagon plan assumes an inflation rate of
3.6 percent in 1990, declining to 1.7 percent in 1994. However, the
Congressional Budget Office and others expect inflation rates of 4
percent or higher for the next five years.
   ``Under CBO's projections, the five-year plan is underfunded by
nearly $48 billion,'' Bowsher said.
   Compounding the problem is the strong possibility that Congress
will approve defense budgets accounting for inflation and providing
for no real increases. That, Bowsher said, would require an
additional $54 billion in Pentagon reductions.
   President Bush has cut Pentagon spending requests for 1990
through 1994 by about $65 billion, but the GAO believes more cuts
are needed.
   The comptroller general also said that the Pentagon has planned
for more than $2 trillion more than provided for in congressional
budget authority.
   ``What is the effect of being that much off on the five-year
defense plan?'' asked Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the committee's
chairman. ``Does that mean the five-year defense plan has been
essentially worthless?''
   ``It might be close to that,'' Bowsher responded.
   ``What's a word close to worthless,'' Nunn interrupted.
   Bowsher told the panel that ``since the mid-1980s, the
department's five-year defense planning has been fiscally
unrealistic. More weapons were being planned and developed than
could be produced in an economic manner or supported once they were
produced.''
   In a related development, a study released Wednesday by the
liberal Brookings Institution found that the administration has
made unrealistic economic assumptions, but also concluded that
Cheney ``was on the right track'' in choosing to cancel major
weapons systems to trim the budget.
   Lawrence Korb, a former assistant secretary of defense in the
Reagan administration, and William Kaufmann of Harvard University
forecast a gap of $200 billion between projected force levels and
available funds.
   Korb said, however, that Cheney had substantially closed the gap
by canceling the V-22 Osprey aircraft and delaying development of
the B-2 stealth bomber by a year. Korb and Kaufman recommended that
the Pentagon produce only six of B-2s for testing rather than the
entire 132 requested by the Air Force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
