<FIRST>r i AM-RefusenikProtest     05-10 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refusenik Protest,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Jews Demonstrate on First Day of Baker Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uniformed police and KGB agents in plainclothes
dispersed about 40 Soviet Jews on Wednesday who were demanding
Washington make no trade concessions to the Soviet Union until
Moscow ends all limits on emigration.
   Their protest outside Moscow's International Trade Center came
on the first day of Secretary of State James Baker's visit to
Moscow.
   Protest organizer Yuri Semenovsky said Baker arranged to meet
some of the demonstrators later at the U.S. Embassy.
   The protesters want the United States to keep denying the Soviet
Union most-favored-nation status until emigration limits are
discarded entirely.
   Many of them carried banners asking the U.S. government to
maintain the 1972 Jackson-Vanik amendment that bars trade
concessions to communist states unless the president can state he
has received assurances that emigration will be liberalized.
   One sign read, ``I wait for permission to leave the U.S.S.R. for
10 years.'' Another read, ``Mr. Vanik, we are still here!''
   Charles Vanik, no longer in Congress, suggested last Thursday
that restrictions he had co-sponsored be waived for one year,
saying such action would encourage further human rights
improvements here under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Semenovsky, leader of a refusenik group called ``Poor
Relatives,'' said the amendment should stay put until Moscow passes
a law letting anyone leave who wants to. He said 100,000 people
were refused permission last year.
   According to the Geneva-based Intergovernmental Committee for
Migration, which helps resettle emigres, Jewish emigration from the
Soviet Union rose in April to its highest level since 1979, with
4,129 Soviet Jews allowed to leave.
   Semenovsky claims, however, that many who want to leave are
afraid to apply, or the government will not accept their
applications.
</TEXT>
