<FIRST>u a AM-ReligiousDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0697 05-10 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religious Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Science Parents Case Argued Before State High Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-11, `According to ..., to give boy's age, correct
spelling of `practictioner,' tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian Science couple who did not seek
medical attention for their dying son should not be tried for
manslaughter, their lawyer argued Wednesday at the state Supreme
Court.
   The outcome of the case is being watched closely by many of the
estimated 650,000 members of the Christian Science church who shun
doctors and medicine and espouse spiritual healing.
   Rikki Klieman, attorney for David and Ginger Twitchell, told
Judge Herbert Wilkins that state laws are so vague about such
matters a trial would be unfair, and the charges should be
dismissed.
   A 1971 amendment to the state child abuse and neglect law
recognized spiritual healing as an alternative to modern medicine.
Klieman said the law gives Christian Scientists no guidance as to
the point at which they must call in doctors.
   ``The problem is, they do not know what the law is,'' said
Klieman. ``They know they have been told by the Legislature that
they will not be prosecuted for caring for their children by
spiritual healing. But then they see that if something goes wrong,
or when it goes to a certain point, then they get indicted for
manslaughter.''
   John Kiernan, a special prosecutor representing the state,
argued that it is every parent's duty to care for the children. He
said a jury should have the opportunity to decide if the Twitchells
fulfilled that obligation.
   Klieman said it was unfair to ask a lay jury to decide a case
based on religious beliefs when the laws are unclear.
   Wilkins is expected to decide within two weeks whether to send
the case to the full Supreme Court or to a trial.
   The Twitchells did not appear in court Wednesday.
   According to police reports, the Twitchells' 2{-year-old son,
Robyn, became feverish and lethargic in early April 1986. The
Twitchells contacted a church practitioner, who came to their home
to pray for the boy's recovery.
   On the evening of his death, the boy went into convulsions and
lost consciousness and vital signs. The boy's father first called a
funeral director, who told him to contact the police. The boy was
pronounced dead at Carney Hospital in Boston.
   Klieman has the boy died from complications of a bowel
obstruction caused by a birth defect.
   A jury in Sarasota, Fla., last month found a Christian Science
couple guilty of murder for allowing their 7-year-old diabetic
daughter to die without medical attention.
   William and Christine Hermanson, who remain free pending
sentencing, were the first Christian Scientists in 20 years
prosecuted in the United States for denying a child medical care
for religious reasons, according to the church.
   The Church of Christ, Scientist, is located in Boston and the
denomination has about 3,200 branches worldwide.
</TEXT>
