<HEAD>Panama Expels Nine Journalists, Claims They `Misinformed'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government under Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega Wednesday expelled nine foreign journalists and
accused them of spreading misinformation on the political crisis, a
government spokesman said.
   ``These foreign correspondents have been misinforming in their
dispatches on the electoral process. Consequently, the Social
Communications Media Bureau has decided to ask them to leave the
country immediately,'' Luis Romero Villalobos, the bureau director,
told reporters.
   The bureau is part of the Ministry of Justice and Government,
which is also in charge of internal security.
   Among those expelled were Charles Jaco, an American working for
Cable News Network, and Michael Drudge and Ruben del Castillo of
the U.S. government's Voice of America, Romero said.
   Drudge is an American based in San Jose, Costa Rica.
   Also expelled were Domenique Petite and Arturo Gudino of Agence
France-Press, Jose Melendez and Javier Rojas of the Mexico City
newspaper Excelsior, and Lafit Fernandez of Costa Rica and Joaquin
Ibarz of the Spanish newspaper Vanguardia.
   The others' nationalities were not immediately availble.
