<FIRST>r w AM-UraniumPlant 490   05-10 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uranium Plant, 490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Plant's Medical Director Was An Animal Doctor, Union Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterinarian headed the medical operation of
the government's Fernald uranium-processing plant in Ohio until
recently, union officials told a congressional panel Wednesday.
   ``To me it is an obvious example of the casual attitude the
(Department of Energy) and their contractors took when dealing with
the health and very lives of the men and women who worked at these
facilities,'' Elmer Chatak of the AFL-CIO's industrial union
department told the House Health and Safety Subcommittee.
   A spokesman for the Feed Materials Production Center confirmed
that David Howell, who holds a degree in veterinary medicine, was
the plant's manager of medical services until April 13.
   Howell, who also holds an undergraduate degree in health
sciences and a graduate degree in pathology, did not ``perform
medical evaluations'' and was not considered the supervisor of the
three physicians who work at the plant on a subcontract basis, said
William Kelley, a spokesman for the plant's operator, Westinghouse
Materials of Ohio.
   ``He has not been a practicing veteriarian at all since his
affliation with Westinghouse,'' Kelley said.
   The medical services job involves overseeing medical records and
technologists, Kelley said. A new administrator has not yet been
named, he added.
   Howell was moved to another department as part of major
reorganization in which many department heads were changed, the
spokesman said.
   The Fernald plant, 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati, processes
uranium for use in nuclear weapons or as fuel for reactors.
   It is the subject of a $300 million suit on behalf of 14,000
people who live or work nearby and believe their health has been
threatened by radioactive discharges into the air and water. The
government has admitted ignoring or undermining efforts to reduce
pollution there.
   The government has estimated that as much as 552,000 pounds of
radioactive uranium dust may have escaped into the air from the
plant. An engineering consultant's report prepared as part of the
lawsuit said releases could be as high as 3.1 million pounds over
37 years.
   Workers have been complaining that they weren't adequately
protected from or told about the dangerous substances to which they
were exposed. Most of those complaints have been directed against
the plant's former operator, NLO Inc., which ran the plant until
1985.
   David Day, president of the Fernald Atomic Trades and Labor
Council, said workers had been unhappy with the plant's medical
staff in the past but that he is satisfied with recent changes and
with the current physicians.
   ``There were doctors that are no longer there that made
diagnoses that were incorrect,'' he said. ``Those doctors have been
replaced.''
   Wrong diagnoses included ``women who were told they had cancer
and they didn't have cancer,'' he said.
   Such episodes led workers to trust only certain doctors and
increased workers' fears about the risks associated with working at
the plant, Day said.
   Concerns increase with each new revelation about the extent of
radioactive releases over the years, he said.
</TEXT>
