<FIRST>r a AM-BreastCancer     05-10 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Breast Cancer,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Support Group Prolongs Breast Cancer Survival, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Breast cancer patients offered a
psychological support group lived an average of almost 18 months
longer than women who received only standard medical care,
concludes a study released Wednesday.
   ``I was quite stunned,'' said researcher David Spiegel, ``since
it was so contrary to what we expected to find.''
   The research provoked some skeptical reactions. One scientist
who has studied the impact of psychology on cancer said she found
the new results questionable.
   Spiegel, of the Stanford University School of Medicine,
presented the study at the annual meeting of the American
Psychiatric Association. He did the study with colleagues at
Stanford and the University of California at Berkeley.
   The work focused on the survival times of 86 women whose breast
cancer had spread elsewhere in their bodies. By random selection,
50 women were given a chance to participate in a weekly support
group for a year.
   Ten years later, researchers compared the survival times of the
two groups of people. Only a few women were still alive, and for
the study they were included as if they had died at the end of the
10 years.
   Analysis showed that the average survival time of women offered
the support group was 36.6 months, in contrast to 18.9 months for
the other women. Survival time was measured from the point the
women entered the study.
   Analysis showed that the survival difference began to appear
about eight months after the support group began, Spiegel said.
   Women in the support group category were comparable to those in
the comparison category on key characteristics, except for stage of
cancer at the time they were diagnosed. Support group women on
average were at an earlier stage, but Spiegel said further analysis
convinced him that staging did not explain the survival difference.
   Troy Thompson, psychiatry professor at Jefferson Medical College
in Philadelphia, said in an interview after Spiegel's talk that the
staging difference still made him skeptical.
   The research should be duplicated to see if the same result
occurs, he said. ``Sometimes when something sounds too good to be
true, it is,'' he said.
   Barrie Cassileth, director of psychosocial research at the
University of Pennsylvania Cancer Center, said in a telephone
interview that the study's conclusion was ``highly questionable.''
   While conclusions were based on survival of the 50 women who
were offered the support group, only 34 attended any sessions and
only 18 attended more than 10 sessions, she noted from the reported
data.
   So it is not clear whether enough women attended enough sessions
to be sure the program really had a chance to influence survival,
Cassileth said.
   Cassileth said, however that research into psychological impacts
on cancer should be encouraged and that support groups are
important for improving quality of life and social interaction for
cancer patients.
   Another researcher who has studied psychological impacts on
cancer said that despite some limitations in the new study, she
believes it does suggest the support groups made a difference.
   ``It looked to me that they have something,'' said Sandra Levy,
associate professor of psychiatry and medicine at the University of
Pittsburgh School of Medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
