<FIRST>r w AM-DiplomaticNominations     05-10 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomatic Nominations,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Delays Action on Bush's Arms Negotiator, Approves Other
Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Wednesday recommended Senate approval of six key diplomatic
appointments but delayed action on three others, including that of
Richard R. Burt to be the new U.S. strategic arms negotiator.
   Burt, now U.S. ambassador to West Germany and a former assistant
secretary of state for European affairs, is under fire by Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., for allegedly publishing classified material a
decade ago in the position he then held as a national security
correspondent for The New York Times.
   Helms asserted at a hearing last week that a June 29, 1979
article headlined ``US Plans New Way to Check Soviet Missile
Tests,'' disclosed ``highly classified information'' involving the
then-new U.S. chalet satellite system. Helms said the Pentagon
believed the disclosure that an antenna associated with the system
was located at a base in Norway would jeopardize Norway's delicate
relations with the Soviet Union.
   Burt said he wrote the story ``not believing at the time that
this would be extremely damaging.''
   Helms also questioned Burt's relationship with a New York Times
reporter while he held his State Department position.
   Helms contended that the reporter, Judith Miller, published a
number of articles allegedly based on classified material
concerning issues with which Burt dealt professionally. The senator
implied, but did not explicitly state, that Burt may have been Miss
Miller's source.
   Burt said he never provided such information to Miss Miller or
any other reporter and that he and Miss Miller had a clear
understanding that he would not do so.
   Burt said he had told Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig Jr.
and his successor, George P. Shultz, that he and Miss Miller had a
social relationship. He said they had told him it was ``none of
their business'' because they trusted Burt's discretion and sense
of responsibility.
   A reporter who twice telephoned the office in New York of Max
Frankel, the Times' executive editor, was told Wednesday there was
no one immediately available to comment.
   Helm's objection to the immediate consideration of the Burt
nomination delays action on it for at least once week.
   The committee also postponed action, apparently for technical
reasons, on the nominations of Michigan Republican activist Peter
F. Secchia to be U.S. ambassador to Italy and Douglas P. Mulholland
to be assistant secretary of state for intelligence and research.
   The panel recommended Senate approval of these nominations:
   _Charles E. Redman, a former State Department spokesman, to be
ambassador to Sweden.
   _Walter J. P. Curley, a New York executive, to be ambassador to
France.
   _Joseph Vernor Reed, to hold the rank of ambassador while
serving as chief of protocol for the White House.
   _Ronald F. Lehman II to be director of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency.
   _Herman Jay Cohen to be an assistant secretary of State for
African affairs.
   _Morris B. Abram to be the U.S. representative to the European
office of the United Nations.
   A committee fight is expected to erupt Friday during
confirmation hearings on the qualifications of Donald Gregg to
serve as ambassador to South Korea. Gregg was Bush's national
security adviser when Bush was vice president.
   Several Democratic senators, including Sen. Alan Cranston,
D-Calif., believe Gregg misled the congressional Iran-Contra
committees as to the role played in the affair by both himself and
Bush. Some Republicans say Democrats are attacking Gregg out of
partisan considerations.
   Some committee members, meanwhile, complain that the
administration has been unusually slow in submitting nominations
for many key diplomatic and State Department positions.
   Nominations have yet to be received, for example, to fill the
posts of assistant secretaries of state for Europe, Asia, the Near
East and Latin America.
</TEXT>
