<FIRST>r a AM-WinerySlayings     05-10 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carmina Leaves Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old recovering from wounds
allegedly suffered when her father slashed her throat in a bloody
murder spree was quietly released from a hospital Wednesday and
left with her grandfather.
   Carmina Salcido ``was really in a good mood. She knew she was
leaving and she was excited about that,'' said Petaluma Valley
Hospital spokeswoman Mary Frost.
   Carmina's grandfather, Robert Richards of Cotati, applied for
her custody following the April rampage in which Ramon Salcido
allegedly murdered his wife, two daughters, his mother-in-law, two
sisters-in-law and a co-worker.
   Carmina was found abandoned at a Sonoma County dump along with
her two sisters, Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1. All had their throats
cut; only Carmina survived.
   Frost said the child's morning departure with her grandfather
and other relatives was kept secret to allow the family to ``leave
in peace,'' without the news media fanfare generated by the
slayings.
   She declined to say where the family will live.
   Doctors will see Carmina to make sure her wound heals properly
during the next few months, Frost said, and although she may have
cosmetic surgery to lessen the scar on her neck, she won't require
additional surgery.
   A tracheotomy performed on Carmina will be removed in a few
weeks and doctors expect no lasting damage to her larynx. ``She's
more than whispering. She's talking,'' Frost said.
   Before Carmina's release, officials met in a closed hearing
before Sonoma County Superior Court Judge Arnold Rosenfield to
discuss her custody. Rosenfield ordered hearing participants not to
discuss the matter and set another hearing for May 30.
   Salcido's preliminary hearing has been set for September, but
Sonoma County Public Defender Marteen Miller has said he will ask
the court to rule Salcido's arrest and deportation from his native
Mexico after the crimes were illegal.
   Salcido could face the death penalty if convicted of the murders
that authorities said may have been fueled by jealousy, drug abuse
and marital trouble.
   The killings and Carmina's survival elicited contributions of
hundreds of toys and stuffed animals for her from well-wishers
around the country.
   In addition, more than $180,000 has been collected in 10
separate trust funds for the families of people authorities say
were slain by Salcido.
   A trust fund for Carmina was opened Wednesday with $1,065
donated by jail officers and inmates at the same jail where her
father is held. Money will continue to be collected for two weeks,
then the fund will be closed until Carmina turns 13.
   That account was initiated by a prisoner counseling group run by
the Rev. Bob Gutleben, the Sonoma County jail's unofficial chaplain.
   He said inmates, many of them abused as children, suggested the
10-year account so funds will be available ``for whatever special
needs she may develop'' as she becomes a teen-ager.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
