<DOCNO> AP890510-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-WHO-PLO     05-10 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WHO-PLO,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Bloc Joins West to Delay Vote on PLO Membership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet bloc delegations and the West united on
Wednesday to delay for two days a decision on the PLO bid for full
membership in the World Health Organization. Arab nations had
sought an immediate vote.
   Most African delegations also supported a motion, proposed by
Austria and seconded by Canada, to delay the choice between rival
resolutions until Friday.
   It carried 56-47 with 20 abstentions, mostly by Latin American
countries, according to an unofficial tally.
   Of the 160 delegations, 37 were absent. Votes were cast by
holding up nameplates of member nations.
   Iraq said after the vote it had wanted a roll call, but that
Chen Min-Zhang of China, the chairman, ignored the request to speak.
   Two draft resolutions are before the WHO assembly. One,
sponsored by all 21 Arab members, would have the organization
decide ``to admit the State of Palestine.''
   The other is designed to avert a showdown with the United
States, which has threatened to halt payments to any U.N. agency
that gives full membership to the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which now has non-voting observer status in the U.N.
system. In November, the PLO legislative body declared an
independent Palestinian state.
   Nine Western and Third World countries support the compromise,
which would combine deferral of the issue until the 1990 assembly
with a call for more aid to residents of the Israeli-occupied
lands, where a Palestinian uprising began 17 months ago.
   By adopting it, the assembly also would express hope ``that the
Palestinian people will be fully represented within the WHO by
their legitimate representatives.''
   That language apparently addresses developing countries that
sympathize with the PLO application but are worried by the warning
from Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima, director general of WHO, that loss of
U.S. funds would ``completely destroy the agency.'' The United
States this year paid the agency $71 million, a quarter of its
annual budget.
   The United States and its Western allies say the nation
proclaimed by the PLO does not fulfill internationally accepted
criteria of statehood, including control of a defined territory and
a capital.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker II has said admitting the PLO
would harm the Middle East peace process and the entire U.N. system.
   On Tuesday, the PLO said it would apply for admission to three
more U.N. agencies: the U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization, based in Paris; the Food and Agriculture Organization
in Rome and the International Labor Organization, whose
headquarters are in Geneva.
   The labor organization probably would be the next target because
its annual conference opens June 7 and its statutes allow
applications for membership to be submitted at any time, even
during the meeting. Admission would require a two-thirds majority,
however, rather than the simple majority stipulated by WHO.
   From 1977 to 1980, the United States withdrew from the
International Labor Organization to protest what it described as
politicization and an anti-Western bias.
   U.S. contributions to the World Health Organization this year
total about $94 million to the regular budget and special programs
to fight specific diseases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
