<DOCNO> AP890510-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-10 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dispute Hits Kohl Government Over Handling of NATO Missile Feud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major dispute has broken out within
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition government over the handling of
NATO's missile feud by Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher,
officials said Wednesday.
   The Munich newspaper Sueddeutsche Zeitung said Genscher angered
Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg by not toning down remarks
aimed at the United States and Britain about short-range nuclear
weapons.
   It said officials within Kohl's Christian Democratic Union and
its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union, fear the
NATO feud could damage West German-U.S. relations.
   Sources within the parties, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the newspaper's account.
   Kohl and Genscher have called for East-West negotiations to
reduce short-range nuclear weapons, which would be used on German
soil. The United States and Britain strongly oppose such talks.
   Genscher has taken the lead in pressing the issue, while Kohl
appears to be standing back to give North Atlantic Treaty
Organization nations a chance to patch up differences.
   In TV and radio interviews, Genscher has also been vocal in his
opposition to making an immediate decision on whether to upgrade
NATO's short-range nuclear missiles.
   He said on May 4, ``We have the first and last word about the
stationing of rockets on our territory, and no one else.''
   Most NATO short-range nuclear weapons are based in West Germany.
   Sueddeutsche Zeitung quoted Stoltenberg as saying Genscher ``is
not among those who contribute to a calming'' of NATO's internal
dispute.
   It further quoted him as saying, ``It is comical that Genscher
appeals for other coalition partners to soften their own remarks
while he constantly speaks his own mind.''
   Stoltenberg is a Christian Democrat. Genscher is a Free
Democrat, the junior partner in Kohl's coalition.
   The newspaper reported Michaela Geiger, foreign affairs expert
of the Christian Social Union, as accusing Genscher of using his
power within the coalition to give the mistaken impression that the
Bonn government wants short-range nuclear weapons eliminated
completely.
   Other Christian Social Union and Christian Democratic officials
fear the NATO feud could ``damage the American view of Germany,''
the newspaper said.
   The comments were made during a private meeting Monday night of
officials of the sister parties, the newspaper said.
   The Defense Ministry meanwhile announced that Stoltenberg would
visit the United States from May 17-19 for discussions that will
include defense topics.
   He will meet with Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, said ministry spokesman Winfried Dunkel.
   The Warsaw Pact also wants negotiations on short-range nuclear
weapons, and denounces NATO plans to upgrade its short-range Lance
rockets.
   NATO says Lance missiles will be have be replaced because of
their age, and plans to upgrade the rockets by extending their
range.
   The West German news magazine Stern quoted Yuli Kvitsinsky, the
Soviet ambassador in Bonn, as saying that increasing the range of
Lance rockets would ``destroy the basis'' of the Intermediate
Nuclear Forces treaty, under which the two superpowers are
eliminating intermediate-range nuclear rockets.
   ``If NATO now builds a missile that perhaps has a range of 20 to
50 kilometers (12 to 30 miles) less than our SS-23, that is a
betrayal,'' Kvitsinsky was quoted as saying.
   Soviet SS-23 rockets are being eliminated under the INF treaty.
   Stern telexed excerpts of the interview to other news
organizations in advance of Thursday's publication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
