<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-10 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms West of Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms rattled through the Plateau region west of
the central Rockies on Wednesday, and heavy rain fell in much of
New Jersey.
   A thunderstorm in southwestern Montana produced wind gusts of up
to 75 mph near Butte.
   In Idaho, a late morning thunderstorm produced high winds at
Palisades that destroyed a small shed and damaged roofs and storm
doors. Later, one-inch diameter hail fell at Burley, in southern
Idaho.
   A severe thunderstorm watch also took in parts of western
Wyoming.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from southern Texas to
northern Florida and southern Georgia, with the showers and
thunderstorms most numerous along the central Gulf Coast, and
across Florida and Georgia.
   Rain showers fell from the lower Great Lakes region and the
upper Ohio Valley across southern New England.
   Through mid-Wednesday, about two-thirds to 1{ inches of rain
fell in northern New Jersey, where flood watches were issued.
   Skies were mostly sunny in the Southwestern deserts, across much
of the Great Plains region and upper Mississippi Valley, and in the
upper Great Lakes region.
   Rainfall totals for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT ranged up to
1.7 inches at Millville, N.J., and .82 inches as Jacksonville, Fla.
   Record low temperatures for the date were 37 degrees in Kansas
City, Mo., and 43 in South Bend, Ind.
   Temperatures warmed into the 70s across the northern Plains
region, 80s across the Florida peninsula, southern Texas, and the
Southwestern deserts. Clouds and rain kept temperatures in the 40s
and 50s in the lower Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio Valley.
   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s in the upper Great Lakes
region, but were expected to drop back into the 30s overnight.
Frost and freeze warnings were posted for northern and western
Lower Michigan.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 90 degrees at Avon Park, Fla., and
West Palm Beach, Fla. The low for the nation Wednesday morning was
27 degrees at Marquette, Mich.
   The forecast for Thursday was scattered showers and
thunderstorms extending across much of the nation west of the Great
Plains, and most numerous across Utah, Nevada, Idaho and western
Montana. Numerous rain showers were predicted across the upper Ohio
Valley, lower Great Lakes region and the middle and northern
Atlantic Coast states.
   High temperatures were forecast below 70 degrees from North
Carolina and Tennessee to the Great Lakes and the northern Atlantic
Coast, and along the Pacific Coast and west of the central Rockies;
the lower 80s in North Dakota and northeastern Montana; and, above
80 from southern California through southern and central Texas to
southern Florida.
</TEXT>
