<FIRST>r i AM-ShipFire     05-10 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Fire,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bodies From USS White Plains Fire Arrive in Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARK AIR BASE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of U.S. naval
forces in the Philippines and other Navy personnel mourned
Wednesday at a ceremony over the flag-draped coffins of six sailors
killed by a ship fire.
   The bodies of the six, who died Tuesday, arrived at this
American-run base 50 miles north of Manila on a Navy C-2 transport
plane.
   Three weeks earlier, an explosion inside a gun turret on the
battleship Iowa left 47 sailors dead off Puerto Rico.
   In Tuesday's accident, the sailors were killed and five others
injured Tuesday when fire broke out in the engine room of the USS
White Plains. It was in the South China Sea 100 miles east of Hong
Kong, heading back to the Pacific island of Guam after supporting
Persian Gulf operations.
   About 100 people were on hand Wednesday when the coffins, each
draped in an American flag, were taken off a the plane.
   ``We mourn six brave Americans in this tragic accident,'' Rear
Adm. Roger Rich, commander of U.S. naval forces in the Philippines,
said during the ceremony. ``This is an irreplaceable loss for our
country. This is an irreplaceable loss for the American people.''
   Crewmen aboard the White Plains, a food stores ship, battled the
blaze for more than an hour before bringing it under control.
   U.S. officials said the White Plains was being towed toward the
American-run base at Subic Bay, 50 miles west of Manila. Navy
spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Kevin Mukri said the vessel was expected to
arrive by Sunday.
   He said a U.S. Navy team was being assembled to investigate what
caused the blaze.
   In Washington, Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said the fire
occurred ``in the main engine spaces.'' A Navy source said it
apparently involved a fuel leak in and around the ship's No. 3
boiler.
   The 581-foot White Plains is based at Guam and normally carries
403 enlisted men and 25 officers.
   The fatalities were identified as Boiler Technician 3rd Class
Muoi Cao, 22, of Ventura, Calif.; Fireman Apprentice Todd Allan
Follis, 22, of Lake Nebagamon, Wis.; Machinist Mate-Fireman
Apprentice Paul Dennis Novotny, 22, of Howells, Neb.; Fireman
Apprentice Darryl D. Edwards, 20, of Flossmor, Ill.; Boiler
Technician Baxter Lesarlley, 26, of Santa Fe, N.M., and Boiler
Technician 2nd Class Jon David Ruhmel, 20, Elmira, N.Y.
   The Navy earlier said Follis was from Zuni, N.M.
   The Navy identified the injured as Damage Controlman 2nd Class
James Henry Britt, 24, of Nashville, Tenn.; Machinist Mate 3rd
Class Keith Gerald Landry, 22, of Greenwell Springs, La.;
Boatswain's Mate 2nd Class Darryl Jerome Williams, 24, of
Birmingham, Ala.; Chief Boiler Technician Walter Rufus Greggs Jr.,
41, of Mobile, Ala.; and Boiler Technician 1st Class William Carl
Glascoe, 25, of Randolph, N.J.
   None of the victims' relatives were on hand for the ceremony.
Murki said the bodies were brought to Clark because it has a large
mortuary. He said he was uncertain when the bodies would be flown
to the United States.
   Howard and Navy spokesmen said the five injured suffered
primarily second-and third-degree burns and were airlifted to the
military hospital at Clark. Mukri said all were listed in stable
condition.
</TEXT>
