<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     05-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Attack 16 Towns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas launched an
offensive Wednesday with attacks on military positions in 16 towns,
and at least 54 combants were killed or wounded.
   The rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said the
early morning push was aimed at showing the Front's fighting muscle
to the rightist party about to assume the presidency.
   Preliminary reports gathered from the army, rebels and civilian
sources indicated at least 34 soldiers and 20 rebels were killed or
wounded in six of the towns. Others reported no casualties.
   The rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos said the drive was
called ``Everyone Against Arena in the Fight for Peace.''
   Arena is the Spanish acronym for the right-wing Republican
Nationalist Alliance. Arena President-elect Alfredo Cristiani is to
take office on June 1.
   The rebels say an Arena government will mean wider polarization
in war-torn El Salvador and a resurgence in violent repression of
political opponents.
   The rebels say the armed forces and Arena are targeting leftist
sympathizers in a campaign of searches, assassinations and arrests.
   Nidia Diaz, a commander of the Front, claimed at a news
conference in Managua, capital of neighboring Nicaragua, that
guerrillas killed or wounded 67 Salvadoran army officers and
enlisted men in all, but gave no breakdown.
   The attacks were meant to show ``the FMLN could attack various
points simultaneously and use different forces and methods of
combat,'' she said.
   She said guerrillas also blew up power lines and carried out
other acts of sabotage.
   Sources said attacks damaged at least two telecommunications
offices, two coffee-processing plants, a gasoline station, six
homes and several electricity poles and towers.
   An armed forces communique said three soldiers were killed and
seven wounded in the heaviest fighting, a four-hour clash in
Tejutepeque, 37 miles northeast of San Salvador.
   It said an intercepted rebel radio transmission indicated 20
rebels were killed or wounded in fighting Wednesday.
   The rebels fired mortars at 3rd Infantry Brigade headquarters in
San Miguel, 85 miles east of San Salvador, hitting a gasoline
storage facility, the armed forces said. About 2,800 gallons of
fuel burned.
   Mortar shells fell in open areas and no casualties or further
damage were reported, the communique said.
   Five homes were damaged when rebels directed mortar fire against
a civilian defense post in Aguilares, 20 miles north of San
Salvador, it said.
   Rebels said 13 soldiers were killed or wounded in Anamoros, 118
miles northeast of San Salvador.
   An estimated 70,000 people have been killed in the 9-year-old
war, most of them civilians.
</TEXT>
