<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Housing     05-10 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Housing,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Outlines Program, Faces Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing chief Jack Kemp on Wednesday praised
anti-drug efforts now underway in public housing, but some housing
residents complained that poor management and unfair eviction
practices have turned them into victims of the nation's drug
problem.
   Citing programs developed in Trenton, N.J., Washington, D.C. and
St. Louis, Kemp praised success in ``the counter-movement'' among
tenants to wrestle control of public housing projects from drug
dealers.
   Kemp, the secretary of Housing and Urban Development, also told
the Senate's Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations he is
encouraged by successful anti-drug strategies used by public
housing authorities.
   But tenants said public housing managers weren't doing enough to
fight drug trade.
   Edith Grisby, a Washington, D.C. resident, said public housing
managers should ``live in public housing'' and be present 24 hours
a day so they could take immediate action when tenants reported
drug problems.
   ``My building wouldn't need one more dime of appropriations from
you in order for it to be run correctly,'' said Charles Jenkins,
another District resident, echoing Grisby's complaints about poor
management.
   One of Kemp's first major actions was to ask public housing
administrators asking them what they were doing to combat drugs.
That query came after he witnessed drug sales while touring housing
developments in several cities.
   Last month, Kemp outlined a series of anti-drug actions _
issuance of photo tenant identification cards, installation of
security fences around projects and increased police patrols _
available to local public housing authorities.
   ``I want to be tough on drugs but I also want to be tough on due
process,'' said Kemp, emphasizing he has waived HUD administrative
grievance procedures to help speed evictions of suspected drug
dealer only in Virginia and Massachusetts.
   ``If your child is doing drugs, it is your responsibility to
deal with that situation. You don't ask the federal government to
take your child to the hospital when he or she has a broken leg,''
said Grisby, backing Kemp's actions.
   ``We don't believe we can make a strong case for eviction unless
(a person's) lease has been violated,'' said Mary Ann Russ,
executive director of public housing in Wilmington, Del.
   Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., the subcommittee's ranking
minority member whose staff investigation prompted the hearing,
noted that Congress three years ago authorized evictions for
drug-related criminal activity in public housing.
   But Herman M. Holloway Jr., a former Delaware state
representative, warned that many ``long-time tenants in good
standing'' are being hurt by hastily conceived eviction procedures.
   Meantime, rain virtually washed out a ``Save Public Housing
Day'' rally by members of the National Tenants Organization, where
about 250 people gathered at Lafayette Park across from the White
House to protest the lack of federal money for construction and
rehabilitation.
</TEXT>
