<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-BusStrike     05-10 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Bus Strike,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Bus Employees Began Returning To Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking city bus employees began returning
to work Wednesday after a labor court ordered more negotiations on
wages.
   ``The service is being resumed immediately and by tomorrow most
of the buses will probably be back,'' said Rafael Cardona,
spokesman for the city administration.
   Judge Maria Esther Cervantes issued an injunction Tuesday night
on the strike and a subsequent lockout, ordering that negotiations
resume. The 23,000 bus employees went on strike May 3.
   After her ruling, union and city officials agreed to incorporate
the bus system into a new transit authority to be established
``within the next few weeks,'' Cardona said in a telephone
interview.
   Public transit in Mexico City also includes a subway, high-speed
street cars and minibuses.
   Before the walkout, the bus system carried an estimated 2
million passengers daily in 3,900 aging buses notorious for spewing
thick clouds of diesel exhaust into Mexico City's badly polluted
air. The buses were dirty, usually ran late and were playgrounds
for pickpockets.
   Millions of commuters were stranded when the bus system's
drivers, mechanics and administrative employees walked out,
demanding pay raises of 50 percent. The strike was declared
illegal, and the city said it was firing all of them.
   The city began taking strikers back on Wednesday, but whether
all 23,000 would be rehired was not clear. No date was set for the
pay negotiations.
   Bus drivers are paid about $9,000 a year, more than four times
the average wage of a public school teacher. Mayor Manuel Camacho
Solis has called them the highest-paid transit workers in Mexico.
   City officials brought 1,000 buses in from a neighboring state
during the strike and pressed hundreds of military vehicles into
service.
</TEXT>
