<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     05-10 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Strike Begins With Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-day general strike ordered by
leftist rebels opened Wednesday with attacks on vehicles, a
railroad bridge, and electricity towers.
   No one was reported injured in the violence, which police blamed
on the guerrillas.
   Most public agencies, private businesses and schools were closed
in this highland city, and traffic was reduced to a trickle.
   The Shining Path guerrillas ordered the strike in a three-state
area around Huancayo, about 140 miles east of Lima, by spreading
leaflets in the streets this week. They threatened violence against
anyone who did not participate.
   In Lima, the government was expected to announce Cabinet changes
soon to deal with rising rebel violence, which has left two
congressmen killed over the past two weeks.
   Police said the insurgents bombed two power pylons and caused a
blackout in the Huancayo area before dawn. They also exploded
several bombs across this city of 100,000, authorities said.
   Insurgents blew up a railroad bridge 12 miles to the north,
officials said.
   Police said rebels confronted four buses and seven trucks,
ordering out passengers and drivers and setting the vehicles on
fire.
   Rebels began such strikes about a year ago to foment economic
chaos.
   Their nine-year-long insurgency aims at imposing Marxist rule in
Peru. More than 14,000 people have died in the fighting, including
about 1,000 this year.
</TEXT>
