<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Austria-Sinowatz     05-10 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Austria-Sinowatz,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Chancellor To Be Charged With Perjury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Chancellor Fred Sinowatz will be
charged with perjury in connection with testimony in a 1987 trial
that arose from a probe into President Kurt Waldheim's World War II
past, the justice minister said Wednesday.
   Justice Minister Egmont Foregger did not specify which
statements by Sinowatz were thought to be false.
   In October 1987, Sinowatz lost a libel suit against a journalist
who quoted Sinowatz as telling fellow politicians two years earlier
that Austria would become aware of Waldheim's past.
   Waldheim's controversial background as a German army lieutenant
in World War II was first publicly disclosed in March 1986 in
reports by The New York Times, the Austrian weekly Profil and the
World Jewish Congress.
   The question of who released the documents on Waldheim's past
has never been answered.
   Waldheim won over a candidate from Sinowatz's Socialist Party in
the 1986 presidential election, which was marked by fierce
controversy over Waldheim's past.
   At the 1987 trial, Sinowatz denied under oath a report by
journalist Alfred Worm that he said in late 1985 Austria would soon
learn of Waldheim's past.
   Sinowatz resigned as chancellor a day after Waldheim was elected
president in June 1986.
   Waldheim denies he was involved in Nazi war crimes during his
service in the Balkans, as media reports alleged.
   An international commission of historians appointed to probe
Waldheim's past concluded in February 1988 it had no evidence he
was involved in war crimes, but said Waldheim concealed his past
and was in close proximity to Nazi crimes when in the Balkans.
</TEXT>
