<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama 3rdLd-writethru a0770-a0765 05-10 0995</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 3rd Ld-writethru, a0770-a0765,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Spokesman Says Noriega Causing Violence After Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with U.S. personnel detained, adds 2 grafs after 12th
previous, ``A senior''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Wednesday accused
Panama's leader Manuel Antonio Noriega of ``blatant attempts at
intimidation'' and of responsibility for violence against
opposition leaders but wouldn't say how the United States might
respond.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said President Bush
``condemned the violence now under way in Panama,'' including an
attack on opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara.
   Fitzwater said Noriega thwarted the desire of the people of
Panama for democracy ``by conducting a fraudulent election. ... He
has now escalated this to include violence against opposition
leaders, including Mr. Endara.''
   Endara was injured when police broke up an opposition
demonstration Wednesday.
   Fitzwater said Bush tried to call Endara in the hospital, where
he appeared before reporters in a wheelchair, but could not reach
him.
   Bush received a first-hand account on the deteriorating
situation in Panama from the U.S. ambassador there in a late
afternoon phone call, Fitzwater said.
   He said ``reported harassment of U.S. servicemen'' was one of
the topics of discussion.
   ``The president also contacted the leadership of other countries
with interests in the region,'' Fitzwater said. ``Those
conversations related to Latin American unity in facing the blatant
attempts at intimidation now being conducted by the Noriega
regime.''
   ``This action underscores that General Noriega does not have the
interests of the Panamanian people at heart,'' Fitzwater said.
   He declined to say how the United States might respond.
   Bush discussed the situation at the White House in a hastily
called afternoon meeting of his national security advisers.
   A senior official, speaking on condition he not be identified by
name, told reporters the administration didn't want to signal what
actions might be taken or when. As for possible military action or
increasing U.S. forces in Panama, the official said he wouldn't
comment on any military actions but that U.S. forces would be
prepared to take whatever action might be necessary.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. military's Southern Command, responding to
reports of violence in Panama City, upgraded an alert to a level
meaning servicemen and their families should ``limit all movement
... should not go into public areas in Panama except for essential
business.''
   No other special precautions or troop movements have been
ordered, Pentagon officials said.
   In Panama, Panamanian defense forces detained three American
army soldiers for three hours because they were taking pictures in
the vicinity of a car carrying Noriega, said Mercedes Morris, a
spokeswoman for the Southern Command.
   In a separate incident, two U.S. military attaches, both Army
majors, were detained by Panamanian defense forces during an
opposition demonstration, according to a U.S. official who declined
to be identified.
   Earlier, U.S. officials said it was important that the United
States make a ``credible demonstration'' of U.S. resolve following
Sunday's national election, which Bush contended was marked by
``massive irregularities.''
   But there were significant drawbacks to virtually all the
proposals designed to bring about quick results, according to the
officials, who asked not to be identified.
   Significant military action or abrogation of the canal treaties
seemed out of the question, the officials said, because such
actions could touch off a wave of anti-Americanism throughout the
hemisphere and encourage sabotage against the Panama Canal.
   In addition, either could lead to retaliatory action against
some of the 50,000 Americans living in Panama.
   Imposing a trade embargo has major drawbacks, the officials
said, because this could deal a devastating blow to the extensive
U.S. business interests in Panama.
   One alternative apparently not ruled out was a legal effort to
seize Noriega's foreign assets, believed to total in the hundreds
of millions of dollars.
   For the third day in a row, the administration accused Noriega
of orchestrating the results in favor of his handpicked candidate,
Carlos Duque.
   ``Having failed to rig the election in advance, Noriega is now
doing everything he can to steal it after the fact despite the
clear message from the people of Panama,'' State Department deputy
spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   In answer to a question during an appearance in Philadelphia,
Vice President Dan Quayle declined to discuss what steps the
administration might take.
   ``The president has all the options,'' he said. ``I'm not going
into that. The people of Panama have spoken. Noriega ought to
accept the view of the people. We should be patient while the
president considers the course to take.''
   ``There was no support for Noriega from any segment of the
Panamanian population. He must go,'' Quayle said.
   Peter Rodman, a National Security Council aide, told a gathering
in Washington that he believes there is reason for hope in Panama.
   ``I am encourged by the fact that a major event has just taken
place, and I am not sure it is so easy for Noriega to contain it,''
Rodman said. ``In the end, maybe he will contain it, but I think an
unmanageable problem has been created.''
   With a few exceptions, much of the rest of the hemisphere seemed
content to await future developments in Panama before taking a
stand on the election process.
   At the Organization of American States, U.S. delegate William T.
Pryce called on OAS nations Wednesday to add their voice to the
``international outcry against the Noriega regime'' and what he
described as its efforts to oppose the will of the Panamanian
people.
   The delegates from Peru and El Salvador criticized Panama but,
as one U.S. official put it, ``there was a lot of temporizing'' by
other representatives.
   Mexico, in particular, sees national elections as an internal
matter which should not be the subject of international criticism.
   A number of countries will be holding elections over the next
year in Latin America and some delegates believe silence on the
Panamanian election now could spare their governments criticism if
their election processes do not go smoothly, the official said.
</TEXT>
