<FIRST>r w AM-HHS-Fulton     05-10 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HHS-Fulton,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Voiced to HHS Appointment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six right-to-life senators signed a letter to
President Bush on Wednesday expressing their continued opposition
to Health Secretary Louis Sullivan's choice of an Oklahoma state
official for a top agency job.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., who drafted the letter, said a
meeting last week attended by a half dozen senators, Sullivan and
his candidate, Robert Fulton, did little to allay his concerns that
Fulton does not share their right-to-life views on matters
involving handicapped infants.
   ``It would be just inappropriate for Mr. Fulton to serve in a
high position at HHS,'' Humphrey said in an interview Tuesday.
   He declined to release the letter, but his spokesman said that
in addition to Humphrey, it was signed by Sens. William Armstrong,
R-Colo.; Dan Coats, R-Ind.; Phil Gramm, R-Texas; Jesse Helms,
R-N.C.; and Steve Symms, R-Idaho.
   When informed of the letter, Fulton said: ``I'm disappointed I
haven't been able to reassure them and I'm still very interested in
the job and hope I can be endorsed by the president.''
   Sullivan has been pushing the White House to name the Oklahoma
secretary of social services as head of the Family Services
Administration at HHS, which manages the government's major welfare
programs.
   Fulton, however, is opposed by right-to-life groups who
criticise him for failing to act when, as director of the state
human services department, he became aware of an alleged state
hospital policy to withhold life-saving care from babies with the
crippling deformity spina bifida. Before Fulton became director, 24
spina bifida babies denied surgery at the hospital died in a
five-year period ending in 1983.
   Fulton fends off the criticism by saying that shortly after he
took office and became aware of the deaths, he put into effect new
federal regulations requiring medical treatment for all infants,
unless the treatment would be futile or would shorten the baby's
life.
   He said that while he served in the top two health offices in
Oklahoma, only one spina bifida infant died and that child died of
complications from multiple birth defects.
   Sullivan ran afoul of right-to-life advocates after he was
nominated for the HHS job when twice he reportedly made pro-choice
comments about abortion. Each time he responded to pro-life critics
by saying he shared President Bush's opposition to abortion.
   Fulton has been actively supported for the HHS post by Oklahoma
Gov. Henry Bellmon, said White House personnel chief Chase
Untermeyer.
   But Untermeyer said that no decision has been made. While Fulton
remains a candidate, he said, ``on something this controversial
we'd be looking at a broad range of candidates.''
</TEXT>
