<FIRST>r a AM-PittstonMeeting     05-10 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pittston Meeting,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikers Meet Management in Annual Meeting Showdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miner Steve Hamilton did something
Wednesday that most other workers only dream about: He confronted
the chairman of his company and told him why he's out on strike.
   Paul W. Douglas, chairman and chief executive officer of The
Pittson Co., listened patiently as Hamilton addressed shareholders
at the company's annual meeting before responding in a calm voice.
   ``The human needs and values of our employees are very much on
our minds,'' Douglas said. He said Pittston needs concessions from
1,700 striking miners in Virginia and West Virgina so Pittston can
modernize and become more flexible.
   Hamilton, a 27-year-old heavy equipment operator from
Castlewood, Va., refused to accept the explanation.
   ``You want us to say we will work seven days a week. We can't go
to church because we have to observe our jobs,'' he said. ``There
are several issues that you are trying to sugarcoat. It's a whole
lot more than you're willing to say.''
   Douglas shrugged off the criticism, saying, ``It's a question of
proper communication.''
   The dialogue ended in a standoff, but both sides later claimed
victory on three proxy issues submitted to the shareholders by the
United Mine Workers and opposed by management.
   Hamilton was one of a few miners and union leaders allowed to
attend the annual meeting in a cramped, third-floor lunchroom at
Pittston headquarters. The session lasted more than three hours as
labor and mangement argued about Pittston's corporate goals as well
as strike issues.
   About 200 other miners and their supporters rallied outside the
building despite a steady downpour. The rally was noisy and the
voices of the chanting crowd could be heard during the annual
meeting, but no arrests were made.
   Violence has marked the strike since it began April 5. More than
1,300 coal miners and their spouses have been arrested in Virginia
and West Virginia since the walkout began, with 140 of those people
charged with felonies.
   The union's main effort was concentrated on the meeting, where
leaders pushed for the acceptance of three proposals questioning
the operation of Pittston. The national union and UMW Local 950
through their Pittston Independent Shareholders Committeee own
1,721 shares of Pittston stock, enabling the miners to include
items on the proxy ballot.
   Kenneth Zinn, the union's director of special projects, said a
goal of the three proxy issues was to return the company to ``good
corporate governance.''
   Douglas told shareholders the proposals were nothing more than
an attempt by the union to enhance its contract negotiations.
   The first proposal asked that shareholders be allowed to vote on
the anti-takeover or ``poison pill'' measures adopted by
management. The second proposal called for secret ballots during
annual meetings, and the third asked to establish a committee to
study the possible sale of subsidiaries.
   Union leaders said after the meeting that the vote was close,
but they believed they had won a majority of the company's 38
million shares. Douglas agreed that the vote was close, but said
``no'' votes would tally just over 50 percent on the first
proposal, well over 50 percent on the second and 80 percent on the
final proposal.
   The results of the vote won't be known until June 12, when
auditors are to report at a special meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
