<FIRST>r i AM-BBCStrike     05-10 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BBC Strike,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>BBC Strike Cuts Schedule of Live Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of journalists, entertainers, and
cameramen at the British Broadcasting Corp. stayed off the job for
the second day Wednesday, forcing curtailment or cancellation of
newscasts and other live programs.
   The corporation said 12,000 of its 25,000 workers stayed home on
the second day of the 48-hour walkout. BBC management said it hoped
conditions would return to normal Thursday.
   All radio and television news programs were cut short.
   A live talk show hosted by popular Terry Wogan was replaced with
a repeat of an interview with ``Dynasty'' star Joan Collins.
   Late-night live pop shows were replaced by pre-recorded material.
   It was the second time in three months the unions have struck
for better pay.
   They want raises of 16 percent to match salaries in commercial
broadcasting. The BBC, which is funded by public fees, has offered
7 percent.
   The unions say the national average pay for a BBC journalist is
$28,390 a year, compared with $40,080 in commercial broadcasting.
