<FIRST>r a AM-People-Monroe     05-10 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Monroe,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Drops Assault Charge Against Bluegrass Music Star Bill Monroe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ingrum is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A charge that bluegrass music star Bill
Monroe hit a woman in the face with a Bible was dismissed Wednesday
after prosecutors said she was a fan who'd harassed him for four
years.
   Wanda Huff, 51, obtained the misdemeanor assault and battery
warrant May 1, saying Monroe struck her with the book after she
asked him to swear on it that he wasn't seeing other women.
   After the incident at Monroe's farm in Goodlettsvile northwest
of Nashville, Mrs. Huff said she was the 77-year-old Grand Ole Opry
star's girlfriend, but prosecutors said she was just a fan.
   Mrs. Huff denied making harassing phone calls.
   ``I know this warrant has been an embarrassment to you,'' Sumner
County General Sessions Judge Jane Wheatcraft told Monroe.
   ``I'm so happy,'' the gray-haired Grammy Award winner said
outside the courtroom. ``It's been difficult with people bothering
me. I'm glad it's over.''
   When Mrs. Huff arrived Wednesday for the hearing, Sumner County
Sheriff Richard Sutton confiscated a loaded .25-caliber pistol from
her pickup truck.
   Monroe lawyer Bob Ingrum said he requested the search because
Mrs. Huff said several times she had received word someone waited
to kill Monroe.
   Prosecutors recommended the charge be dropped after talking to
several witnesses who said Mrs. Huff, often using aliases, called
Monroe's home and office up to 15 times a day.
   Before the May 1 incident that led to the charge, Mrs. Huff
called the farm to warn workers she was coming to see Monroe to
retrieve some gifts she gave him, Assistant District Attorney Dee
Gay said.
   Ingrum said Mrs. Huff wanted to take back some blue jeans, a tie
tack, a hatband and $27 for garden seeds she had given Monroe.
   ``She threw the britches in the yard, the hatband in the mule
yard and the $27 in Mr. Monroe's face,'' Ingrum said. ``We never
did find the tie tack, and she threw her glasses on top of the
roof.''
   Monroe called Goodlettsville police to throw Mrs. Huff off his
farm, Gay said. She asked them to arrest Monroe, but they refused
to file charges against him.
   Mrs. Huff went to a magistrate, who issued the assault warrant.
Monroe was arrested May 2, and released on $500 bond.
   Ingrum obtained a temporary restraining order Wednesday
instructing Mrs. Huff to stay away from Monroe. Mrs. Huff agreed to
comply, Gay said.
   Grand Ole Opry security officer James Lewis said the harassing
phone calls began in later 1984 or early 1985 when Mrs. Huff called
him at the Opry and said she had gotten a call from someone who
threatened Monroe's life.
   Lewis said he talked with Mrs. Huff five or six times since, and
each time she mentioned death threats.
   Monroe, best known for the song ``Blue Moon of Kentucky,'' said
he didn't like publicity about the incident, ``but my good friends
and fans know it was wrong.''
   A tearful Mrs. Huff denied making the harassing phone calls.
   ``You can pay people to tell all kind of lies,'' she said as she
left the parking lot.
   ``I've been deceived. I've been betrayed. I got beat up,'' she
said. ``I did not threaten to kill him. If I wanted to, I could
have when we were alone.''
</TEXT>
