<DOCNO> AP890510-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Mice-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0799 05-10 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mice-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0799,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys 500,000 Mice at Genetics Lab, Five People Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Four construction ..., to reflect that lab is
leading non-profit supplier; SUBS 6th graf, `The fire broke .. ., with
3 grafs to UPDATE with comments from fire chief; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th
graf pvs, `Each year, ..., to UPDATE with some of lab's customers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire killed about 500,000 laboratory
mice and injured five people Wednesday in a blaze at a genetic
research center that one lab official said would set back
scientific research worldwide.
   Four construction workers and a firefighter were injured in the
midday fire at Jackson Laboratory, the world's leading nonprofit
supplier of genetically identical mice used in research on cancer,
AIDS, diabetes and other human diseases.
   The lab's director-designee, Kenneth Paigen, said the fire would
not retard the Jackson Laboratory's research because mice used in
its own experiments already had been transferred to the research
building.
   ``What it will set back is the research efforts of scientists
all over the world'' who depend on the lab for specially bred mice,
he said.
   ``We managed to save what are called the foundation stocks ...
the original genetically defined strains,'' Paigen said. ``It will
take us time but we will be able to reproduce what was there.''
   The fire broke out about 1:15 p.m. in the one-story, brick-faced
Morrell Park building where the mice are bred and housed, in a room
that was undergoing renovation, fire officials said.
   Bar Harbor Fire Chief Royal Higgins said a sealant being used by
the construction workers apparently acted as an accelerant in the
fire, but ``what ignited it, I don't know.''
   He said several propane tanks had exploded, but he was not
suggesting that it caused the fire.
   Most of the mice were earmarked for shipment to researchers
throughout the world, said Barbara Trevett, the laboratory's
spokeswoman. She said the building was destroyed, along with the
mice housed in its 18 storage rooms.
   The facility stocks 1,700 different strains of mice, some of
which are produced only at the Jackson Lab.
   Each year, the laboratory ships about 3 million mice to
scientists around the world. Sales of the mice generate $10 million
a year, which is plowed back into research and other programs at
the laboratory, Trevett said.
   She said the lab's the major customers include the National
Institutes of Health, Harvard, MIT and other universities doing
research on mammalian genetics, and major hospitals with research
centers.
   Lab officials said about 230 employees worked in, or in
connection with, the animal production building. The campus-like
laboratory complex beside Acadia National Park employs more than
500 people.
   One injured construction worker was transferred in stable
condition to Maine Medical Center's burn unit in Portland, but the
extent of his injuries was unknown, officials said.
   Jeanne Dulong, director of nursing at Mount Desert Island
Hospital said three other workers were admitted with non-extensive
first-and second-degree burns and would probably be released in a
day or two.
   The firefighter, whose name Ms. Dulong could not release, was
being treated for minor smoke inhalation and would probably be
quickly released, she said.
   In 1947, a forest fire that swept across Mount Desert Island,
destroying the laboratory that was founded 18 years earlier with
financing from wealthy summer residents. Rebuilt after the fire,
the lab grew rapidly to become the world's largest center for the
study of mammalian genetics.
   Earl Green, a former director of the laboratory, said it would
take six to eight generations of mice, or about two or three years,
to replace the destroyed animals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StubbornSilos 1stLd-Writethru a0805 05-10 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stubborn Silos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0805,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Grain Elevator _ Stubborn or Cursed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `Fort Worth ...,' to CORRECT sex of murder victim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grain elevator besieged by a
demolition crew is making one of the most stubborn last stands
since the Alamo, but some say the problem isn't tough concrete.
It's a curse.
   People who've climbed secretly to the top of the 110-foot-high
silos and looked across a moonlit Fort Worth say the curse has
struck a number of times, including the fatal stabbing last year of
a Japanese tourist.
   ``They've found several dead dogs and cats by it,'' said Charles
Shields, 25, who works near the 1902 structure just west of
downtown.
   ``I don't believe in curses,'' said Jerry Vann, whose Chicago
demolition company has spent 39 days trying to knock the elevator
down with more than 500 dynamite blasts. ``All I know is it's
costing me money.''
   Vann took the job for a flat fee, expecting to finish the job in
eight or nine days. So far, he's $9,000 in the hole and expects to
stay at least through Saturday _ at a cost of $1,000 or so a day.
   ``I've got my reputation,'' he said. ``I've knocked down
buildings worldwide. But this is like nothing I've ever seen.''
   Twenty-two of the 17-foot-wide silos are gone, but 23 remain,
lined three deep in a honeycomb pattern. Alongside the remaining
silos is the 190-foot-tall main building.
   Among those working for Vann is Tony Cruson, 37, who grew up in
Fort Worth and heard rumors the elevator was haunted.
   ``Around Halloween, the big deal for boys was to bring girls out
here, and try to get in good with them by protecting them,'' he
said.
   James Ferrar, 33, who has climbed the tower secretly a number of
times, said he believes it's haunted and has heard chilling screams
several times.
   One of his friends, making a night climb by lantern light in the
late 1970s, fell and broke both arms, he said. Cruson and others
have heard the story.
   The unidentified man told others he was climbing a circular
staircase in the main building, reached the top, but then the
staircase seemed to extend itself. As he kept climbing, someone
from above reached out and pushed him, Ferrar said.
   ``For 30 years, I wanted to go up and see the top of this
silo,'' Cruson said. ``But when you get up there, the wind whistles
through it and you hear all kinds of noises. It's eerie, really
eerie.''
   Fort Worth police homicide Lt. Tommy Swan said the only
real-life horror he can associate with the elevator is the stabbing
of Japanese tourist Fumika Okada, who was lured to her death.
   ``I grew up in Fort Worth and I never heard about anything
satanic about that place,'' Swan said. ``But of course, I never
heard about marijuana until I was 21, either, and that doesn't mean
it wasn't there.''
   Developer James Toal, who hopes to build an office and
residential complex on the site, along with a major hotel, said
he'd never heard the elevator was haunted. ``There's people killed
all over the place,'' he pointed out.
   Toal says there are plenty of rumors flying as the silos make
their last stand. But one rumor workmen say they can't discuss in
detail is true. A local production crew is making a movie at the
site, the story of an entity trapped in the elevator as it is being
destroyed.
   The title? ``Incantations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
