<FIRST>r a AM-SecondAbduction     05-10 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Suspected in Baby's Death Bury Her Next to Their Slain Firstborn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple suspected of killing their
6-week-old daughter buried her Wednesday beside the unmarked grave
containing remains of what is believed to be their slain firstborn.
   Robert and Paula Sims were joined by more than a dozen family
members at a private, 30-minute service for Heather Lee Sims at the
First Baptist Church in Bethalto. The infant was buried nearby in
Woodland Hills Cemetery.
   The Simses reported both of their baby girls kidnapped in nearly
identical incidents three years apart. The parents are considered
suspects in both deaths, but their lawyer has said they are
innocent of wrongdoing in the cases.
   The Simses, who had not publicly displayed any emotion toward
each other since they reported Heather abducted April 29, held
hands as they walked into the church. Mrs. Sims, 29, appeared
tearful as she left the church.
   During the 10-minute graveside ceremony Sims, 37, placed his
right arm around Mrs. Sims. Onlookers were kept about 50 yards away.
   The funeral party included Mrs. Simses' parents, Orville and
Nylene Blew. Police have also subpoenaed the Blews to testify
before a grand jury in Heather's slaying.
   Heather was buried in a tiny white coffin. An employee of the
Gray Funeral Home in Wood River was the sole pallbearer.
   The Simses requested that Heather be buried at the side of their
firstborn daughter, Loralei, said Bill Helvie, cemetery manager.
   Loralei Sims was 13 days old when the Simses reported her
kidnapped June 17, 1986. Remains believed to be Loralei's were
found near the Simses' former home in nearby Brighton aout a week
after she vanished.
   The case was never solved, though the Simses were considered
suspects in Loralei's disappearance.
   In the latest case, the Simses told police that a masked gunman
attacked Mrs. Sims about 10:30 p.m. April 29 as she took out the
garbage, and that she presumed he had taken Heather.
   On May 3, a fisherman found the child's body in a trash barrel
in Missouri, across the Mississippi River from Alton.
   Heather was suffocated by someone who placed a hand over her
mouth, according to police, who said her body was placed in a
freezer before it was left in the trash barrel.
   An autopsy revealed cuts inside the baby's upper lip, Alton
police Sgt. RickMcCain testified Tuesday at a hearing where the
Simses' were denied custody of their surviving child, 15-month-old
Randy.
   The Alton Police Department reported no arrests in the case
Wednesday.
   The Simses have refused to comment on the case, but their
lawyer, Donald Groshong has said they are innocent.
   Mrs. Sims was expected to appear before a Madison County grand
jury investigating the case Thursday.
</TEXT>
