<FIRST>a a PM-AlaskaVillage Adv17 APPhotoPkg 05-10 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Village, Adv 17, AP Photo Pkg,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, May 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Life in Fishing Village Uncertain Since Exxon Valdez Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Story and photos by AP Photographer John Gaps III</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos scheduled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TATITLEK, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one sense, this small native fishing
village was spared. Although the tanker Exxon Valdez hemorrhaged
more than 10 million gallons of crude just 5 miles from their cove,
local folks have seen little of the oil in their waters.
   In another sense, they're not so fortunate. ``It's probably
still going to get us,'' says village president Gary Kompkoff.
   ``Right now most of us would be out collecting salmon spawn,''
he said. ``But that has been canceled. We're not sure if we're
going to be able to fish at all this year. Ninety-eight percent of
the annual income of the village is fishing.''
   Tatitlek, settled in the late 1800s on the northern shore of
Prince William Sound, has 95 residents. All but 10 are Aleut
Indians, and many are Russian Orthodox, typical of this part of
Alaska.
   Tatitlek fishermen have caught salmon in Prince William Sound
for decades, but since the Exxon Valdez ran aground on Bligh Reef
on March 24, the familiar cycle of village life has been disrupted.
   ``Right now we're just trying to understand what this will mean
for us long term,'' said Kompkoff.
   The lucrative herring season has already been canceled.
   In the nearby fishing town of Cordova, loss of the herring catch
will cost $12 million. But Cordova fisherman are making up some of
the loss with income from working booms for Exxon, gathering
remnants of the spill in their boats.
   Few of Tatitlek's fishermen have been offered such work.
   Says Kompkoff, ``We've gone from fear to anger to apprehension
over this thing. It's going to be with us for a long time to come.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, May 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
