<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-BusCrashAnniversary Adv14   05-10 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bus Crash Anniversary, Adv 14,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bus Crash Anniversary Marked by More Questions Than Answers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK R. CHELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whenever Lee Williams sees a school bus he
thinks of his wife and daughters, and of one gnawing question that
remains for him a year after their deaths shattered his life: ``How
do you put it back together?'
   Joy Williams, 10-year-old Robin and 14-year-old Kristen were
among the 24 children and three adults killed a year ago Sunday
when an allegedly drunken driver slammed into the bus carrying 67
people home from a church outing.
   ``Before you put something back together, you have to have
pieces. He has no pieces,'' said the Rev. W. Don Tennison, whose
Radcliff First Assembly of God church sponsored the trip to an
amusement park.
   The crash, the nation's worst alcohol-related highway accident,
also raised questions about school bus safety and treatment of
drunken drivers. The acting chairman of the National Transportation
Safety Board called it ``one of the most influential highway
accidents'' the board had ever considered.
   Recommendations have been made to get some older buses off the
road. The bus involved, a 1977 model, was manufactured before
federal regulations on some safety matters took effect, such as
protective cages around gas tanks.
   Emergency push-out windows have been added to school buses in
Kentucky after it was revealed that the emergency exit in the back
of the bus was partly blocked by seats and hard to use because of a
narrow aisle.
   Because the deaths were caused by smoke inhalation,
recommendations also have been made to use less flammable, less
toxic materials in bus seats.
   A state school bus safety task force apparently will recommend
testing all fuel for buses as the debate over fuel explosiveness
continues.
   Stricter drunken driving laws have been endorsed by Gov. Wallace
Wilkinson, though the General Assembly has shown reluctance to get
too tough.
   ``The law's not fair here. The law's not right,'' said Williams.
He notes that Kentucky law allows the vehicle of a deer poacher to
be seized. No such provision is allowed for drunken drivers.
``Where's the value?''
   Larry W. Mahoney of rural Owen County was driving the pickup,
police say, on the wrong side of Interstate 71. His blood alcohol
level two hours after the accident was 0.24; legal intoxication in
Kentucky is 0.10.
   Mahoney was indicted on 27 counts of murder, 13 of assault, 44
of wanton endangerment and one of driving under the influence,
second offense. He pleaded innocent and could be given 27 life
sentences plus 480 years if he is convicted on all counts at his
trial in November. Meanwhile, he is free on bond.
   For Williams, that raises another question: ``Can you promise me
tonight this guy won't drink and drive?''
   It's drunken driving that continues to prompt the most
discussion and activity in this town near Fort Knox. ``It's made
the judges not only in our area but in the whole county more aware
of the need to tighten up on the law and enforce it more
strictly,'' said Mayor Joseph Hutcherson.
   Students Against Drunken Driving chapters are active at Radcliff
Middle School and North Hardin High School. Linda Probus, a
counselor hired to help students cope with the tragedy, said
drinking and driving is no longer acceptable behavior among the
students.
   Residents take time to pull off the road to report suspected
drunken drivers, said Police Officer Greg Mayfield.
   On the anniversary of the crash, Radcliff is holding a memorial
expected to draw hundreds of people.
   Many of those touched by the crash have mixed emotions about the
ceremony.
   ``I think the community, not to forget the families, is ready to
put the accident to rest,'' said Dick Booher, whose son Jason
escaped from the bus.
   ``We want to be left alone. We want to try to put our lives back
together,'' said Williams, a career soldier who spends much of his
off-duty time speaking publicly about the dangers of drunken
driving.
   But another reminder of the tragedy will come Nov. 8 when
Mahoney goes on trial. His role is still a troubling one for many
involved.
   Ms. Probus said many of the students who survived the crash have
changed their attitudes toward Mahoney. ``Initially, they really,
really wanted Mahoney to die.'' As they have come to grips with the
tragedy, they ``want him punished, left in jail, but not to be
killed.''
   The memorial Sunday will mark a milepost in this tragedy but
will not end it. Legislators still will debate tougher laws. State
agencies will weigh the benefits of additional training for school
bus drivers against the cost. Drunken drivers still will kill
innocent victims.
   First Sgt. Lee Williams still will think of his family when he
sees a bus. And he will continue to warn people of the danger.
   ``I give these speeches for the Robins and the Kristens who
haven't been killed. I give these speeches for the husbands and the
wives who haven't been hurt.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
