<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Peru Adv00-2Takes   05-10 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Peru, Adv 00-2 Takes,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Peru _ A Threat of Civilbureau chief in Lima
surveys Peru, which has possibly reached the lowest point in its 165 years
as an independent nation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``These are the days of the anonymous
nocturnal bullet, of the slashing of throats of village officials,
of the disappearance of union leaders.''
   So wrote Cesar Hilderbrandt in a column recently in Si magazine
in a passage that epitomizes the desperation of today's Peru, a
nation struggline with economic chaos and a savage leftist
insurgency that threatens to explode into civil war.
   From cab drivers to congressmen, Peruvians are asking themselves
what went wrong in their Andean country, which had one of South
America's strongest economies until the 1960s.
   _More than 14,000 people have been killed in the nine-year
uprising by the the leftist Shining Path (Sendero Luminoso)
guerrilla organization. Blackouts and bombs have become part of
daily life in Lima. A paramilitary death squad has made its
appearance.
   _Inflation hit a record 1,722 percent in 1988 and is widely
projected to soar above 10,000 percent this year, pushing wages and
salaries down to bare-survival levels. The economy shrank 9 percent
in 1988 and is likely to contract even more this year.
   _The collapse is putting hundreds of thousands of people out of
work in the continent's third largest country and one of its
poorest. In 1976, Peru produced 34,000 automobiles; this year it is
expected to assemble, at the most, 3,500. Few people can afford
them.
   Although many Peruvians blame President Alan Garcia for the
chaos, most independent analysts say the economic crisis had been
building toward an eruption for the past several decades; Garcia's
populist, free-spending policies lit the fuse.
   Highway bandits have begun waylaying buses and automobiles,
making travel outside Lima dangerous and adding to the sense of a
disintegrating nation where law and order has broken down.
   Many Peruvians now speak of ``the civil war that is coming,''
seeing it as inevitable.
   ``There is a very real danger that Peru, without realizing it,
is sinking deeper into the swamps of fratricidal war,'' the
magazine Oiga commented in a recent editorial.
   Surveys indicate most people have little faith that solutions
will be found.
   Garcia, a dynamic young leader, was elected in 1985 as ``the
president of hope.'' But his defiant stance against paying the
foreign debt, now $19 billion, cut Peru off from international aid
and his uncontrolled spending bankrupted the country, critics say.
   These days angry crowds shout ``Alan, you charlatan'' when he
speeds by in heavily armed convoys.
   In recent months Lima has been hit by waves of coup rumors and
many Peruvians doubt the presidential election scheduled for April
1990 will take place. Leftist military officers seized power in
1968; constitutional government was restored in 1980.
   Former Mayor Alfonso Barrantes of Lima, a Marxist, is one of the
favorites in the campaign. The other front-runner is the writer
Mario Vargas Llosa, leader of a center-right coalition.
   Peruvians frequently mention the opening passage in Vargas
Llosa's 1974 novel ``Conversation in the Cathedral,'' saying it
succinctly reflects their feelings now:
   ``From the doorway of La Cronica, Santiago looks at the Avenida
Tacna without love: cars, uneven and faded buildings, the gaudy
skeletons of posters floating in the mist, the gray midday. At what
precise moment had Peru (screwed) itself up?''
   One who saw things that way was Morty Weisselberg, 41, a
second-generation Peruvian, who had a high-paying job as the
manager of a small metallurgical company. He packed up and left a
few months ago for Canada with his wife and two small daughters.
Before he left he explained why.
   ``What worries me is the kind of future I am going to leave my
children. `The future that this country offers is very different
from the one 30 years ago when I was in the position of my
children. Then there was a bright future for the country, at least
apparently.''
   The Weisselbergs were among 150,000 Peruvians, most of them
professionals and skilled workers, who bought one-way tickets out
the country in 1988, the largest exodus in Peru's history.
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
