<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled Pan Am Corp. said it may
offer to buy much-larger NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines and
the target of several other potential suitors.
   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett did not provide details Tuesday,
but said Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. was considering providing
significant new equity for Pan Am so that it could make an all-cash
offer for NWA.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. said it was not
prepared to submit a formal bid for strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, the owner and chairman of
TWA, has held numerous discussions with officials of Eastern's
unions and had been widely expected to make a bid for the
Miami-based airline.
   TWA said Tuesday it needed more time to discuss the idea with
its unions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viacom Inc. has sued Time Inc. in federal court
for $2.4 billion in antitrust damages, accusing its rival of
monopolizing pay television.
   Viacom Inc. is parent of Showtime-The Movie Channel and Time
owns Home Box Office as well as major cable operators.
   Time blasted Viacom's suit on Tuesday as baseless.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORNELIUS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon farmers have planted 18 percent
less land in strawberries this year because of fluctuations in the
migrant work force and complications of the new federal immigration
law.
   The harvest may cover even less acreage if more migrant pickers
don't arrive in the next few weeks for the June picking.
   Under a 1986 law, employers face fines of up to $10,000 for each
illegal worker they hire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a bid to generate excitement for CBS' fall
television programs and gain publicity for K mart Corp., the TV
network and the retailer plan a big national promotion tied to the
September premiere of CBS shows.
   The promotion will be built around a viewer involvement game.
   K mart and CBS will alert viewers in print and via electronic
media how to play and which shows to watch.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. electronics industry has released a
plan proposing more than $1.3 billion in government aid to help
America catch up in the global race to develop high-definition
television technology.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, however, said Tuesday U.S.
manufacturers shouldn't depend on Uncle Sam to be their ``Uncle
Sugar'' in bankrolling the effort.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government study suggests that the Sematech
research consortium is no guarantee the United States will capture
the commercial edge in production of semiconductor chips.
   The Commerce Department study said Tuesday a host of trade, tax
and antitrust issues will continue to affect the competitiveness of
U.S. chipmakers, regardless of the success of the Austin, Texas,
consortium.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 100 biggest black-owned industrial
and service companies grew 14.4 percent in revenue last year,
topping the 7.6 percent growth of the Fortune 500, according to
Black Enterprise magazine.
   The companies achieved the revenue growth despite streamlining
efforts that trimmed their employment rolls by 21.7 percent, the
magazine reported in releasing the list Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government said it would grant South
African-controlled Minorco SA a limited extension in its hostile
$5.8 billion bid for Britain's Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   The Panel on Takeovers and Mergers on Tuesday also ordered Gold
Fields to discontinue its court proceedings against Minorco unless
its shareholders approve such actions at a May 30 meeting.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell in sluggish trading Tuesday.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 5.14 points to
2,371.33, its eighth consecutive decline.
   The dollar retreated slightly.
   Bond prices dropped sharply. The yield on the Treasury's
benchmark 30-year bond, which rises when the price falls, climbed
to 9.09 percent from 8.99 percent.
   Coffee futures prices climbed and petroleum futures rebounded.
</TEXT>
