<FIRST>r f PM-BlackCompanies Bjt   05-10 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Companies, Bjt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biggest Black-Owned Company Grossed Nearly $2 Billion Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest black-owned company
garnered nearly $2 billion in revenue last year and the 100 biggest
experienced healthy growth, according to a survey by Black
Enterprise magazine.
   The top 100 black-owned industrial and service companies
achieved revenue growth of 14.4 percent, vs. 7.6 percent for the
Fortune 500, in spite of cutting their staffs by 21.7 percent, the
magazine said in a report released today.
   Black-owned auto dealerships, which are in a separate top-100
list, saw sales rise 14.4 percent last year, the magazine said.
   ``As the next decade fast approaches, the nation's largest black
businesses are readying themselves,'' Black Enterprise stated in
its June issue.
   Reginald Lewis's TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc.
continued to dominate the list. Its $1.96 billion in revenue
accounted for close to half the $4.46 billion grossed by the 100
companies combined.
   Lewis acquired the international companies of Beatrice Cos., the
giant food processor and distributor, in a $985 million buyout in
1987 and has paid off debt incurred in the purchase by selling
divisions. He personally owns 55 percent of the stock, a Black
Enterprise spokesman said.
   Divestitures last year by New York-based TLC Beatrice cut the
payroll nearly in half, to 11,000 from 20,365, accounting for
nearly the entire staff decline in the 100 companies. However, TLC
Beatrice revenue rose 8.9 percent.
   Johnson Publishing Co. Inc. of Chicago, the publisher,
broadcaster and maker of cosmetics and hair-care products, retained
second place on the list with $216.5 million in revenue.
   J. Bruce Llewellyn's Philadelphia Coca-Cola Bottling Co. Inc.,
the soft-drink bottler, kept third place with $210 million.
   H.J. Russell &amp; Co. of Atlanta, a company involved in
construction, property management and food and beverages, stayed in
fourth place with revenue of $160 million.
   In fifth was Gordy Co. of Los Angeles, formerly Motown
Industries Inc., which changed its name when it sold its flagship
Motown Records to MCA Inc. and the investment banker Boston
Ventures last year for an estimated $61 million. Gains in other
businesses contributed to a rise in revenue to $105 million from
$100 million the year before.
   Construction companies accounted for 19 of the top 100
companies, followed by 16 food and beverage companies, 13 computer
and information companies and 12 manufacturing companies.
   Among the nation's 100 biggest black-owned auto dealerships,
sales rose to $2.33 billion.
   ``The long-predicted bust'' for black-owned auto dealers ``does
not appear to be on the horizon _ at least not anytime soon,'' the
magazine stated.
   Ford Motor Co. franchises accounted for 46 of the dealerships,
while General Motors Corp. accounted for 26 and Chrysler Corp. 15.
   The nation's biggest black-owned car dealership was Shack-Woods
&amp; Associates of Long Beach, Calif., whose sales jumped 42.7 percent
last year to $127 million.
   California led all states with 22 of the companies belonging to
one or the other of the two top-100 lists. New York and Michigan
had 20 apiece, followed by Illinois and Ohio with 13 apiece.
   To make the list, companies had to be at least 51 percent
black-owned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
