<FIRST>r f PM-PanAm-Northwest Bjt   05-10 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am-Northwest, Bjt,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smaller Pan Am Would Gobble Northwest Under Possible Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pan Am-Northwest-Profile, PM-Pan Am-Glance, PM-Northwest-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heavy debt load, antitrust laws and
possible labor conflict could be sticking points for
financially-troubled Pan Am Corp. if it decides to bid for the
much-larger NWA Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines and the
target of several other suitors.
   Pan Am, backed by Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. and an
investment group including members of Texas' Bass family, said
Tuesday it would consider making a buyout offer for NWA.
   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett told a Washington news
conference that Prudential-Bache and the Airlie Group Ltd. were
considering providing significant new equity for Pan Am to make an
acquisition possible. He did not provide any details.
   NWA said that Pan Am, the parent of Pan American World Airways,
stated in a letter that if it made a formal proposal, it likely
would be an all-cash offer.
   Pan Am's announcement was in response to NWA's general request
for buyout proposals, Plaskett said. NWA made the request afte
rejecting oil billionaire Marvin Davis' unsolicited $90-a-share, or
$2.7 billion, buyout offer.
   Another potential buyer for NWA is an investment group headed by
Los Angeles investor Al Checchi.
   Pan Am's limited contact with Northwest has been ``cordial and
friendly,'' Plaskett said.
   Plaskett said in February that Pan Am, with nearly $1 billion in
debts, would need to find a merger partner or otherwise attract new
investment in order to survive. The New York-based company lost
$151.1 million in the first three months of 1989, $72.7 million in
all of 1988 and $265.3 million in 1987.
   By contrast, NWA, based in Eagan, Minn. reported first-quarter
earnings of $12.6 million, or 43 cents a share, and is one of the
country's most profitable airlines.
   A marriage of Pan Am and Northwest would create one of the
world's farthest-ranging airlines, joining Pan Am's strong Atlantic
and Latin American routes with Northwest's Pacific routes to the
Orient.
   But some analysts doubted that Pan Am, the eighth-largest U.S.
carrier, could successfully bid for No. 4 Northwest. Reaction on
Wall Street was cool with Pan Am stock rising 62{ cents a share to
$5 on the New York Stock Exchange and NWA falling 50 cents to
$104.25 a share.
   Kurt Rivard, an airline analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. in
Minneapolis, said a merger of the two was plausible, but it could
be the kind of highly leveraged deal that Northwest's pilots and
machinists have said they would resist.
   The machinists have said they are interested in making their own
bid for Northwest. The pilots have an open contract and pose a
strike threat.
   ``The company (Pan Am) has a working capital deficiency,'' said
Mike Hamilton of Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood Inc. in Minneapolis.
``That's not the kind of situation that labor nor NWA managment is
eager to move into.''
   There also could be labor turbulence at Pan Am.
   William Genoese, head of the Teamsters local representing 5,300
Pan Am cargo, passenger service workers and stock clerks, said his
union could disrupt a possible bid by threatening to strike and
scaring away Pan Am's financial backers. The union is trying to
negotiate a new contract.
   ``We're the only ones who can strike Pan Am right now,'' Genoese
said. ``Wall Street won't give them money with an open contract.''
   Said Plaskett: ``We would expect employees of both companies to
be a very important part in our evaluation of whether or not to
proceed.''
   Charles Rule, a Washington, D.C., lawyer who formerly was in
charge of the antitrust division at the U.S. Justice Department,
said there is a chance the department would reject a Northwest-Pan
Am merger proposal on the grounds that it would weaken domestic
competition in the industry.
   But he said chances for approval would be increased if the two
carriers can prove their routes do not overlap.
   ``I wouldn't want to speculate as to what the conclusion is
going to be,'' Rule said.
   NWA said Pan Am had shown previous buyout interest but had not
signed a confidentiality agreement that NWA has required of all
suitors seeking non-public financial information. NWA Chairman
Steven Rothmeier said Northwest's board would consider Pan Am's
request for information.
   Pan Am will make an offer or back out by the June 2 deadline NWA
has set for offers, Plaskett said.
   Hamilton, the Piper Jaffray analyst, said a bid by Pan Am could
possibly be intended to lure NWA into a takeover of Pan Am.
   ``If I had to speculate in either direction it would be that Pan
Am is trying to get themselves into play,'' Hamilton said. ``Pan Am
has been looking for a merger partner for a while.''
   But Plaskett said he has no hidden agenda.
   ``What we think we bring to this transaction is something that a
pure financial investor cannot bring, the opportunity for revenue
and growth, for financial and cost synergies,'' Plaskett said.
``The combined carriers serve a total of 290 cities worldwide with
virtually no overlap, only eight duplicated routes between the two
carriers and no duplicated international route authority.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
