<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Viacom-TimeSuit Bjt   05-10 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Viacom-Time Suit, Bjt,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Viacom Sues Time, Says HBO, Other Time Cable TV Units Break Antitrust
Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viacom Inc., charging that Time Inc. and its
cable television units are monopolizing pay-TV, has filed a $2.4
billion antitrust lawsuit seeking to loosen Time's grip on the
cable industry.
   Viacom, parent of the Showtime cable television channel, filed
its suit against Time and its Home Box Office and other cable TV
divisions in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
   Viacom charged Time and its TV holdings are monopolizing,
conspiring to monopolize and attempting to restrain trade,
practices prohibited by the federal Sherman and Clayton antitrust
acts.
   The suit contended the violations entitle Viacom to recover
three times the actual monetary damage done to it, an amount placed
at $800 million. After trebling, the amount sought in damages is
$2.4 billion.
   Time blasted Viacom's suit as baseless.
   ``Many of the allegations rehash issues that have been
periodically raised for more than a decade,'' stated Time, one of
the world's largest entertainment and publishing conglomerates.
``On several occasions, the Justice Department has reviewed many if
not all of these allegations and repeatedly concluded that no
action was warranted.''
   Viacom alleged that Time and its Home Box Office Inc., American
Television and Communications Corp. and Manhattan Cable Television
Inc. are ``engaging in an integrated series of predatory and
exclusionary acts and strategies designed to increase the costs of
their rivals, raise barriers to entry and expansion, and otherwise
entrench themselves as monopolists by anticompetitive conduct,
injuring the competitive process and ultimately, consumers,'' the
suit said.
   Among the numerous complaints listed, Viacom said HBO abuses its
position as the dominant firm in the business of providing pay TV
programming services.
   HBO holds about 65 percent of the nationwide market for these
services, a market share three times larger than its closest rival,
the suit said.
   These programming services are competing for access to national
and local markets. HBO's dominance allows it to undercut
competitions' prices to such an extent that competitors never
obtain a large enough subscriber base to survive, Viacom alleged.
   Viacom also asked the court to bar Time and its pay TV operators
from further allegedly anticompetitive behavior.
   Time vice president for corporate communications Louis J.
Slovinsky said Viacom's Showtime unit actually engages in some of
the practices that it has criticized HBO about in the suit. For
instance, both HBO and Showtime have negotiated exclusive contracts
with studios for films, according to Slovinsky.
   Also, he said Time is puzzled why Viacom has decided to launch
the legal salvo at this point.
   ``This is the kind of suit they could have brought any time in
the past 10 years. Why are they doing it now?'' Slovinsky said.
   He noted that the issues specified in the suit have been
examined thoroughly. Most recently, they were addressed when the
government reviewed the antitrust implications of the proposed $18
billion merger between Time and Warner Communications Inc., he said.
   A completed merger would make Time Warner the world's largest
media concern, with projected annual revenue of $10 billion, and in
all likelihood increase the combined company's clout in every field
in which it operates.
   Viacom said that more than a year was spent preparing the legal
action against Time, indicating it was not prompted by the
Time-Warner merger announcement in March.
   Slovinsky said Time will contest the many charges Viacom has
leveled and he predicted vindication.
   ``This is a suit that includes the kitchen sink and the coffee
grounds,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Texaco     05-10 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texaco,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Shareholders Endorse Anti-Takeover Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Texaco Inc. have approved a new
``poison pill'' to protect the oil company from unwanted takeover
attempts.
   The poison pill, also known as a shareholder rights plan, was
one of several company-backed measures approved Tuesday at the
Texaco annual meeting. Three proposals opposed by the Texaco board
_ two urging the company to curtail its operations in South Africa
and one to make proxy votes confidential _ were rejected.
   A shareholder vote on a poison pill is rare. But Texaco agreed
to the vote after shareholders handed the company a victory in a
proxy fight a year ago with takeover strategist Carl Icahn.
   The pill had been a point of contention between Texaco and
Icahn, its largest stockholder, until they settled their
differences aside in late January.
   The anti-takeover plan entitles stockholders to buy additional
shares of common stock at a considerable discount within 10 days of
the announcement that a suitor had acquired 20 percent or more of
Texaco common stock without meeting certain conditions.
   The plan's intent is to dilute the value of the suitor's
interest and increase the cost of making the offer.
   The Texaco plan, however, would not be triggered if an offer for
the company was considered by the board of directors to be ``a bona
fide, fully financed, all-cash offer and meets other conditions.''
The takeover offer also would have to give the board reasonable
time to explore other opportunities.
   The plan was approved Tuesday by 84.2 percent of the shares
voting, said Texaco spokeswoman Anita Larsen. Texaco has 250
million shares of common stock outstanding.
   Other proposals approved by shareholders included two special
dividends worth about $2 billion, an employee compensation plan
tied to performance, the hiring of a new auditor and the election
of five directors.
   The meeting Tuesday marked the first time officials of the White
Plains, N.Y.-based company faced the shareholders since Texaco
launched its post-bankruptcy restructuring.
   Texaco, the nation's third-largest oil company, asked a federal
bankruptcy court in 1987 to protect it from claims by its
creditors. The move followed a $10.3 billion judgment won against
Texaco by Pennzoil Co., which charged Texaco with blocking
Pennzoil's plans to acquire Getty Oil Co.
   Texaco emerged from bankruptcy protection last year and launched
a restructuring program that included the projected sale of more
than $5 billion in operating assets. In February, the company
completed the sale of Texaco Canada Inc. to Imperial Oil Ltd. for
$3.24 billion.
   ``After several years of some very special challenges, a new
Texaco has emerged _ a company with its own vision for greatness, a
company with its sights set firmly on the future,'' Texaco Chairman
Alfred C. DeCrane told the shareholders Tuesday.
   DeCrane and James W. Kinnear, Texaco's president and chief
executive officer, served up large helpings of optimism for the
attentive, if low-key, gathering.
   The officials said the company is in good financial health and
is poised to reclaim its position as an industry leader. Noting the
recent Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska, Kinnear also stressed that
Texaco is committed to preventing another environmental disaster.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-High-TechForecast Bjt   05-10 0976</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Tech Forecast, Bjt,1005</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan, Taiwan and Korea Put Squeeze on U.S. Electronics Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's biggest industry _ electronics
_ still leads Japan and the rest of the world, but not by much.
   Japan produced $250 billion worth of electronic goods in 1988 _
everything from computer chips to copiers and facsimile machines _
while the United States barely stayed ahead with $262.8 billion,
the research firm Dataquest Inc. said Tuesday in an annual industry
analysis and forecast.
   As the high-tech industry heads into the 1990s, it is
experiencing a shifting balance of power, said Manny A. Fernandez,
president of the San Jose-based firm.
   The rapid growth of Japan and the rest of Asia not only enlarged
the world's market for electronics products, but reduced American
and European shares of that market, Fernandez said.
   The move toward a unified European market in 1992 will put
further pressure on American manufacturers, Fernandez said,
although he noted that `` `Fortress Europe' is a fear, not _ at
least yet _ a fact.''
   ``All manufacturers worldwide must take the longer term view and
make the commitment necessary to be true global players, both
operationally and technologically, in Europe,'' he said.
   The globalization of the electronics marketplace is here to
stay, Fernandez said, and companies no longer can afford to
manufacture in just one country and sell everywhere else.
   ``This year we have seen some incredible things take place,''
said Fernandez, who called Japan's surge toward the top in overall
electronics production more signficant than its recent dominance of
the semiconductor industry.
   Apple Computer Inc. passed International Business Machines Corp.
in unit sales of personal computers in the United States in 1988,
Fernandez said. But the big news in that arena, he said, was the
penetration into the U.S. market of Korean and Taiwanese computer
makers.
   On a day when Apple announced new software and IBM unveiled a
cheaper personal computer and a portable one, Dataquest said both
companies lost U.S. market share in 1988 to foreign vendors, whose
sales grew from 35 percent to 45 percent of the U.S. total.
   The personal computer market, which grew 27 percent worldwide to
$51.7 billion and 22 percent in the United States to $28.7 billion,
will continue to grow impressively in 1989, Dataquest said. Growth
in the U.S. market will be 25 percent in 1989, and 12.6 percent
compounded annually through 1993, the company said.
   Laptop computers will be the fastest growing part of that
market, said Fernandez.
   American companies will have to change their marketing
strategies, however, to recover lost market share, said Fernandez.
   ``The era when it was the technology strength of one giant
company against another, those days are pretty much over,''
Fernandez said. ``It has become a marketing game. It has become a
game of pricing, a game of software supply, service and
distribution channels.''
   Apple led U.S. personal computer makers by selling 1.27 million
units of its Macintosh and Apple II lines in 1988, while IBM sold
1.23 million units of all its personal computers, said Dataquest
vice president Steve J. Lair.
   That trend will reverse in 1989, however, according to Lair, who
predicts IBM personal computer sales of 1.48 million units and
Apple sales of 1.42 million units.
   ``IBM is finally getting its act together,'' said Lair, who
cited the company's new products and stronger marketing push.
   IBM pulled the plug on its PC-AT line prematurely and made a
mistake in focusing on technology instead of marketing over the
past year or two, Lair said.
   ``IBM was expecting U.S. industry to respond to technological
advancement, whereas corporate decision makers were really
interested in productivity,'' Lair said.
   Japanese personal computer makers sold 730,000 units in the
United States, while Taiwan, Korea and other Asian companies sold
1.03 million units. European companies accounted for another
133,000 in U.S. sales.
   The hottest electronics markets over the next five years will be
telecommunications, which Japan already dominates, as well as
software, business computer peripherals and workstations, said
Dataquest.
   The estimated U.S. revenue in the telecommunications market in
1988 was $152.6 billion, and is expected to rise to $159.5 billion
in 1989 and $191.3 billion by the end of 1993, Dataquest said.
   Among the big winners in that market will be cellular radios,
facsimile machines and data communications equipment, Fernandez
said.
   ``Fax had a hot year in 1988 and that marketplace grew an
incredible 78 percent to $1.8 billion,'' he said. ``No industry is
going to be capable, at the $2 billion level, of maintaining that
kind of growth. But fax business is going to grow in 1989 another
14.6 percent to $2 billion, and then 12 percent every year after
that through 1993 to a new high of $3.2 billion.''
   By the end of this year, more than 105 million personal
computers will be in use around the world, creating a huge market
for add-ons, software and other related items, said Fernandez.
   Personal computer software sales totaled $9.3 billion in North
America in 1988, and are expected to rise to $10.7 billion in 1989
and $19.3 billion by the end of 1993.
   In what Dataquest called ``one of the great boom years for the
worldwide chip business,'' the overall semiconductor industry grew
32 percent in 1988. The industry posted $16 billion in sales in
North America in 1988, and is expected to grow to $18.3 billion
this year and $33.3 billion by the end of 1993.
   Worldwide chip consumption will grow 15.3 percent in 1989,
Dataquest said. Workstations also will be a high-growth area,
taking a bite out of the minicomputer market and putting pressure
on personal computers, said Fernandez. The proposed merger of
Hewlett-Packard Co. and Apollo Computer Inc. announced recently is
just the beginning of a continuing restructuring of the workstation
segment of the industry, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
