<FIRST>r f PM-GooberGlee     05-10 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Goober Glee,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Peanut Consumption Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. peanut consumption has jumped 10.8
percent since last year _ proof that good old goobers are becoming
a posh and fashionable food, Georgia's top peanut official says.
   A U.S. Department of Agriculture report said Americans are
eating 18 percent more peanut butter, 7.2 percent more salted nuts
and 1.2 percent more candy bars.
   ``We hope there aren't lots of folks out there who aren't eating
peanuts,'' said Don Koehler, executive director of the Georgia
Peanut Commission. ``But for those who aren't eating enough: we've
got a product that's gained a lot of acceptance.''
   Koehler said the USDA figures demonstrate the effectiveness of
the industry's promotional programs. The report, released on April
27, compares the first eight months of the peanut marketing year to
the same period a year earlier.
   ``At that kind of growth rate, we could be looking at $85
million in added sales for producers nationwide,'' Koehler said.
   To keep pace with increases in consumption and to maintain
stable prices and supplies, the USDA increased the national peanut
quota to 1.44 million tons this year from 1.4 million tons last
year.
   Koehler is particularly pleased about the 1.2 percent increase
in candy consumption.
   ``Candy has been kind of flat,'' he said in a recent interview.
``It seems we live in a health-conscious society that worries about
that (eating sweets). Folks are beginning to say, `Wait a minute,
everybody is overkilling ... food safety, food quality and what's
good to eat.' Once in a while, you just like a candy bar.''
   Another reason for the increase in consumption is cost, he said,
noting that peanut prices traditionally lag behind the consumer
price index for food.
   ``You can't buy bologna or hot dogs or any other protein source
nearly as cheap as you can peanuts,'' he said.
   The Peanut Commission spends more than $1 million annually to
promote the state's top cash crop and cooperates with similar
groups in Florida and Alabama in funding the Peanut Advisory Board.
   One of the industry's most successful promotional programs has
been the Adults-only Peanut Butter Club, sponsored by the board.
   ``I think ... we have made it acceptable again for adults to eat
peanut butter,'' he said. ``It's not just kids' food any more.
We're around 40,000 members and they just keep coming in.''
   This year, the commission is focusing on tourists who drive
through the state. The newest official Georgia maps at highway
welcome centers have a picture of a peanut on one side and peanut
information on the back.
   Georgia growers, who produce nearly half of the nation's
peanuts, devoted 688,000 acres to the crop last year.
   To provide more money for promotion, the advisory board's
headquarters was moved from New York to Atlanta, where operating
costs should be about 20 percent less, said Koehler.
   ``We brought it to the peanut belt,'' he said. ``We felt it was
a move we needed to make. We found we could do an equally effective
job in Atlanta and probably an ever more effective job.''
   Nearly all the peanuts grown in Georgia are a type known as
``runners.'' Runners account for 80.1 percent of all the peanuts in
candy, 64.4 percent of all salted nuts and 75.7 percent of all
peanut butter cookies and crackers. In addition, runners comprise
86.5 percent of all peanuts used in peanut butter.
   ``I think people have accepted peanuts as being a good food, and
though they're reasonably priced, we like to think of them as a
posh, in-vogue food,'' he said. ``We just want people to get out
there and eat peanuts and know we're going to keep growing them
down here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
