<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SearsMove     05-10 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears Move,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>State, City Officials Make Bid To Keep Retailer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governor James R. Thompson and Mayor Richard M.
Daley made what they called a competitive bid to Sears, Roebuck and
Co. executives in an effort to keep more than 6,000 jobs in Chicago.
   The two officials met Tuesday evening in a closed-door session
at Sears Tower with Sears Chairman Edward A. Brennan and other
company executives to discuss the planned relocation of the
retailer's Merchandise Group.
   ``We are going to be competitive with other cities across the
country,'' Daley said in a press conference with Thompson after
they left the world's tallest building. ``They're very aggressive,
other cities and states.
   ``I think some of the states would give their whole state to
Sears just to land (it) there,'' Daley said.
   In a major reorganization plan announced last autumn, Sears said
it would sell the 110-story Sears Tower and find less costly
facilities for the Merchandise Group, which operates Sears' retail
store and catalog division.
   State and city officials since then have pledged to use whatever
economic incentives are necessary not to lose the retailer, whose
$50 billion revenue last year nearly tripled the state's.
   Daley said it would be ``devastating'' for Chicago if Sears
moved out of the city.
   Thompson said Sears still is considering ``a number'' of sites,
both inside and outside the state.
   He said Illinois was preparing a ``very aggressive ... package''
to keep the company in the state and that it would be ``equally
applicable'' whether Sears decided to stay in Chicago or move to
another Illinois town.
   ``I wanted to assure the chairman...that if the city of
Chicago's package was one they chose, the state would be a very
aggressive partner with the city,'' Thompson said.
   Thompson and Daley declined to give any details of the package,
which is expected to include tax breaks, land writedowns,
transportation improvements and other incentives.
   Daley said ``there was a number of sites offered.'' Reports have
circulated in the last week that Sears was eyeing a site near
Chicago's O'Hare International Airport as well as several suburban
locations.
   ``I think we're highly competitive and we have a good proposal
by the state and by the city to keep them here,'' Daley said.
   Brennan confirmed the meeting took place, but declined to
comment further on what deadlines Sears has for the headquarters
search. Brennan and other Sears officials are expected to meet the
media Thursday when the retailer holds its annual shareholders
meeting.
   Sears officials still maintain that Chicago is the best choice
for a relocation site for the Merchandise Group's 6,700 employees,
although they are also looking outside the area.
   Thompson called Dallas and Charlotte, N.C. ``big tough
competitors'' for the Sears site.
   Brennan didn't attend the news conference and the governor and
mayor declined to say whether the company has given them a deadline
by which any proposals must be completed.
   Sears is the state's largest employer, with a total of almost
30,000 employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
