<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Semiconductors     05-10 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Semiconductors,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prediction: Japan's Procurement Of Foreign Chips To Reach 18 Percent
In 1991</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's procurement of foreign-made semiconductors
will fall 2 percent short of the U.S. target of 20 percent of the
Japanese market by 1991, a major Japanese economic newspaper said
Wednesday.
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun made the prediction based on annual
chip consumption by 40 major Japanese users in value terms in 1988.
They also looked at the companies' own estimates of their chip
purchases in 1991.
   The 40 companies surveyed, including electronics, auto-parts,
precision instrument and other manufacturing firms, account for
about 60 percent of the nation's total consumption annually, the
newspaper said. It said with the survey it could judge the
country's overall market-share trends.
   U.S. officials maintain that under a 1986 U.S.-Japan
semiconductor trade pact, Japan promised to increase its foreign
chip market to about 20 percent in 1991. Japanese officials say
there was no such promise.
   The share of foreign semiconductor sales in Japan stood at 10.6
percent in the fourth quarter of 1988, according to figures by the
World Semiconductor Trade Statistics.
</TEXT>
