<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Retail     05-10 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woolworth's Income Growth Crimped By High Interest Rates, Other Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. Woolworth Co. said Wednesday its
first-quarter earnings edged up 2.9 percent, restrained by the
impact of rising interest rates, higher short-term borrowings and
the cost of opening new stores.
   The New York-based retailer reported earnings of $36 million, or
56 cents a share, in the three months ended April 29, up from $35
million, or 54 cents a share, in the corresponding 1988 quarter.
   ``As anticipated, higher interest rates and higher average
levels of short-term borrowings put pressure on our first quarter
net income,'' said Harold E. Sells, Woolworth chairman and chief
executive officer.
   ``Higher depreciation expense due principally to the record
number of specialty stores opened in 1988 also impacted first
quarter results,'' he stated in a prepared announcement.
   He said interest and depreciation expenses as a percentage of
net income are expected to decline during the rest of the year.
   Woolworth's revenue grew 9 percent to $1.88 billion in the first
quarter from $1.72 billion a year earlier.
   Besides the Woolworth general merchandise stores, Woolworth has
many specialty retail holdings, including Foot Locker, Lady Foot
Locker and Kinney shoe stores.
</TEXT>
