<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FSX 2ndLd-Writethru   05-10 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FSX, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say U.S. Will Get Short End of Plane Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs new; pickup at pvs 4th graf, ``Beyond the''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional critics of the FSX warplane deal
told a Senate panel today that the United States would get the
worst of the bargain in sharing with Japan technology used for
America's F-16 fighter.
   ``The evidence before us is that we're really not getting
anything in return,'' Sen. Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill., said in testimony
before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   Advocates of the FSX agreement, which involves co-producing an
advance version of the F-16, have said the United States would gain
access to Japanese composite wing construction and phased array
radar technologies.
   But Dixon said a study by the General Accounting Office, an
investigative arm of Congress, has found that U.S. companies
already have such technologies.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., called the arguments on the
technology flowback from Japan ``total nonsense and a facade to
cover up the shortcomings of this deal.''
   The FSX deal was strongly defended at the hearing by a panel of
senior Bush administration officials, including Commerce Secretary
Robert Mosbacher.
   ``I am confident that this agreement will not harm the economic
security interests of the United States,'' Mosbacher said.
   The comments came on the second day of congresssional hearings
on the FSX deal.
   ``We will teach the premier Japanese aerospace firm how to build
a world-class fighter, something they cannot do today,'' Rep. Mel
Levine, D-Calif., said at one session Tuesday. ``It is a fact that
enhancing the capabilities of one's competitors will, by
definition, decrease one's technological lead.''
   ``Beyond the issue, there is so much wrapped up symbolically,''
said Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind. ``It is clear to me what the people of
Indiana want ... They have a deep, deep mistrust of the Japanese.''
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee and three House Foreign
Affairs subcommittees scheduled additional hearings today.
   President Bush last month approved a $7 billion agreement under
which the United States and Japan would co-produce an advanced
version of the F-16 fighter.
   The agreement calls for the United States to transfer designs
for the F-16, developed by General Dynamics, to Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries, Japan's prime contractor.
   The United States had urged Japan to buy the F-16s, but the
Asian nation said it wanted to build a new fighter on its own. The
Defense and State departments then pushed for a co-production deal.
   Lawmakers in the House and Senate have introduced resolutions to
disapprove the deal. Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., introduced a
resolution of approval Tuesday.
   ``The haunting question is, why won't they buy our planes?''
said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., at a hearing of Senate Armed
Services subcommittee on defense industry and technology. ``We buy
their cars, TVs, radios, VCRs.''
   Senators expressed concerns about how much technology the United
States will provide and how it will benefit Japan in the aerospace
industry. Witnesses from the State, Defense and Commerce
departments sought to assure the lawmakers that the United States
will not be giving away all its secrets and will retain safeguards.
   ``What we're providing to Japan was built in 1975, 1978. It's
not current state of the art,'' said Lt. Gen. Ronald W. Yates,
principal deputy to the assistant secretary of the Air Force for
acquisition.
   Yates said the only updated equipment are engines and avionics.
The United States will sell the engines but not allow Japan to copy
the technology. Japan will develop its own avionics, Yates said.
   Carl W. Ford, deputy assistant secretary of state for East Asian
and Pacific Affairs, noted that the FSX deal was made in the
interest of U.S. national security.
   ``Any suggestion that we are not in command about U.S.
production base couldn't be further from the truth,'' Ford said.
``... The FSX is our idea.''
   But Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., complained that any
``farsighted strategy to maintain our lead in aerospace'' is absent
in the FSX deal. Gore noted that at the same time the United States
is working with Japan on an advanced fighter jet, funding for the
National Aerospace Plane may be cut. The high-speed transport, a
joint project with NASA, could fly around the world in just two
hours.
   But Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has proposed slashing the
project's fiscal 1990 budget from $300 million to $100 million.
   Gore also cautioned that rejection of the Japan deal would leave
the United States with ``serious ongoing disputes with two major
allies'' _ West Germany, which does not want to modernize
short-range missiles, and Japan.
   In the House, Levine; Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.; and Helen Delich
Bentley, R-Md., urged support for the disapproval resolution at a
hearing before the Senate Foreign Affairs subcommittees on Asian
and Pacific affairs, arms control international security and
science, and international economic policy and trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
