<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-10 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Narrowly Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures were down slightly amid disappointment that the
Agriculture Department has become more conservative in subsidizing
wheat export sales.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter told the House Agriculture
Committee today in Washington that the government must be cautious
in awarding subsidies for sales of wheat from existing stockpiles,
although Yeutter said the USDA would use the export bonus program
aggressively for sales of new-crop wheat.
   Corn and soybean futures opened higher in line with strong cash
markets, but soybeans quickly turned lower on perceptions of
improved growing conditions in the Midwest.
   Although recent rains have dampened fears of a second
consecutive year of drought in the Corn Belt, some parts of
southern Iowa remain so dry that the National Guard is carrying
drinking water to parched communties.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.25{ a bushel; corn was }
cent lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $2.79 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent higher with May at $1.89 a bushel; soybeans
were 2 cents lower to 1\ cents higher with May at $7.65{ a bushel.
   Pork futures were higher while cattle futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .05 cent higher with June at
72.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .40 cent lower
with May at 76.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent lower to
.23 cent higher with June at 48.15 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.18 cents to 1.70 cents higher with May at 35.50
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Tuesday with pork
bellies up sharply on strong technical signals.
</TEXT>
