<FIRST>u f PM-Pittston     05-10 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pittston,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Miners, Management Confront Each Other at Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking coal miners and Pittston Co.
management squared off today at the company's annual meeting,
debating three labor proposals questioning the company's operation.
   Representatives of both sides traded charges but no vote had
been taken on the proposals by noon and debate dragged on.
   As the annual meeting inside Pittston headquarters got underway,
the chants of hundreds of striking coalminers from Virginia and
West Virginia could be heard.
   United Mine Workers members at Pittston mines in Virginia, West
Virginia and Kentucky have been without a contract since Feb. 1,
1988. About 1,700 miners in Virginia and West Virginia struck April
5 over what they called labor practices.
   Since the strike began, about 1,300 coalminers and their spouses
have been arrested, including about 140 on felony charges from
rock-throwing and assault.
   The union has placed three proposals on the company's proxy
ballot that challenge the way the Greenwich-based company is
operated.
   One proposal asks that shareholders be allowed to vote on the
company's anti-takeover measures and another seeks to have
shareholders vote by secret ballot. The third measure would force
the establishment of a committee that would study whether Pittston
should sell any subsidiaries.
   The proposals are part of the union's so-called ``corporate
campaign.'' The company said it considers the strategy to be
harassment.
   Kenneth Zinn, union director of special projects, said the
company's anti-takeover measures adversely affect the company's
stock value and make it unattractive to potential suitors.
   The so-called ``poison pill'' is unfair because it was
implemented by management without a vote by shareholders, Zinn said.
   ``We think shareholders should vote on whether they want to hand
over this important right to the board,'' he said. ``We believe it
may have a negative affect on share price.''
   Paul Douglas, Pittston's chairman and chief executive officer,
disputed the union claim, saying the poison-pill measures ``are not
entrenchment devices'' intended to keep management in place.
   ``I think there are some honest differences of opinions about
it,'' he said.
   The Pittston Co. took out a full page advertisement in the local
newspaper today accusing the union of ``using violence to bully the
companies it targets into submission.''
   The advertisement accused the UMW and its leaders of selfishly
encouraging striking miners to commit serious crimes. The ad said
that striking miners have seriously hurt innocent people and that
striking miners have also been hurt in picket line violence.
   Both sides met with a federal mediator for the first time Monday
in New York. No details of the talks have been made public.
   Pittston earned $48.6 million in 1988, including $36.4 mllion
from coal operations. The company lost $116 million on coal
operations in 1987, primarily due to the devaluation of mining
properties.
   Besides coal mining, Pittston is the parent company of
Burlington Air Express Inc., Brink's Inc. and Brink's Home Security
Inc.
</TEXT>
