<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Ukrop Adv14   05-10 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Ukrop, Adv 14,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, May 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ukrop Brothers Beat Big Grocery Rivals With Family Values, Personal
Touch</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How does a local supermarket chain that
closes on Sundays and doesn't sell beer beat a national chain and
make it to the top of the grocery store heap?
   The personal touch, says James E. Ukrop.
   That's why Ukrop, 52-year-old president of Ukrop's Super Markets
Inc., is carrying a letter in his briefcase from a woman upset that
her coffee brand is sold in smaller cans.
   The letter, in which the woman threatens to stop shopping at the
store, is covered with notes from Ukrop's conversation with the
district manager about why the store can't satisfy her. Ukrop says
he'll respond personally to the complaint.
   ``It was addressed to me,'' he said in an interview. ``I'll
answer it. I hope she comes back.''
   Getting a personal reply from the president of Ukrop's wouldn't
surprise most regular customers of the Richmond stores, where
clerks are friendly, baggers insist on carrying shoppers'
groceries, and a framed statement declares that the stores' mission
is ``to serve our customers and community more effectively than
anyone else by treating our customers, associates and suppliers as
we personally would like to be treated.''
   Despite not selling beer, wine or liquor, staying closed on
Sundays, and steering clear of promotions like double coupons, the
family-owned chain has beaten out national leaders such as Safeway
to take the biggest bite of the Richmond market.
   Ukrop's had sales of $273.5 million or about 30 percent of the
metropolitan region's grocery sales in 1987-88, according to the
industry publication Food World.
   The stores have a national reputation for excellence, said Bill
Bishop, a food retailing analyst with Willard Bishop Consulting in
Barrington, Ill.
   ``The people that know them know them as a company that runs
superb food stores,'' Bishop said. ``I think that far and away the
most important thing that Ukrop's does is to put their customer
number one. A lot of people say that, but it's not done all that
frequently, and they do that.''
   With 19 stores and two more on the way, Ukrop's is still growing
_ but not too much. Safeway has 18 stores in areas where both
chains compete.
   Ukrop's will continue growing with Richmond, Ukrop sad, and is
expanding in new directions, such as its own central bakery and
central kitchen for prepared take-home foods that are set to open
soon.
   But Ukrop doesn't want to expand the stores beyond the Richmond
area, where he can keep a close eye on them. The farthest store is
in Petersburg, about 30 miles away, and Ukrop said he frequently
rejects requests to open stores elsewhere.
   ``We have an advantage in being local,'' he said. ``We live
here, we have friends here. We talk to our neighbors, hear what
they like and don't like. We're able to put our arms around our
business. We can do a lot of things that companies with branches
can't do.''
   Things like bringing employees, known as associates, together at
``values meetings'' with Ukrop or his younger brother, vice
president Robert S. Ukrop, to talk about what customers expect.
Workers, even part-timers, are encouraged to memorize a list of the
store's ``corporate values'' and recite them publicly, which gets
them their name on the values honor roll and a Ukrop's lapel pin.
   People always ask where he finds such good employees, Ukrop
said, and the answer is the company takes the dollars it doesn't
spend on promotions such as double coupons and games and invests
them in its workers.
   Running the business is ``a contact sport'' between management
and employees, said Robert Ukrop, a past co-captain of the
University of Richmond basketball team. Eleven years younger than
his brother, he speaks in quick bursts of enthusiasm, sprinkling
the conversation with expressions like ``It's fun.''
   Their father, Joe Ukrop, founded the family's first grocery
store in 1937. The brothers grew up next to the store, and neither
of them has ever considered a different career.
   There's never been a conflict between family values and running
the company, they said.
   ``Growing up, we went to Sunday school, we knew what the golden
rule was,'' James Ukrop said. ``We never heard it related to
business, but we both saw it.
   ``We've never had to make a decision that wasn't consistent with
our values,'' he said. ``We're very fortunate _ if we felt we
couldn't operate our business that way, we can sell it. I
personally would opt out.''
   Not selling alcohol goes along with the brothers' Baptist
values, and they say they've never considered doing otherwise.
   ``It's a non-issue,'' Bobby Ukrop said. The store stays closed
on Sundays, he said, because ``if you want to be the best place to
shop, you have to be the best place to work.''
   ``We lose some business and gain some business,'' because of
those policies, James Ukrop said. ``Our friends around the country
don't think we're very bright.''
   Ukrop's also gives 10 percent of its pretax profits to charity,
and for the last two years has donated more than $1 million to
non-profit groups that get 2 percent of the sales receipts they
collect.
   Giving to charity is ``just the way we think it ought to be,''
Robert Ukrop said.
   ``You can't separate what's family and what's business.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 14.</NOTE>
