<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mostly higher on slim volume,
with the market focused on the Treasury auction and on economic
reports due out later this week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 8.07 points to
2,379.40 at 2 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was off 1.65 at
noon New York time.
   Advancing issues barely edged out decliners on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 675 issues up, 633 down and 574 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 104.30 million shares.
   Brokers said the market regained some of its early losses after
a slight recovery in the bond market.
   On Tuesday, stock and bond prices fell in response to the
Treasury's sale of three-year notes. Analysts said investors were
concerned that U.S. and foreign investors bought fewer of the notes
than expected.
   The market was expecting more of the same today, but initial
results from today's sale showed a more favorable response.
   ``The rumor is that the 10-year treasury note auction is doing
fairly well,'' said Philip Puccio, senior vice president with
Dillon, Read &amp; Co. ``The bond market hasn't sold off to any great
degree, so it seems the auction is taking hold.''
   The final day of the sale is Thursday, when the government will
auction 30-year bonds.
   Traders said the market also continued a cautious posture ahead
of retail sales and producer price reports due out Thursday and
Friday. The concern is that data suggesting strong economic growth
and higher inflation could drive up interest rates.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.53 to 171.33.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
1.23 to 343.86.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Pan Am was down [ to
4~, Northwest Airlines was off } to 103{ and UAL Corp. had lost {
to 121{.
