<FIRST>u f PM-SEC-Lynch 1stLd-Writethru   05-10 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Lynch, 1st Ld-Writethru,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enforcement Chief To Step Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with background, Lynch interview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said
today that enforcement director Gary Lynch, who led the agency's
crackdown on insider trading on Wall Street, would leave the
commission staff in mid-July.
   Lynch, as the agency's top enforcement officer since 1985, was
the prime mover behind the commission's biggest cases in recent
years, including the settlements with stock speculator Ivan Boesky
and Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Lynch had joined the commission as a staff attorney in 1976, a
year after graduating from Duke University Law School. Lynch, in an
interview, said he had no specific plans after leaving the SEC.
   ``I've been director for over four years. It just got to the
point where it seemed like it was the appropriate time to move on
to something new,'' he said.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder, in a statement, said, ``During
Gary's tenure ... the commission has undertaken major programs to
combat securities fraud. ... The culmination of Gary's very
successful career ... is, of course, the historic settlement ...
between Drexel Burnham Lambert and the commission.''
   That settlement of civil charges, announced last month, capped a
two-year investigation that began when Boesky implicated the
nation's fifth-largest securities firm. He settled insider trading
charges with the SEC in 1986.
   The Drexel civil settlement helped pave the way for Drexel to
settle a criminal complaint and pay a record $650 million in fines
and restitution.
   The insider trading scandal uncovered during Lynch's tenure
forced venerable brokerage houses to re-evaluate their compliance
and ethics codes and led Congress to increase the penalties for
insider trading.
   ``I think we went an awful long way to cleaning up some serious
problems that existed,'' Lynch said. `` ... There's more concern
now about the possibility of being the subject of an SEC
enforcement action. In addition, probably more importantly, as a
result of the abuses that were exposed, brokerage firms have become
more alert to possible problems within their own organizations that
can lead to near disaster and ruin.''
   Lynch is credited with personally piercing the veil of secrecy
surrounding the Bahamas branch of a Swiss bank, where convicted
inside trader Dennis Levine maintained an account. It was Levine
whose cooperation with the SEC led to Boesky, who in turn
implicated Drexel in the largest securities fraud case ever brought
by the government.
   Lynch took over the SEC's top cop job at a time of turmoil for
the agency and is credited with restoring morale. His predecessor,
John Fedders, departed amid charges he had beaten his wife. Now 38
years old, Lynch was the youngest enforcement director in the
agency's history.
   As a government employee, Lynch earned an annual salary of about
$72,000, far less than he could earn in private practice. However,
he said neither the salary nor the long hours he worked played a
major role in his decision to leave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
