<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-10 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Dip On Reported Argentine Sales To Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately lower
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors that the Soviet
Union had purchased as much as 500,000 metric tons of soybean meal
from Argentina.
   Wheat futures advanced slightly while corn prices were mixed.
   The Soviet Union had been widely expected to make a major
purchase of U.S. soybean meal. The talk that they had bought from
Argentina instead prompted selling of futures contracts.
   There was no official confirmation of the rumors, which
apparently originated with oilseed traders in Buenos Aires.
   But a Soviet purchase of Argentine soybean meal ``shouldn't be a
major surprise,'' said New York-based grain specialist Ted Mao of
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., since both Argentina and Brazil are
flush with newly harvested soybeans.
   The wheat market see-sawed in a narrow range as traders
positioned themselves for Thursday's Agriculture Department
winter-wheat crop estimate.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower to 2 cents higher with May at $2.79{ a bushel; oats were 2{
cents lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $1.86 a bushel; soybeans
were 2 cents to 8\ cents lower with May at $7.58 a bushel.
