<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-KmartPlanners Adv14   05-10 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-K mart Planners, Adv 14,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Before Neighborhood Blooms, K mart May Be There</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10 years ago, suburban White Lake was
considered too thinly settled for a new K mart.
   Now, the prospect of future growth has prompted the nation's
second-largest retailer to open a store in the area, surrounded by
meadows that developers plan to cover with homes.
   ``This store will definitely be a store of the future with the
growth that's coming in here,'' said manager Gary Cook. ``We've got
a big development coming in behind here with townhouses and
apartments.''
   The promise of developing neighborhoods like White Lake _ plus
competitive pressure on from No. 1 Sears Roebuck &amp; Co. and No. 3
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. _ keeps K mart Corp. scrambling to scout new
sites and re-scout old ones as it attempts to place stores in every
untapped market.
   There aren't many surprises in the search; K mart says it
already is in nearly every county of the United States.
   But the store chain keeps a squad of real estate experts, store
designers and demographers busy looking for ways to squeeze ahead,
including placing stores in suburban fringes where homes are still
going up.
   K mart has more than 2,200 stores in 48 states and Puerto Rico.
It plans to open 70 more this year.
   A standard K mart takes up 86,000 square feet, while a
free-standing store generally requires eight acres, to provide for
the building and parking lot.
   In contrast, Chicago-based Sears' large stores, with displays of
space-filling furniture and appliance lines, typically take up
150,000 square feet, with some using more than 200,000 square feet.
   K mart's construction and real estate manager Mike Skiles has
property experts scouting several hundred potential locations at
any given time from K mart's five regional offices as well as its
Troy headquarters, he said.
   Leads come from their efforts and from shopping center
developers who want a K mart store to anchor a new mall. Final
decisions follow demographic studies and site visits, Skiles said.
   ``Other retailers, the state of the economy in that particular
area, the amount of housing growth that's occurring and the quality
of the particular piece of real estate would all be factors,''
Skiles said.
   Although K mart's major target is the 25- to 45-year-old
middle-income consumer, the demographic profile of the K mart
shopper is much broader.
   For example:
   _Forty-two percent are high school graduates, 23 percent didn't
finish high school, 19 percent have some college, 16 percent are
college graduates.
   _Forty-five percent are aged 25-44, 26 percent are 45-64, 16
percent are 18-24, 13 percent are older than 65.
   _Forty-three percent live in households of three or four, 30
percent in two-member households, 18 percent live in households of
five or more, 9 percent live alone.
   _Thirty-nine percent have household incomes of $25,000-$49,999,
25 percent have less than $15,000, 22 percent have $15,000-$24,999,
13 percent earn more than $50,000.
   ``We're everywhere, so the demographics of our shopper are more
or less like the demographics of the country as a whole,'' said Ron
Gellish, manager of an operations and research department that
employs two full-time demographers.
   Some new K marts represent ``back filling'' in areas where sites
couldn't be found before, Skiles said, such as a store that opened
last year in Detroit's long-established Oak Park neighborhood.
   K mart had looked at the area over the years but never was able
to find a suitable building, or a new site with enough space to
meet its needs, Skiles said.
   However, a mall developer now wants a K mart to anchor his Oak
Park project and the plan fits K mart's needs as well.
   Most new K marts are in growing areas like White Lake, where the
expanding Pontiac, White Lake, Union Lake and Highland communities
are beginning to converge about 35 miles northwest of Detroit.
   The new White Lake store stands amid grassy fields, although
builders' signboards tout development on the way.
   ``We're opening to service the new housing out there,'' Skiles
said.
   The 86,000-square-foot store also is in sight of the slopes and
lifts of Alpine Ski Valley. In a departure from traditional
discount decor, beams in the facade around the store entrance
suggest a chalet motif.
   That kind of planning is K mart's best hope for a competitive
edge, rather than any dramatic attempt to surprise Sears or
Wal-Mart, Gellish said.
   ``We know where their stores are. They know where ours are. Our
moves are pretty well publicized in the trade journals,'' he said.
``There's no secrets. We just have to operate as efficiently as
possible.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for Sunday, May 14</NOTE>
