<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-10 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market was mixed in moderate
trading Wednesday, with home heating oil rising in price but crude
oil and gasoline declining.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
24 cents lower at $19.52 a barrel. The contract had risen 32 cents
Tuesday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for June delivery declined 0.80 cent to
64.72 cents a gallon, after rising 0.54 cent Tuesday.
   June heating oil, which rose 0.30 cent Tuesday, settled at 47.48
cents a gallon, up another 0.49 cent.
   Peter Beutel, an energy analyst at Elders Futures Inc.,
attributed Wednesday's trading largely to internal forces of supply
and demand.
   However, he said the market was somewhat affected by the latest
weekly American Petroleum Institute report, which showed an
increase in U.S. crude and gasoline supplies and a drop in supplies
of heating oil.
   Traders also remain concerned that members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries may be raising daily production
above the current quota of 18.5 million barrels, Beutel said.
   The oil cartel is scheduled to meet next month in Vienna,
Austria to review its production and pricing policies.
</TEXT>
