<DOCNO> AP890510-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OPECSecretary     05-10 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC Secretary,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Head Meets With Texas Oil Producers, Energy Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC Secretary General Subroto said Wednesday that
world demand for petroleum was strong and could support a higher
benchmark price by the cartel.
   Subroto met Wednesday with Texas oil officials, who he indicated
had expressed support for the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries' attempts to stabilize world oil prices.
   The 13-nation cartel agreed last November to limit its
production to levels that would support a benchmark price of $18 a
barrel, about 18.5 million barrels a day. The action has helped
crude prices recover from their October 1988 lows of near $12 a
barrel.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
24 cents lower Wednesday at $19.52 a barrel.
   OPEC was to review its production at a meeting scheduled to
begin June 5 in Vienna, Austria. There has been speculation that
the cartel would increase its self-imposed production limits if
demand was strong enough to support higher output without
depressing prices.
   Subroto said OPEC nations have been striving for stability at
$18 per barrel, but he realized petroleum demand worldwide was
strong and could support a higher price.
   ``We are all along for cooperation between the major players in
the oil industry, including producers and also consumers, because
we think only by working together and not antagonizing...we can
bring the stability in the markets that we believe we can,'' said
Subroto.
   Subroto had a 1{-hour breakfast meeting with Texas Railroad
Commissioner Kent Hance, about 10 independent oil producers and
others at a downtown hotel. Subroto agreed with Hance that the
meeting had gone well.
   ``He has been instrumental in involving me in the thinking of
the oil industry in the United States, particularly in Texas and so
on,'' Subroto said. ``And we are very grateful for him to give an
indication of the support of the efforts that OPEC has given to
achieve stability in the market.
   Hance said state energy consumers and officials appreciated the
opportunity to meet with Subroto.
   ``One of the important things is that we have to have a dialogue
with OPEC because they are the major player. They are so important
not only to producers but to consumers in the United States,'' said
Hance.
   Subroto was scheduled to address a Thursday luncheon sponsored
by Southern Methodist University's Institute for the Study of Earth
and Man in his only planned U.S. talk this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
