<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-10 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines in Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued a minor retreat Wednesday,
digesting the gains that took it to nine-month highs at the start
of the week. Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign-exchange dealers said the dollar's decline came without
any push from central banks and appeared to be a reaction to the
rapid run-up that peaked on Monday.
   ``Fresh buying of dollars never really materialized,'' said Marc
Cohen, a vice president at Republic National Bank of New York.
   In London late Wednesday, one British pound cost $1.6717, more
expensive for buyers than $1.6605 on Tuesday. The pound also rose
against the dollar in New York, to $1.6740 from $1.6665 on Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 134.44 Japanese yen, down from
135.00 yen. In London late Wednesday the dollar traded fractionally
higher at 134.45 yen. In New York the dollar fell to 134.41 yen
from 134.53 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Tuesday's late
rates included: 1.9020 West German marks, down from 1.9094; 1.6921
Swiss francs, down from 1.6955; 1.1843 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1870; 6.4220 French francs, down from 6.4455; and 1,385.25
Italian lire, down from 1,391.50.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Tuesday's late rates: 1.9047 West German marks, down from 1.9158;
1.6925 Swiss francs, down from 1.7035; 6.4645 French francs,
unchanged; 2.1500 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1610; 1,390.125
Italian lire, down from 1,397.125; 1.1849 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1869.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was bid at
$376.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $378 an ounce late
Tuesday. Earlier gold bullion for current delivery fell to $377.70
an ounce on the Commodity Exchange in New York, down from $378.80.
   Gold traded late in London, the major market, at a bid price of
$377.25 a troy ounce, up from $376.50. The late bid price in
Zurich, Switzerland, was $376.75, up from $376.40.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $378.25, up from $376.15.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.68 a troy ounce, up
from $5.63. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $5.607 a troy ounce, down from $5.667.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890510-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-10 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose in lackluster trading
Wednesday, with the Dow Jones industrial average rebounding from an
eight-day losing streak.
   Traders said the market drifted in a fairly narrow range for
most of the session with little except the Treasury's $28.75
billion refunding to give the market direction.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.12 points to
finish at 2,374.45, ending an eight-day string of losses, the
longest since August 1982. The blue-chip indicator had lost 47.66
points since April 28.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by about 9 to 8 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
722 issues up, 641 down and 594 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board totaled 146 million shares,
down from 150.09 million in the previous session.
   Market strategists said large investors remained reluctant to
make commitments before the government provides new information on
inflation and before the final outcome of the Treasury auction.
   Traders are worried that the reports this week will show strong
economic growth and higher inflation that will drive up interest
rates.
   Figures on retail sales are due Thursday followed by producer
prices Friday.
   ``People want to keep the economy from overheating. But we keep
getting mixed signals,'' said Thomas Walsh, head of equity trading
for Nikko Securities Intl. ``Until the interest rate picture gets
clearer and we get a stable dollar the market will be fickle and
boring.''
   A slight recovery in bond prices after the second round of the
Treasury's quarterly borrowing failed to bring new players into the
market.
   On the first day of the sale Tuesday, stock and bond prices fell
in response to what strategists called a disappointing response to
the Treasury's sale of new debt. There was fear the Treasury would
have to raise the interest offered on its fresh issues of notes to
attract more buyers.
   A more favorable response by foreign investors after Wednesday's
sale of 10-year notes produced only a brief upward blip in the bond
market.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 174.47 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose $5.81 billion, or 0.19
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.33 to 171.13.
   Among actively traded issues, Avon surged 3~ to 39~ after Amway
offered $39 a share for the company. Newmont Mining gained 1 to 40\
on expectations that a buyer would emerge for the company.
   On the downside, Pan Am remained unchanged at 5 and Northwest
Airlines fell 1 to 103\ after Tuesday's announcement that Pan Am is
considering buying Northwest. AT&amp;T lost \ to 33| and IBM dropped [
to 109|.
