<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Belly Futures Extend Sharp Gain In Speculative Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of frozen pork belly futures soared the permitted daily
limit of 2 cents a pound for the second straight day Wednesday as
more speculators hopped aboard the market's rally from its lowest
level in nine years.
   Other livestock and meat futures finished the day mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   On other markets, energy futures were widely mixed; precious
metals were lower; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Frozen pork bellies settled 1.53 cents to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at 35.80.
   The pork-belly market has gained more than 17 percent since last
Thursday, when the May contract fell to 30.47 cents a pound, the
lowest price for a near-month contract since mid-1980.
   Prices for hogs and pork bellies, which are sliced to make
bacon, typically rise in May as hog marketings decline due to a
variety of seasonal factors.
   But this year's upturn in pork-belly prices is more pronounced
than usual because the market has been severely depressed for
nearly a year.
   Frozen pork bellies averaged about 65 cents a pound from
mid-1981 to mid-1988. But prices began falling sharply in the
spring of 1988 when it became apparent that production was far
outpacing bacon consumption.
   The Agriculture Department reported last month that as of April
1, U.S. cold storage warehouses contained 133.8 million pounds of
frozen pork bellies, the second-largest April 1 tally on record.
   Chuck Levitt, senior livestock market analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago, said the aggressive stockpiling
continued through April and he estimated that 150 million pounds of
frozen bellies were on hand as of May 1.
   ``We haven't had that many bellies in storage in any month for
at least 25 years,'' Levitt said. ``We are not going to run out of
pork bellies.''
   So despite expectations for a seasonal drop in hog slaughters,
the supply-and-demand factors for pork bellies are predominantly
bearish.
   Analysts attributed this week's strong rally to technical
factors, which basically means chart interpreters decided it was
time for prices to rise.
   ``Technically, the market got grossly oversold,'' Levitt said.
``Technically, it hasn't had a significant rally in God knows how
many months.''
   In other livestock and meat trading, live cattle settled .35
cent lower to .07 cent higher with June at 72.07 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .43 cent lower to .20 cent higher with May at
77.15 cents a pound; and live hogs were .20 cent lower to .22 cent
higher with June at 48.30 cents a pound.
   Near-month crude oil and unleaded gasoline futures tumbled while
heating oil futures rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange
following Tuesday's weekly American Petroleum Institute report
showing unexpected increases in U.S. supplies of crude and gasoline
and a drop in supplies of petroleum distillates.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 23 cents lower to 17
cents higher with June at $19.53 a barrel; heating oil was .28 cent
to .63 cent higher with June at 47.50 cents a pound; unleaded
gasoline was .97 cent lower to .01 cent higher with June at 64.55
cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange, giving up nearly all of Tuesday's gains.
   Gold settled $1.10 to $1.70 lower with June at $379 a troy
ounce; silver was 6 cents lower across the board with July at
$5.695 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures fell moderately on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid rumors that the Soviet Union had purchased up to 500,000
metric tons of soybean meal from Argentina. Wheat futures advanced
slightly while corn prices were mixed.
   Wheat settled { cent to 1{ cents higher with May at $4.26{ a
bushel; corn was } cent lower to 2 cents higher with May at $2.79{
a bushel; oats were 2{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with May at
$1.86 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 8 cents lower with May at
$7.58\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
