<FIRST>u f AM-BrothelBuyout     05-10 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brothel Buyout,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mustang Ranch Stock Sale Halted After Marketing Efforts Stall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wallstreet one word is cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An effort to make the Mustang Ranch the
nation's first publicly-owned bordello went on hold when a public
stock offering failed to sell the required number of shares by a
Wednesday deadline.
   Eric Walloga, whose American Wallstreet Securities Inc. is
underwriting the offering, said the firm had negotiated an
extension of the stock sale until Oct. 31 to allow time to
restructure the offer.
   Meanwhile, the sale of common stock in Mustang Ranch, Inc. has
been halted and all the money received for the shares so far will
be returned to investors, Walloga said in a statement released by
his office in Tampa, Fla.
   Walloga, president of American Wallstreet, was out of the office
Wednesday and unavailable for comment.
   Plans had called for a $23.3 million offering of stock in the
legal bordello at $20 a share. Walloga said last week about 75
percent of the 1.165 million shares had been sold during the
three-month offering, leaving the company some $5 million short of
its goal.
   A statement said an amendment would be filed with the Securities
and Exchange Commission and the states that have approved sale of
the stock to reflect the terms of the new deal, which it said would
change the types of securities Mustang Ranch Inc. would offer.
   The statement said details of the restructured offering would
not be released pending an SEC response to a request for a ruling
on a technical issue over the amended offering.
   Peter Perry, a Reno attorney and vice president of Mustang Ranch
Inc., said in the statement that he expected the amended
registration to be filed with the SEC by June 15. Perry would not
comment specifically on the offer. them.
   Mustang Ranch Inc. is an investors' group composed primarily of
Reno businessmen and attorneys who are making a second attempt to
turn the brothel public.
   A 1985 bid by a group by John Davis of Irvine, Calif. fell
through after failing to generate enough interest in the $18
million proposal.
   The money raised in the current sale was to have provided $13
million to buy the 102-room brothel 10 miles east of Reno and its
440 acres of land from Joe and Sally Conforte, $5 million in
exchange for the Confortes' promise not to set up a competing
brothel and $5.3 million for expansion, improvements and working
capital.
   Conforte has been trying to sell the brothel since 1985 when he
was released from prison after serving 18 months on a tax
conviction.
</TEXT>
