<FIRST>r f AM-SteelImportQuotas     05-10 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Import Quotas,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soon-To-Expire Steel Import Quotas Have Raised Prices, ITC Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel import quotas have hurt American exports
by raising steel prices, the U.S. International Trade Commission
said Wednesday as the Bush administration weighed the fate of the
soon-to-expire protectionist program.
   The ITC's 96-page report is certain to enliven the debate over
whether to continue steel import quota agreements with 19 nations
and the European Community.
   The Reagan administration negotiated five-year,
product-by-product voluntary restraint agreements, or ``VRAs,'' in
1984 with Japan, South Korea, Brazil, South Africa and other
nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the United States.
   President Bush has pledged to continue the restraints in some
form beyond their Sept. 30 expiration But with the steel industry
newly profitable, opponents of the curbs believe they can make a
case for ending the program, or at least narrowing its scope.
   The ITC said the curbs caused steel prices in the United States
to rise by as much as 0.6 percent in 1985, 1.6 percent in 1986, 1.4
percent in 1987 and 0.2 percent in 1988. It said the weakening of
the dollar overseas and other factors also contributed
significantly to further price hikes.
   As a result of the VRA-induced price increases, the commission
estimated that American exports in steel-consuming industries
decreased by $258 million in 1985, $673 million in 1986, $699
million in 1987 and $95 million in 1988.
   ``The recent increases in steel prices have been distributed
unevenly among categories of customers,'' said the study, which was
conducted at the request of the House Ways and Means subcommittee
on trade.
   ``Price increases were not as great for large steel purchasers
as for small ones, apparently because the larger purchasers buy a
great deal of their steel through long-term contracts with prices
set for the duration of the contract, and smaller purchasers
generally buy steel in spot transactions,'' the ITC said.
   The question of whether the restraints have caused steel price
increases has divided American manufacturers into rival camps.
   Last month, a coalition of 374 manufacturers headed by Chrysler
Corp., Maytag Corp. and others was formed to lobby on behalf of
continuing the quota agreements on grounds that the curbs have
helped make the steel industry healthier.
   The coalition contends that steel price increases have been
caused by strong worldwide demand and shifting exchange rates.
   But a rival group, led in part by Caterpillar Inc., asserts that
had quotas not been in effect, steel prices would have risen only
modestly.
   The ITC cautioned that the figures reflected an ``upward bias''
because of the procedures it used. That means that the effect of
the import restraints on prices might have been overstated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
