<FIRST>u f AM-InsiderTrading     05-10 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insider Trading,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Charges 2 Lawyers with Insider Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partner in a Buffalo, N.Y., law firm and his
brother-in-law agreed to settle civil Securities and Exchange
Commission charges Wednesday that he traded on inside information
about a client corporation.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Henry M. Porter, agreed to
return more than $78,000 in alleged illegal trading profits and pay
an equal amount in civil penalties.
   Porter's brother-in-law, William Wolski, 40, of Marietta, Ga.,
also settled civil insider trading charges with the SEC and agreed
to return more than $37,000 in alleged illegal profits plus an
equal amount in penalties.
   The settlement remains subject to a judge's approval.
   According to court papers, Porter, 51, of Buffalo, has been a
partner since 1975 in the law firm of Lippes, Kaminsky,
Silverstein, Porter, Matthias &amp; Wexler, which was general counsel
to Amherst, N.Y.-headquartered Mark IV Industries Inc.
   The SEC charged in its civil complaint that Porter, traded in
the common stock of LFE Corp. and tipped Wolski in 1985, after
allegedly stealing confidential information from his law firm that
the Clinton, Mass.-based corporation was a possible takeover target
by Mark IV.
   The complaint also charged that in 1986 Porter tipped Wolski
about Mark IV's then-impending tender offer for Gulton Industries
Inc. and that Wolski, who was living in Stamford, Conn., at the
time, traded on Gulton securities.
</TEXT>
